 <html>
<header>
<title>Refugees, displaced persons and development cooperation</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H2><center><img src="../images/nar.jpg"><p></a>
Refugees, displaced persons and development cooperation</h2>
<h4><i>NAR Secretariat</i>
<p>
Source: <i>In Brief: Information from the NAR</i><br>No. 6, October 1993</h4>
<h5>The full text of the report in English, as well as a list of other publications, are available free of
charge from the Council's secretariat: E-mail: nar-dgis@dgis.minbuza.nl</h5>
</center>
<hr>
<b>The 102nd report of the National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) on the
relationship between development cooperation and the refugee problem was presented to Mr J P Pronk,
Minister for Development Cooperation, at the beginning of October 1993.</b>
<p>
<h3>Summary of the problems and questions considered in the report</h3>

How can development cooperation help to prevent large-scale flows of refugees and combat and/or help to
forestall their negative consequences? How can host countries - developing countries in particular - be
assisted in dealing with an influx of refugees and displaced persons? These were the questions posed by the
Minister in his request for recommendations on the refugee issue. Another was how can support be given to
sustainable solutions to the refugee problem other than asylum in the region? It is a fact that more people
than ever before are now fleeing. Current estimates indicate that twenty million people have left their home-
land, while a similar number have been driven out of their homes, albeit not out of their country of origin.
The great majority of them are women and children fleeing from one developing country to another. Many
of them wait to return, sometimes for decades, in desolate camps. The report is principally concerned with
aid to such people, and definitely not with migrants coming to Europe in search of work. It does, however,
discuss the changes that the definition of a refugee has undergone in the last ten or twenty years. The
Council would associate itself with the policies developed by the UNHCR, the UN refugee agency.
<p>
However, we have to be very cautious concerning the potential contribution of development cooperation to
resolving the refugee problem. After all, the question of the extent to which economic underdevelopment is
responsible for creating refugee flows is well-nigh impossible to answer. The connection between economic
inequality and violent social upheaval is a highly complex one. Nevertheless, development cooperation is
increasingly called upon to serve as a preventive instrument, and speculation is voiced about reducing the
numbers of asylum seekers by "developing" poor regions. Leaving aside the incentive to poor government
which would result from such a policy, it is a formula that takes no account whatever of the capriciousness
and unpredictability of the refugee problem. The Council wold argue that economic underdevelopment as
such is not a major cause of refugee flows.
<p>
The question even arises of whether conflicts are inherent in the development process itself, since
development implies social change and the emergence of a new situation affecting relations between groups
and the relationship between people and their environment. Such a process rarely proceeds smoothly. Some
critics say that the current economic crisis, with all the violence it entails (such as increasing domestic and
international crime rates, conflicts involving the use of force, civil wars, drug trafficking and damage to the
environment) is the product of the dominant Western-style development model.
<p>
On the other hand, development cooperation can be seen as a potential way of preventing the conflicts which
give rise to refugee flows. Improved living standards might forestall conflicts caused by scarcity, ecological
degradation or economic inequality. However, as stated above, the causes of refugee flows are legion: the
formation of states and nations, decolonisation, sometimes linked with economic factors, problems of
institutional development, and not least environmental degradation. Violations of human rights, life-
threatening violence and national or ecological disasters drive vast numbers of people to abandon the scene
of their misfortune. Alongside the wider reality of persecution in general can be found the more personal,
individual motive of fear. All this is closely related to changes in the identity of the population of developing
countries, changes brought about to some extent by education and development, resulting in a new sense of
individuality. Such values as autonomy, personal liberty, responsibility, mutual respect and, above all,
guarantees of physical integrity thus acquire a new meaning, particularly for young people, as a result of
which violence in society is more frequently regarded as unjust and unacceptable. This may lead to political
radicalisation and hence the need to flee. At the same time, however, the numbers participating in what are
increasingly rigid political processes are declining all the time and collective action is hardly an option. In
that case there is nothing for politically aware young people in the South to do but leave. Their main
motives for doing so are - in that event - by no means economic. In general they would have stayed if they
could have been guaranteed freedom from violence or from the caprices of an unpredictable tyranny. 
<p>
<h3>Conclusions and recommendations</h3>

The Council therefore believes that development policy should be based to a greater extent on concepts of
social, economic and cultural diversity as the foundation of self-elected development from the bottom up. In
the long term a policy of this kind can have a preventive, or at least moderating, effect on polarisation and
violent outbursts of idiosyncratic fundamentalism. Moreover, as stated in NAR report no. 100, many
developing countries are the victims of skewed growth, with the result that the structure of society has
become one-sided, being dominated by economic institutions or an overgrown state apparatus. Skewed
growth of this kind often leads to social tensions, which sometimes spill over into violence, forming an
obstacle to efforts to achieve sustainable development.
<p>
In this connection the Council feels that fostering respect for human rights is vital. Measures such as early
warning systems, the physical presence of international organisations and the promotion of good governance
can have a direct preventive effect. The Council would recommend that support be given to human rights
organisations, more particularly if human rights violations are on the increase. This should be extended to
include working with other organisations which are sensitive to human rights issues, such as trade unions
and women's organisations. Early reporting of trends in the area of human rights violations is likewise
called for. Local embassies should report on law enforcement and the beginnings of trends such as
disappearances, incarceration and executions. Good reporting on human rights violations and incipient
refugee flows could also help to raise awareness of the problems, as could invitations to and assignments of
journalists and commissioning television documentaries from journalists in the relevant countries. As part of
enhanced conditionality,  all industrialised countries should declare themselves willing to accept international
monitoring of observance of human rights in their own region, in the same way as most of the states of
Europe have done by means of the European Convention on Human Rights.
<p>
The Council wishes to point out once again that 80% of the world's refugees are women and children. It
would be advisable for this to be stressed at both bilateral and multilateral level, and for policy to take
account of this fact.
<p>
The Council is very concerned to note that no more than 35% of total Dutch development aid expenditure in
1992 on refugee aid (including reception facilities for asylum seekers) went to refugees in developing
countries. This percentage is in danger of declining even further in the near future. The Council would urge
that a halt be called to this trend, adding that the provision of reception facilities for asylum seekers in the
Netherlands should no longer be paid for out of the development cooperation budget.
<p>
Asylum in the region certainly merits support. It must be remembered that what is referred to as the cultural
region for some refugees is situated in the West rather than in countries near their country of origin. Some
years ago, for example, it would have been improper for Bhutto supporters from Pakistan who sought refuge
in London to have been sent back to a camp in the sub-continent. The Council recommends that a distinction
be drawn between the policy field relating to Dutch admission and reception problems and that relating to
assistance to refugees in developing countries. Moreover, given the different timescales involved, simply
linking policy on refugees and asylum seekers with development cooperation would be in the interests of
neither.
<p>
The Council believes that development cooperation should be involved in voluntary repatriation projects for
refugees. Both bilateral and multilateral efforts can be effective, particularly in relation to the reconstruction
of a country. The restoration of human rights - political, social and economic - should also be actively
promoted. If voluntary repatriation is to work in the long term, conditions in the home country must be such
that those who return are never again compelled to seek refuge elsewhere.
<p>
Development cooperation should give more consideration to social structures in a post-conflict situation.
This means doing more to reconcile warring factions. Links could be sought with an international policy on
organising peace through development which is gradually taking shape. The Council also believes that
consideration should be given to the problem of the millions of people who have been living in exile for
many years in refugee communities with political leadership structures and military wings which wage war
for political ends. Their existence not only creates problems as far as fund-raising is concerned but also
poses dilemmas in terms of international law, since refugee status is incompatible with armed political
activism.
<p>
Refugees and their own organisations in the West should be closely involved with both repatriation projects
and reconciliation processes. Their knowledge, experience and dedication as regards development projects in
their countries of origin would then be doubly effective. Such involvement would help to stem the brain
drain from developing countries, as highly-qualified persons could contribute to the reconstruction of their
countries while Western donors could take advantage of refugees' expertise.
<p>
The Council is of the opinion that support should be given to regional, integrated approaches, which
embrace political, economic and development-related aspects of the problems associated with refugees
and/or those returning home. Such an approach requires coordination, particularly between (and within) the
UN and the EC and the various international aid organisations. The UNHCR is attempting to expand its
programmes and step up its activities. The Council believes that generous support should be given to the
UNHCR in this, as in its more traditional activities, namely increasing and improving emergency aid in
collaboration with other international organisations, donor governments and NGOs, increasing scope for
voluntary repatriation of refugees, for example by the introduction of quick impact development projects, the
resettlement of refugees whose lives or fundamental wellbeing would otherwise be threatened and measures
to improve the protection afforded refugees.
<p>
<HR>
<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle
SRC="../images/nar.jpg"> <i>Updated on January 22, 1996</i><p>
