<html>
<header>
<title>ODI Publications</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><img src="../images/odi_blue.gif"><p></a>
ODI Publications</h3>
<a href="http:../../odi/index.html" target="_top">Visit the ODI WWW Home Page</a>
<p>
</center><p>
<HR>


<p>
<a name="howdev"><hr><b>How Developing Countries Trade: The Institutional Constraints </b>.
<i>Sheila Page </i>. Over the last fifteen years there have been dramatic increases in both private and
public intervention in international trade. Traditional barriers to market- based trade such as
commodity cartels and tariffs have been augmented by new developments such as the rise of regional
trade blocs and the growth of intra-firm trade. This book argues that these changes are large and
persistent enough to have an impact on total development performance, and on the performance of
both individual countries and sectors. It illustrates this with a wealth of theoretical arguments,
empirical evidence and country studies.(1994, price = &#163; 15.99). Order from: <a href="mailto:publications@odi.org.uk">publications@odi.org.uk</a></a>
<p>
<a name="trawit"><hr><b>Trading with South Africa: The policy options for the EC</b>. <i>Sheila
Page and Christopher Stevens </i>. Provides wide ranging analysis of South African trade
post-sanctions, detailing its current exports, and examining what types of external support South Africa
needs, and how South Africa and its trading partners can encourage new products and markets. It also
identifies which existing suppliers to the EC could be affected. The report compiles and analyses data
on South African trade, commodity data for all major trading partners, tariff and non-tariff data, and
competitiveness indicators. (1992, price &#163; 20.00). Order from: <a href="mailto:publications@odi.org.uk">publications@odi.org.uk</a></a>
<p>
<a name="wortra"><hr><b>World Trade Reform: Do Developing Countries Gain or Lose?</b>.
<i>Sheila Page and Michael Davenport</i>. The Uruguay Round of trade negotiations reduced barriers
to trade in all economic sectors, with the largest changes in food and clothing. An unprecedented
number of activities and government policies related to trade will come under international regulation
for the first time, as the move from GATT to the World Trade Organization creates a new institution
with stronger powers as well as wider responsibilities. For the developing countries the effects of this
new international framework are increased because their special privileges are defined more precisely,
but also more narrowly. Estimates of the consequences have varied from massive gains to crippling
losses. This Special Report analyses the changes and where possible quantifies them. It sets out their
impact on a range of countries at different stages of development. Finally it considers how the new
trading system may need to evolve to meet its increasing responsibilities. (1994, price = &#163; 17.50). Order from: <a href="mailto:publications@odi.org.uk">publications@odi.org.uk</a></a>
<p>

<a name="eurpre"><hr><b>Europe's Preferred Partners? The Lom&#233; Countries in World Trade </b>.
<i>Michael Davenport, Adrian Hewitt and Antonique Koning</i>. Countries in Africa, the Caribbean
and the Pacific (ACP) have enjoyed preferential access to the European Market under the Lom&#233;
Convention for over twenty years. This report assesses the impact of their special treatment, examines
in detail their trade performance and investigates the difficulties that ACP exporters experience. The
Report also explores potential effects on ACP trade performance of changes in EU policy regarding
the Lom&#233; Convention and of trade liberalisation that resulted from the Uruguay Round. (1995, price 
&#163; 17.50). Order from: <a href="mailto:publications@odi.org.uk">publications@odi.org.uk</a></a>
<p>
<a name="crior"><hr><b>Crisis or Transition in Foreign Aid?</b> <i>edited by Adrian P Hewitt </i>.
Has the end of the Cold War caused a crisis in official aid, already  beset by budgetary cuts,
challenges on effectiveness and so called 'donor fatigue'? Or is the  problem specific to a few donors,
while others move ahead with more constructive policies,  stronger and broader-based public support,
and larger programmes? This Special Report assesses  the current position in ten of the leading donor
countries (UK, USA, Canada, Japan, France,  Germany, Netherlands, Norway, Sweden and Denmark)
and looks to the future role of foreign  aid. (1994, price  &#163; 17.50). Order from: <a href="mailto:publications@odi.org.uk">publications@odi.org.uk</a></a>
<p>

<a name="foraid"><hr><b>Foreign Aid Reconsidered</b>. <i>Roger C Riddell</i>. Examines in depth
the moral and theoretical questions raised in the  aid debate and weighs up the different arguments in
the light of the range and quality of  current evidence.  '...the most thorough and authoritative analysis
of foreign aid that I have seen.  It is balanced and well argued and based on a broad range of relevant
sources. In the  literature on development, it is a landmark that no doubt will attract interest among
both academics  and professional aid administrators.' Goran Hyden author of No Shortcuts to Progress.
(1987, price  &#163; 14.95). Order from: <a href="mailto:publications@odi.org.uk">publications@odi.org.uk</a></a>
<p>
<a name="afrmul"><hr><b>Africa's Multilateral Debt A Modest Proposal</b>. <i>All Party Group
on Overseas Development</i>. Many African countries now see the lending policies of the World
Bank  and the IMF as an impediment to development rather than a help. What is the truth  behind this
perception? Should the international financial institutions now reverse their  policy of refusing to
reschedule or write off bad debts? Are our own governments bailing  out the IMF and the World Bank
with scarce bilateral aid to keep debts current and if so  should the donors be prepared to continue?
The Working Party has drawn up a framework of  recommendations after meeting representatives of
all points of view   banks, creditor  and debtor governments, as well as the international financial
institutions and independent  experts. (1994, price = &#163; 10.00). Order from: <a href="mailto:publications@odi.org.uk">publications@odi.org.uk</a></a>
<p>
<hr>
<b>Overseas Development Institute</b>, Portland House, Stag Place, London SD1E 5DP, United Kingdom<br>
Tel:  +44 171 393 1600 / Fax:  +44 171 393 1699<br>
E-mail:  <a href="mailto:publications@odi.org.uk">publications@odi.org.uk</a>

