<html><head><title>AFRICAN FOOTBALLERS TO LEAD HIV/AIDS AWARENESS CAMPAIGN</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><img src="unicef_pix/unicef_logo.gif"><hr><br><h2>AFRICAN FOOTBALLERS TO LEAD HIV/AIDS AWARENESS CAMPAIGN</h2><p><b>6th February 1996:</b><p>Africa's leading footballers have teamed-up with the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) in its HIV/AIDS prevention and care campaign across Africa.<p>The campaign 'African Footballers Unite Against AIDS' was officially launched in Johannesburg at the African Nations Cup.  Amongst the players who have agreed to participate in the campaign are:<p>George Weah (Liberia)Abedi Pele Ayew (Ghana)Tony Yeboah (Ghana)Nii Lamptey (Ghana)Kalusha Bwalya (Zambia)Neil Tovey (South Africa)Doctor Khumalo (South Africa)<p>along with John Fashanu, the former England, Wimbledon and Aston Villa star, who is now a UNICEF UK Special Representative.<p>Although not able to be present at the launch, the FIFA, European and African Footballer of the Year, George Weah has agreed to lead the campaign, stating that he would lend his support in any way that will further the work of UNICEF with the children of the world.<p>The campaign is one element of a broad relationship being developed between footballers and football associations, as part of UNICEF's partnership in the United Nations Joint Programme on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS), according to Mr Ian MacLeod, from UNICEF in South Africa.<p>'As the number one sport in Africa - indeed, across the globe - football has the unique capacity to be able to reach out to millions of young men and women, and improve their understanding of health issues, especially the threat of HIV/AIDS,' said Mr MacLeod.<p>'The top players in each country are listened to by young men and women - they have great influence over their behaviour. Hopefully, these young people can be better informed about how to protect themselves against HIV/AIDS,' he said.<p>The programme between football associations and UNICEF/UNAIDS kicked off at the African Cup of Nations.  During the period of the Cup, in countries across Africa, activities have been organised bringing together youth organisations to watch and listen to the games and then to discuss health and pro-social issues.  During the games, media in many African countries are broadcasting and printing special messages for youth on HIV/AIDS, including some from football stars', said Mr MacLeod.<p>'UNICEF has been very fortunate that CAF have been supporting our work, in allowing us to have signboards at the games, and allowing us to meet with players and officials to increase their understanding of this major health concern, and how we can work together to stem the advance of HIV/AIDS' he said.<p>Dr Rob Moodie, a Director of UNAIDS who is based in Geneva, and in South Africa for the development of the initiative, reinforced the importance of football now taking up the issue of HIV/AIDS as a priority.<p>'In many parts of Africa between 10% and 20% of 15-24 year olds are already infected with the virus that leads to AIDS, HIV.  Every day it is estimated that there are over 4000 new infections across the continent - of which at least half are in this age group,' stated Dr Moodie.<p>'The African Footballers Unite Against AIDS initiative will be a catalytic factor in ensuring that the present and future generations across this vast continent are able to make informed decisions to ensure their own healthy development, and that of their families and communities,' said Dr Moodie.<p>'People with HIV live productive and fulfilling lives and continue to work and play sports for many years.  Just look at the basketball star, Magic Johnson.  We all have a responsibility in this era to show solidarity and to be supportive of HIV-infected people, giving them love and care, not prejudice and rejection'.<p>'We know that HIV prevention does work and can reduce infection rates.  Together with these football stars, we are taking up the challenge and working in unity towards a safer, stronger, and more economically dynamic Africa,' he said.<p><b>Note to Editors:</b><br>John Fashanu is currently visiting AIDs projects in Tanzania and will be available for interview on his return to this country the week beginning February 13th. There will also be Beta footage and photos available of his trip, filmed by ITV in Tanzania on his return.<p>Please contact Stacey Adams UNICEF UK Press Office on 0171 430 0162 or Deborah Valentine UNICEF Pretoria South Africa 00 27 12 320 7066/7/8/9<p><hr>©Copyright: UNICEF 1995<hr><a href="index.html" target="_parent"><img src="unicef_pix/unicef_logo2.gif"> Unicef Home Page</a></body></html>
