<html><head><title>Planned Parenthood Challenges 1996/1</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><img align=left hspace=3 src="../ippf_pix/ippf_logo.gif"><h3>International<br>Planned<br>Parenthood<br>Federation</h3><i>The material that follows has been provided by <a href="../ippf_info.html">IPPF</a></i><br clear=left><hr><h1 align=center>&quot;Backers of the people" in China</h1><h3 align=center>by Li Yang and Jeremy Hamand</h3><img align=left border=1 hspace=10 vspace=10 width=175 height=147 src="p25.jpg"><br><b>The human rights aspect of China's family planning programmeis constantly under attack by Western media and politicians,as are IPPF and the United Nations for providing support tofamily planning in China at all. Yet IPPF's affiliate inChina, the China Family Planning Association, performs avaluable role in representing people in the family planningprogramme against coercion or abuses by local officials andgenerally safeguarding their legal rights and interests.</b><p><font size=2>Collecting people's views on the family planning programme in Gongzhuling, Jilin Province</font><p><hr width=71%><p>The China FPA is different from family planning associationsin other countries. Like other organizations in this vastcountry, it is a 'mass organization', which means that thereis not a single FPA, but literally hundreds of thousands ofFPAs - at provincial, municipality, prefecture, county,township and village level.<p>The organization relies heavily on the services of unpaidvolunteers - numbered in tens of millions - who mainly do notprovide contraceptive services (that is done by theGovernment) but work in their own communities giving advice onfamily planning, child care and related family matters.<p>One of their main aims is to reduce the incidence of abortiondue to contraceptive failure, by ensuring that couplesunderstand the proper use of contraceptives and bycampaigning, where necessary, for a wider choice of methods.Another is to educate families on the value of girl children.The FPAs also generate practical help for couples, throughorganizing income-generating activities to reduce poverty andinsurance schemes to provide financial security in old age.<p><h3>Democratic supervision</h3>A major responsibility is to provide what is called'democratic supervision' - a function that is supported by theGovernment and has been repeatedly stressed by the FamilyPlanning Minister, Mrs Peng Peiyun. The China FPA has, shesays, "the responsibility of safeguarding the legal rights ofthe people, reflecting the demands and the voice of thepeople, and supervising that the officials of the Governmentact according to the law."<p>The basic aim is to ensure that individuals are fully informedof their rights and responsibilities in the family planningprogramme, and that these rights are respected. The FPAsencourage people to stand up for themselves and participate incommunity planning and improvement. While exercising thisfunction, the FPAs at all levels play a significant role bychannelling the people's comments, criticism and opinions tothe Government. The FPAs urge the government authorities toface up to any problems the people have with the familyplanning programme, and they point out inconsistencies in theprogramme and inaccuracies in the demographic data used.<p>The FPAs also monitor abuses by individual officials and urgethe authorities to eliminate all forms of abuse. TheGovernment is very sensitive to foreign accusations of abuseand coercion, and has laid down strict guidelines for theconduct of family planning programmes. Through internalregulations, it promulgates <i>Three Principles and SevenForbidden Acts.</i><p><blockquote><b>According to the <i>Three Principles</i>, stress should be laid on:</b><p><ol><li>  information and education rather than economic     disincentives;<li>   contraception rather than abortion<li>  day-to-day family planning management rather than     irregular campaigns.</ol><p><b>Under the <i>Seven Forbidden Acts</i>, the following are unlawfulactions in family planning programmes:</b><p><ol><li>   putting people in custody, beating them or     assaulting them<li>   destroying their possessions<li>  removing their possessions unlawfully<li>  imposing arbitrary charges penalties<li>   imposing penalties on relatives<li>  interfering with legal childbearing<li>   conducting pregnancy checks on young unmarried women.</ol></blockquote><p>But in such a huge country, monitoring of such regulations isnot easy. And even if individuals know of the existence ofthese guidelines, they may well feel too vulnerable to reportabuses themselves. Hence the importance of the 'democraticsupervision' function of the FPAs.<p><h3>Quality and choice</h3>Another valuable aspect of FPA involvement is quality controlof family planning services: any cases which infringetechnical quality standards and jeopardize people's health andsafety are reported to the authorities. They also look out forinadequate choice in their local programme. In DalianMunicipality, in the North-east, the family planning programmerelied only on IUDs and sterilization until 1991. The localFPA convinced officials that a better choice of methods wouldlead to a higher acceptance rate by the population - and thisproved to be the case.<p>In Jilin Province, the FPAs at all levels in GongzhulingMunicipality have gained a reputation as 'backers of thepeople' for their work representing the people who participatein the family planning programme.<p>The main approaches by Gongzhuling FPAs to their supervisionof the family planning programmes include:<p> <li>Collecting and consolidating the FPA members'     perspectives and ideas from the members' General     Assembly, meetings of their Councils and from individual     members;<li>Carrying out special studies and submitting reports with     recommendations to the government authorities;<li>Participating in the planning and implementation of the     approved programmes modified according to FPA proposals.<p>An example of the cases that the FPAs take up and resolve wasa local government ruling on collecting fines from coupleswith unplanned births and making bonus payments to finecollectors in a rural township. The FPA challenged some of thestipulations as being likely to lead to coercive practices.They urged the authorities to emphasize persuasion andpublicity rather than fine collection, and consider thespecial difficulties of some individuals. The townshipgovernment accepted this recommendation and there was nofurther opposition to the ruling.<p><h3>Local ruling</h3>People's rights and privileges are also closely monitored. Inone township last year FPA members found that in some villagesthe one-child health care fee, an incentive payment made toone-child families, had not been paid, and they quickly hadthis remedied by the authorities.<p>Over the past two years, the FPAs at all levels in Gongzhulingtrained 52,410 FPA council members, staff and volunteers toimprove their capacity and performance in democraticparticipation and supervision.<p>In Fujian Province in South China the FPA of Minhou County hasmade an agreement with the local authorities to authorize over3,000 FPA members to be responsible for monitoring theperformance of the family planning programme.<p>Taking the advice of the FPA that information and educationshould be the priorities in the family planning programme, theGovernment mobilized all possible media, including newspapers,magazines, radio, television, exhibitions and posterpublicity, to carry more family planning information so as tohelp the people to make an informed and responsible choice inplanning their families.<p>Through its supervising members' network, the FPA has beensupervising the performance of the government personnel at alllevels, to eliminate any possible abuses. Special letter boxesare in place throughout the county where people can post theircomments confidentially, and the people's concerns areregularly consolidated and passed on to the relevantauthorities for follow-up action.<p>The FPA has also urged the authorities to ensure thatincentives are given in the form of preferential assistance tofamily planning acceptors. The county government has providedspecial maternal and child health services to over 50,000women of reproductive age and all their children up to the ageof eight, and allocated 3.5 million yuan (over $450,000) to set upspecial insurance schemes for one-daughter families, such aschild safety insurance and family planning pension insurance.<p>The FPA asked the authorities for policy support for incomegeneration projects (home processing, home farming, animalrearing and community services) for young couples planningtheir families. These income generation projects are helpingshift people's concept of childbearing from 'the importance ofhaving sons for support in old age' to 'being self-sufficientfor retirement'.<p>In some places it may happen, through official inertia orignorance of the regulations, that people do not receivebenefits due to them. FPA investigators in a county inLiaoning Province found that people were not receiving theeconomic incentives promised in local policies; they raisedthe matter with the local government which, as a result,ensured that all incentives were awarded and also introducedan old age insurance scheme for one-child families. Lack ofreliable life insurance for old age is a major reason for somerural families wanting more children.<p>Local officials sometimes draft regulations designed to servetheir own ends rather than further government policy. In apoor mountainous county in Shandong Province with an annualper capita income of US$30, the local government hadintroduced a draconian penalty system for couples who had toomany children. People complained to the FPA who suggested tothe local government that the emphasis should be changed fromcollecting fines to helping the people to generate income, andwithin two years the FPAs in the county started more than2,000 income-generating projects, using local reservoir waterresources for fishery and growing and processing fruit.<p>In these and many other ways, the China FPA is playing animportant role in enhancing democracy, improving choice andcombating poverty in the country's rapidly changing economicand social environment. <hr><p>©Copyright IPPF<br><font size=-1>Picture: &copy;China FPA </font><hr><img align=left src="../ippf_pix/ippf_logo2.gif"> <a href="index.html">PPC 1996/1 Contents</a><br><a href="../index.html">IPPF Home Page</a><hr></body></html>
