<html>
<header>
<title>IGC 1996 -- What's at Stake?</title>
</header>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<hr>
<H2><center><img src="../images/2000.jpg"></a><p>
IGC 1996 -- What's at Stake?</h2>
<p>
Full text of an article from <i>Lom&#233; 2000</i>, No. 1, January 1996: page 3</h4>
</center>
<hr>
  Four years after the Maastricht Treaty, the EU is convening  an intergovernmental conference
  (the so-called "IGC") to revise it. Officially due to begin on 29 March 1996, the IGC aims to
  adapt the institutional structure of the EU to an increase in Member States and to revise the
  EU's Common Foreign and Security Policy (CFSP) as stipulated by the Treaty. Whilst the
  Maastricht treaty constituted a benchmark for EU development policy (by providing a legal
  base for it), it is not, so far, on the agenda of the IGC. It could, however, be affected by the
  quest of the IGC for coherence in external policies.
  <p>
  Indeed, the search for coherence in external relations is now the buzz word. Within
  cooperation policy itself, coherence could imply incorporating ACP-EU relations in a broader
  EU cooperation policy.  However, it is a broader coherence between the three sets of external
  policy (trade, development cooperation and CFSP) that is of primary concern to European
  policy-makers. Coherence can be enhanced by defining common goals to which all external
  policies aim, or by designing a clear task division between the three areas of external policy.
  In both cases, regardless of the benefits that coherence can bring to an incipient European
  foreign policy, it does pose some threats to ACP-EU cooperation. The first scenario, in which
  common goals or interests would be defined  within CFSP, would most likely lead to an
  instrumentalisation of development cooperation in which it is subordinated to political,
  security or immigration concerns. On the other hand, a clear division of tasks would
  incorporate strategic and political questions including relations with areas of "common
  interest" (Mediterranean or Eastern Europe) within CFSP, give trade policy overall
  responsibility for economic sets of relations (Latin America, South East Asia) and reduce
  development policy to cooperation with the ACP and other least developed countries. 
  <p>
  In both cases, the ACP should avoid the dangerous situation in which they would not be seen
  to represent any common European interest. Only by demonstrating a central position in
  European foreign and economic policy can a marginalisation of development cooperation be
  avoided. It would therefore be wise for the ACP to articulate, as soon as possible, their
  positions towards the EU, as has been suggested by the former Prime Minister of Mauritius.
<p>
</h5>
<H3><A HREF="l20_gb.htm">Return to Contents Page</A></H3>
