<html>
<header>
<title>Europe - ACP Development Policies from a Maastricht Perspective</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><A HREF = "../index.html"><IMG SRC  =
"../images/logo.gif"><p></a>
Coordinate or be Coordinated:<br>Europe - ACP Development Policies from a Maastricht Perspective
<br>
<i>Louk Box and Paul Goodison</i><p></h3>
<h5>(Summary of Box, L. and P. Goodison. 1994. Coordinate or be coordinated: Europe - ACP development
policies from a Maastricht perspective. In: Coordinating the development aid policies of European
countries, edited by J.L. Rhi-Sausi and M. Dass&#249;. Rome: Centro Studi di Politica Internazionale.)
<p>
<a
href="../prog4/p4pub.htm">For related ECDPM publications</a></h5>
</center><p>
<hr>
For decades, the call for coordination in European development policy making has been heard.
Although certain forms of policy coordination have emerged, especially under the Convention of
Lom&#233;, only a beginning has been made. With the ratification of the Maastricht Treaty on 1 November
1993, a new phase in the coordination debate was reached. This Treaty specifies under its Title XVII that the "Community and the Member States shall coordinate their policies on development cooperation."
<p>
The question is: who coordinates what, where and why? Since the general principle of subsidiarity
   does not immediately apply to these forms of coordination and 'complementarity' does, the situation
is even less clear than in other areas of European cooperation. Since, moreover, no clear design, old or new, seems to lie yet at the basis of EC development cooperation in the 1990's, the question must be asked: what forms of coordination have emerged over the past decade, what lessons can be drawn and what implications does this have for the future coordination of European development policies? 
<p>
In this paper, we focus on the experience with the Lom&#233; Convention and the countries in Africa, the Caribbean and the Pacific (ACP).
<p>
We limit ourselves to the problem of coordination in Europe - ACP development cooperation. This
has two reasons: the availability of a recently published descriptive study on EC development
cooperation, and the fact that the coordination issue by itself is sufficiently important to warrant a
separate paper. We argue that the positive experiences with Lom&#233; Convention form the basis for
coordination between Europe and poor countries, provided institutional development takes place in
these countries allowing for partnership... and institutional development takes place in Brussels
allowing policy coherence. Provided, as well, that the Maastricht Treaty is elaborated to guide internal
European coordination and that the notion of complementarity is defined much more clearly in relation
to development cooperation. Provided, finally that the aims of European development policies are
reduced to come into line with the limited institutional resources it can muster.
<p>
<h3>Conclusion: A National Base is Still Lacking</h3>
<p>
What comes through quite clearly from the experience of programming under the Lom&#233; Convention
is: 
<ul>
<li>the extent to which potentially it could facilitate coordination of Community and Member States programmes in individual ACP countries;

<li>the relative inability of many ACP Governments, particularly in Africa, to play the lead role in determining the utilisation of development assistance resources in the context of coherent national development strategies, which the programming exercise places upon them;

<li>the relatively weak capacity of the Commission to actually coordinate with EC Member states and the other major providers of funds when considering the deployment of Lom&#233; resources in support of recipient led development strategies and programmes.

<li>In certain countries and in certain important areas, such as the utilisation of Counter-part Funds, the
Commission services have provided a lead in the initiation of coordinated action. 
However, this has largely been the consequence of dedicated action by individual civil servants and
the "right" personal chemistry between key actors. Only if the capacity of ACP Governments is
increased to lead the programming exercise is the programming process likely to provide a focus for
the coordinated deployment of available resources in a more effective manner.
<p></ul>
The European Commission could give consideration to assisting in this process by:
<ul><p>
<li>paying more attention to operationalising policy priorities in the social and economic
     circumstances pertaining in individual ACP countries and sub-regions of the ACP; 

<li>reviewing the relationship between Delegations and headquarters;

<li>giving priority to strengthening the Delegations capacity to exploit existing instruments in a coherent and systematic manner consistent with policy priorities and in a manner relevant to local economic and social circumstances;

<li>redefining the role of the Delegate to move away from project administration towards policy dialogue and appropriate programme design.
<p></ul>
<hr>
<H6><A HREF = "../index.html"><IMG ALIGN=middle
SRC="../images/logo.gif"></a> <i>Updated on October 18,
1995</i><br>
