</DOCHDR>
<html>
<header>
<title>The objectives of bilateral aid, structural adjustment and donor policy</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H2><center><img src="../images/nar.jpg"><p></a>
The objectives of bilateral aid, structural adjustment and donor policy</h2>
<h4><i>NAR Secretariat</i>
<p>
Source: <i>In Brief: Information from the NAR</i><br>No. 1, February 1992</h4>
<h5>The full text of the report in English, as well as a list of other publications, are available free of
charge from the Council's secretariat: E-mail: nar-dgis@dgis.minbuza.nl</h5>
</center>
<hr>
<b>The 98th report of the National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) on the
relationship between the bilateral aid policies of donor countries and structural adjustment policy was
presented to the Minister for Development Cooperation, J P Pronk, on 27 February 1992.</b>
<p>
<h3>Summary of the problems and the questions explored in the report</h3>

Developing countries which wish to receive loans from the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the
World Bank have to agree to the conditions laid down by these institutions. These conditions are part of the
"adjustment programmes" which the recipient countries are expected to implement. An adjustment
programme is a package of economic measures designed to restructure the national economy, in other words
macroeconomic measures. Many donor countries also finance projects in developing countries, the purpose
of which is to improve the situation of particular sections of the population at local level. Such projects are
described in economic jargon as designed to operate at "micro-level". Since both the macroeconomic
measures contained in adjustment programmes and projects affect the situation at micro-level, these two
forms of development aid need to be coordinated. Otherwise, the effectiveness of aid policy is likely to be
undermined and efforts to reduce poverty may conceivably suffer a setback.
<p>
The report indicates that the level of coordination is less than satisfactory and raises the question of how
coordination of the macro and micro-policies of donors can be improved and what problems this presents for
developing countries and donors. Some of the reasons for the lack of policy coordination are explored and a
number of suggestions are made for remedying the situation. Finally, attention is turned to the matter of
how to strengthen the position of developing countries in the policy dialogue with donors.
<p>

<h3>Problems</h3>

The purpose of an adjustment programme is to redress the balance between a country's income and its
revenue by means of a number of economic measures at national level. In the longer term it should also
bring about a restructuring of the economy to the benefit of those sectors in which there is room for growth.
An operation of this kind involves what are known as "macroeconomic" measures, such as improving the
balance of payments, altering the rate of exchange, reducing the public spending deficit, stimulating
productive investment, improving the investment climate, eliminating market restrictions, ensuring proper
government, creating a sound infrastructure, etc. Measures of this kind affect many different sections of the
population and the reaction of the different socioeconomic groups (farmers, traders, employees, etc.) varies.
It is the sum total of all these reactions which determines the ultimate effect of measures taken at the
national level.
<p>
The other form of aid mentioned above - development projects - is very often geared to specific groups and
the particular circumstances in which they live. It would seem logical therefore to coordinate adjustment
programmes on the one hand and project aid on the other. The report indicates that coordination is not as
effective as it should be.
<p>
<h4>Lack of understanding of socioeconomic implications</h4>

One important reason for this mentioned in the report is a lack of understanding of the socioeconomic
implications, which hinders the coordination of macro and micro-policies in the short term. It may be
possible in some sectors, such as agriculture, to predict the impact of adjustment policy on specific
socioeconomic groups and their reaction to it in broad terms, but that is all. Any attempt to make a more
detailed forecast of the reaction of certain groups to adjustment measures will to some extent be a question
of guesswork, and it is likely that the response at micro-level will differ according to country and culture.
Most economic models are not sophisticated enough to be of any help. There is a very real danger,
therefore, that certain economic measures will prove too heavy-handed or backfire, despite the good
intentions behind them. The authorities in the country in question often have no factual information to hand
about the local situation with which it would be possible to make a more accurate analysis. The resources
and manpower/expertise necessary for collecting such data are often lacking. This makes it extremely
difficult to pursue an effective poverty-reduction policy geared to the specific needs of particular groups.
<p>
The policy document "A World of Difference" refers in this context to the need for "a far-reaching
knowledge of and insight into social processes" and asks what categories of poor people should be
distinguished.
<p>
<h4>Inadequate coordination due to the interests of the donor countries</h4>

It should come as no surprise that development policy is influenced in part by the interests of the donor
countries themselves. However, this is another factor which hinders coordination between the donor
countries as a group and with the recipient countries and the multilateral financial institutions.
<p>
<h4>Excessive influence of donors over long-term policy</h4>

Because the developing countries often lack any systematic data or knowledge and understanding of their
socioeconomic situation, they have very limited scope for presenting a wellfounded long-term policy of their
own. This is a major handicap for them when it comes to formulating a view of their own future in the
discussions held with donors about the adjustment measures to be taken. This task is more or less
automatically taken over by the donors, who proceed to formulate a long-term policy for their own activities
in the developing countries, often on the basis of inaccurate information and instruments which are not
sufficiently geared to the local situation.
<p>
<h3>Conclusions and recommendations</h3>

The report comes to the conclusion that developing countries are not given sufficient opportunity to voice
their own opinions on long-term development policy. Development policy is primarily the responsibility of
the governments of developing countries. Donors may of course ask questions about that policy. The report
sees the relative inability of developing countries to formulate a well-founded viewpoint as a fundamental
problem. It means that they are often more or less forced to accept the strategies proposed by others, which
are often tied to funding and reflect interests other than their own. A policy which has been accepted only
under external pressure is less likely to be successful because it does not have the wholehearted support of
the recipient country.
<p>
This problem is partly brought about by a lack of technical capacity on the part of the competent authorities
in developing countries. The Council recommends that countries be given more support in shaping and
planning their own development on the basis of priorities they themselves have formulated. This can be done
by strengthening the government agencies responsible for research and planning in these countries,
preferably in the framework of an innovative policy of technical aid and long-term aid relations. Such
support would be conditional on the countries conducting a policy geared to eliminating poverty.
<p>
The report concludes that besides problems of a technical nature there is also a lack of scientific understan-
ding of the socioeconomic structures in society. A different view is adopted of the working of the national
economy than is customary in macroeconomics. If a more careful analysis is made macroeconomic issues,
aims and stategies can be integrated with more specific objectives with regard to poverty, the environment,
the rural or urban population, the access of particular groups to education or other social services, or the use
of natural resources. Integral analysis is essential, both from the point of view of macroeconomic policy and
with regard to supporting policy recommendations at micro-level. Such integration has been lacking to date
in the analysis not only of structural adjustment but also of specific target group, sectoral and regional
problems. More needs to be known about gender relationships, the division of labour and decision-making
within households if integral analysis is to be possible. An integrated approach is necessary both in the
developing countries and on the part of the bilateral and multilateral donors. Models have been, or are
being, developed which will permit a more effective analysis to be made. A number of examples are
mentioned in the report.
<p>
The Council recommends that more use be made of integral analysis models. The World Bank should be
encouraged to resume its old pioneering role in the field of policy analysis.
<p>
The Council concludes that a greater understanding of local circumstances in countries with which the
Netherlands has an aid relationship is essential. The same point is made in the policy document "A World of
Difference". The Council recommends that understanding of local circumstances be improved by commis-
sioning more research in these countries.
<p>
Information which would allow a prompt response to be made to unforeseen situations is not always
immediately available. The Council recommends in such cases that an early warning system be set up to
detect in advance major disruptions in the normal pattern of events (e.g. crop failure). It may be necessary,
with regard to the accumulation of information on individual countries, for donors to specialise in one field
or another; the EC could play a role here.
<p>
The problem of coordinating policy at macro and micro-level applies equally to the formulation and
implementation of environmental policy. A thorough understanding of the role played by the environment at
micro-level as the means of livelihood for specific groups is crucial to an effective policy. Poverty
alleviation and sustainability must be given a key position. Environmental policy should also guarantee that a
consensus is reached on the way in which various uses of the environment by different groups can be
reconciled with each other. The Council fears that the so-called "hard option", which prohibits the
destruction of non-renewable natural resources, places too severe a restriction on the ability of poor
countries to pursue a policy aimed at combating poverty. The Council concludes that this would particularly
affect those of the poor with limited access to non-renewable resources.
<p>
The Council recommends that the replacement of natural resources by other productive capital should not
be excluded unless it can be shown that the preservation of certain natural resources does not stand in the
way of poverty alleviation. Macroeconomic policy, including adjustment programmes, should be assessed in
the light of its effects on each socioeconomic group and their access to natural resources.
<p>
<h3>Other recommendations</h3>

The Council recommends that countries which make genuine efforts to implement an effective structural
adjustment programme should be offered the prospect of more permanent benefits, such as inclusion in a
currency zone similar to that of the Francophone countries of Africa.
<p>
Investments should be compatible with the implementing capacity of the government. The Council
recommends a more hands-off approach with regard to investments. Donor countries must ensure that new
projects do not conflict with the necessary rationalisation of activities. As market forces come increasingly
into play, investment decisions can be further decentralised. The identification and support of development
projects can then take place from the bottom up.
<p>
<HR>
