<HTML>

<HEAD>

<Title>Kirkstall Valley campaign Letter</Title>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGColor="#FFFFFF" Text="#000000" Link="#0000FF" VLink="#FF00FF" ALink="#FF0000">





<H3>This is the letter included in an email to us from Kirkstall Valley Campaign Group

</H3>



<pre>



In the light of the media interest in allegations of parliamentary

sleaze, I would like to draw your attention to the controversy

surrounding a major development in Kirkstall, Leeds.  Although of

particular concern to local residents, it is of National significance in

that it draws attention to the failure of  existing regulatory bodies to

protect the public interest.  It is a glaring example of how vested

interests and secrecy can destroy a neighbourhood, and how the

Government can suppress the truth.  Certainly, if you are genuinely

interested in sleaze, corruption, maladministration and incompetence,

and more importantly how these can combine to override the public

interest you could do much worse than look at this case.  You will find

that criticism should be levelled at the behaviours of the DoE, the

Treasury solicitors, the officers of the local Council and most

significantly the operation of a former quango, the Leeds Development

Corporation (LDC).



The controversy surrounds the grant of planning permission for a huge

supermarket on playing fields in a highly dense residential area of

Leeds.  The main beneficiaries of this are the local RUFC, several

directors of which were involved on the planning authority (the LDC). 

In addition, the actions of the Chair of the planning authority must be

suspect since most of the decisions leading to this consent were taken

when he had a substantial pecuniary interest (estimated to be 20

million).



A cursory look at the scheme shows that it has been rushed through

without consideration of the highways problems.  The site is situated on

the second busiest road into Leeds and conservative estimates suggest

that the development will lead to a 25% increase in traffic volumes. 

The local population have been denied crossing facilities in the

existing scheme on the grounds that there are too many pedestrians. 

Now, under pressure to push the scheme through, the Highways officers

have failed to consider the interests of Public transport, cyclists and,

most importantly, pedestrians.

This scheme has not yet passed all the obstacles but the Government is

exerting pressure on the Council to push it through.  A little bit of

investigative journalism would certainly give Ministers and the Council

something to think about and, maybe, prevent the accumulated effects of

bias, maladministration and protection of self interest from ruining an

inner city community.



Some key facts, for which there is documentary and legal evidence,

follow:-



  1) Appointment of a major political activist for the Conservative

Party to the Chair of the Leeds Development Corporation (LDC) by the

DoE.  This quango was the planning authority for an area in Kirkstall,

Leeds.



  2) The failure by the aforementioned appointee to declare both a

substantial pecuniary interest (up to 20 million) in connection with a

planning application in Kirkstall, and his connections with the

Developer.



  3) The grant of planning permission by the LDC to this Developer for a

very large supermarket on playing fields in a high density residential

area without consideration of the full traffic and environmental

effects, not to mention the detrimental effect on the local population.



  4) The destruction of evidence (the controversial planning file) by

the LDC at the end of its operational life.  All other planning files

were handed to the Council.



  5) The failure of the DoE to investigate the actions of its

appointees.  Instead it sought to subvert the public interest and defend

the actions of the LDC.



  6) The failure of the Treasury solicitors, acting for the DoE, to

disclose material facts in court.  They knew the planning file had been

destroyed yet stated that it had been handed to Leeds City Council after

the demise of the LDC.



  7) The behaviour of Council officers in the Highways department who

have failed to consider properly the safety and interests of

pedestrians.





Most of the information proving the above statements has already been

collated and all you would need to do is to ask certain Ministers and

local Councillors what threats are being used to push the scheme

through.  This is a case where your questions and reporting of the truth

could prevent a major miscarriage of justice.  I will gladly provide you

with a fuller account of the events surrounding this case and back them

up with  documentary evidence.

I look forward to hearing from you.





</pre>





