<html>

<head>

<title>World Aids Day - 1st December</title>

</head>

<hr>

<body>

<center>
<TABLE BORDER=4>

</center><p>



<i>This information has been supplied by<a href="index.html"> AVERT</a></i><hr><p>


<center><h3>WORLD AIDS DAY 1st December</h3></center>

<i>"AIDS is a terrible thing. World AIDS Day is an opportunity to remind people the future is in their hands." <p>

"We don't hear much about AIDS anymore. You need a day once a year to remind people it hasn't gone away." <p>

"At college we had a special lecture about AIDS and HIV because it was World AIDS Day. You realise how many people are affected. People with AIDS and their families, friends, everything...." </i><p>

This page tells you about the meaning of World AIDS Day, the Red Ribbon and how you can help. It gives you the facts and figures about HIV and AIDS in the UK and where to go for further advice and information. <br><br><br>



<center><h3>WORLD AIDS DAY</h3></center>

Every year the 1st December is set aside as a special day for people all over the world to remember all those who have died and all those who have been affected.<p>


It is also a day to continue our efforts to reduce the effect of HIV infection and AIDS in the future. <p>


There are conferences, services of remembrance, public events and meetings all over the UK and many other countries. Many people wear a piece of folded red ribbon as a symbol of AIDS awareness. <p>


Lots of individuals are involved, as well as schools, colleges, health centres, hospitals, charities and voluntary groups. <br><br><br>

<center><h3>'WHAT CAN I DO...?'</h3></center>

Lots more people will become infected with HIV in the future. And lots more families, friends, partners and carers will be affected unless we act NOW.<p>

We need to act:<br>
<li>to educate people so they can avoid infection in the future <br>
<li>to care for and help those needing our support. <p>


If you have children or grand-children you could: <br>
- talk to them about HIV and AIDS.<p>


If you have a sister or brother, a friend or a partner you could:<br>
 - talk to them about what World AIDS Day is. <p>


If you could be at risk in the future, you can make sure you don't become infected yourself. <p>


You can help increase AIDS awareness by wearing a red ribbon on World AIDS Day. <p>


Through talking about AIDS and taking action we can all help to reduce the effects of AIDS in the future.<br><br><br> 


<center><h3>AIDS AND HIV: THE FIGURES</h3></center>

The first person with AIDS in the UK was diagnosed in 1981. By 1995 over 11,000 people in the UK had been diagnosed as having AIDS. Nearly three quarters of these people have already died. <p>


It is much harder to say how many people are infected with HIV. By 1995 over 25,000 people were known to be infected. Of these about<p>



21,500 are men<br>
3,600 are women<br>
600	are children<p>


But these are only the people who are known to be infected. The actual number of infected people could be five times greater. This means that the number of men, women and children infected in the UK could already be over 100,000.<br><br><br> 


<center><h3>THE FACTS</h3></center>

- Every day the number of people infected with HIV in the UK increases. <br>
- There is no cure for AIDS.<br>
- We all need to act NOW to reduce the effect that HIV infection and AIDS will have in the future. <br><br><br>


<center><h3>INFORMATION ABOUT AIDS</h3></center>

AIDS is caused by a virus called HIV.<p>


After a person has been infected with HIV for some time, their body's natural defence system can no longer fight against diseases which they would normally get over quite easily. <p>


When the person gets one or more of these serious diseases they are considered to have AIDS. Most people with AIDS die within three years of diagnosis.<p>


Many people live with HIV infection for many years without any signs of ill health. It can be as much as ten years or more after becoming infected before someone develops AIDS. <p>


Even if a person does not have any symptoms of ill health they can still pass on HIV to someone else. <p>


The main ways in which people become infected with HIV are: <br>
- by having sexual intercourse with an infected person<br>
- by injecting drugs with a needle or syringe which has been used by someone who is infected <br>
- by the virus being passed by an infected woman to her unborn child or through breastfeeding. <p>


This is because the virus is present in the sexual fluids and blood of infected people. If infected blood or fluids get into your blood then you can become infected.<br><br><br>


<center><h3>THE RED RIBBON</h3></center>

Anyone can make or wear a red ribbon. It is one way that you can show your concern about AIDS. <p>


To make your own red ribbon:<br>
<li>Get an ordinary piece of red ribbon about six inches long <br>
<li>Fold it into a loop, then fasten it using an ordinary safety pin. <p>


Making extra red ribbons and giving them to your friends and relatives to wear is one way of helping to raise AIDS awareness. <br><br><br>

<center><h3>FURTHER INFORMATION ABOUT HIV INFECTION AND AIDS: </h3></center>

National AIDS Helpline (for people in the UK) <br>
If you are concerned about AIDS you can phone the National AIDS Helpline at any time on <br>
0800 567 123
All calls are free, entirely confidential and do not appear on the phone bill. <br><br><br>

<center><h3>AVERT</h3></center>

<a href="index.html">AVERT</a> is a small non-governmental organisation in the UK whose aim is to prevent people becoming infected with HIV and to improve the quality of life for those already infected. AVERT works towards this aim through research and education. <p>


For free information about HIV infection and AIDS (including <a href="stats.htm">UK statistics</a>) or for details of AVERT's publications you can contact <p>


AVERT<br>
11-13 Denne Parade<br>
Horsham<br>
West Sussex<br>
RH12 1JD<p>


Tel +44 (0)1403 210202<p>


Fax +44 (0)1403 211001<p>


e-mail: avert@bbcnc.org.uk


For more information:<p>

<ul>
- in the UK contact <a href="http://www.was.hea.org.uk">The Health Education Authority </a><p>


- worldwide contact <a href="http://www.who.ch/">The World Health Organisation</a></ul> <p>

<hr>


<a href="./index.html">Return to AVERT Home Page</a>

</center>

<hr>       

</body>

