<html>
<header>
<title>Finland's and EU's Development Cooperation</title>
</header>
<hr>
<h3><center><IMG align=middle SRC  = "../images/fi.jpg"><p>
Finland's and EU's Development Cooperation: A Comparison.<br>
<i>Jarle Harstad and Paul Silfverberg</i><p></h3>
<h5>(Summary of FINNIDA Evaluation Study 1995:2)<br></h5>
</center><p>
<hr>
Upon Finland's entry into the European Union, FINNIDA decided to carry out a comparative analysis of Finland's and the EU's development cooperation policies and modalities. The points of departure were the new obligations and responsibilities as well as the new opportunities which participation in the new European-level international cooperation offered Finland. The study contains:
<ul>
<li>a comparative analysis of Finnish and EU development cooperation policies and processes;<br>
<li>a comparison of the modalities of developing country relations, as well as the concurrence and coherence between and within Finnish and EU relations;<br>
<li>visions for future Finnish participation in policy dialogue and development cooperation issues within the EU.
</ul><p>
After a review of EU and Finnish development policy and programmes, the authors suggest that:
<ul>
<li>Finnish comparative advantages compared to the EU seem to be in the areas of environmental protection, sustainable use of natural resources, and social development (including gender issues).<p>
<li>Finland can benefit from cooperation within the EU in matters such as democratisation, macro-economic policies, institutional development, trade, untying of aid, and the development of private sector institutions.<p>
<li>Finland can activity promote Finnish experience and expertise in countries such as Vietnam, Nepal, and Nicaragua where the EU has been a marginal donor until now.<p>
<li>Finland should continue its efforts to increase recipient responsibility and execution in its programmes. This includes seeking to influence the EU towards establishing real partnerships with recipient countries.<p>
<li>Together with fellow EU members, Finland should assess ways to simplify and streamline EU aid and cooperation procedures, espcially for ACP countries.<p>
<li>Both Finnish and EU aid should gradually shift from an emphasis on attainment of physical targets toward more concern for local competence and institution building.
</ul>
<p>
To get a copy of the report, please contact the Evaluation Unit, Department for International Development Cooperation, Ministry for Foreign Affairs, Katajanokanlaituri 3, 00160 Helsinki, Finland<p>
<HR>
