<HTML>
<header>
<title>NGOs and the IGC</title>
</header>

<hr>
<H2><center><img src="../images/2000.jpg"></a><p>
NGOs and the IGC</h2>

<p>
<h4>Full text of an article from <i>Lom&#233; 2000</i>, No. 2, May 1996: page 3</h4>
</center>
<hr>
<P>
While the Inter Governmental Conference to revise the Maastricht
Treaty does not have development cooperation on its agenda, the
NGO community in Europe is determined to influence IGC discussions
so that their values and principles are reflected in the common
foreign and security policy of the EU.
<P>
From 19-20 April, participants at the annual NGDO-LC Conference
on &quot;The IGC and a Europe open to the world&quot; discussed
the coherence of European policies affecting developing countries.
Three main questions were addressed: What are the inconsistencies
in EU policies, where do they come from, and how can they be overcome?
Three policy-areas were singled out: the common foreign and security
policy; immigration and citizenship policies; and common economic
policies (mainly trade and agriculture) that seem to &quot;give
with one hand and take with the other.&quot; Participants concluded
that inconsistencies are mainly due to the clash of interests
between different groups in Europe, including within civil society
(consumers, agro-business).
<P>
The view that the EU should respect the objectives it sets for
itself and promote values of human security was equally at the
core of two NGO meetings held in London and Helsinki to discuss
the future of EU aid.
<P>
The British platform of the NGO-EC Liaison Committee organised
a conference entitled &quot;Lost Horizons? The future of Europe's
Relations with the South.&quot; Representatives of the Commission,
the British Government and the European Parliament gave their
views on the future direction of EU aid. Opinions were split on
several issues of concern to the NGO's -- the focus on the poorest
countries, the reorientation of EU interests and aid towards neighbouring
countries. The IGC, the future of Lom&eacute; and the position
of LDCs in the world trade system were also discussed.
<P>
These issues also dominated a meeting organised by KEPA, the Finnish
NGO umbrella organisation. ECDPM presented some of the challenges
facing EU development cooperation at this seminar whose aim was
to raise awareness of EU development cooperation among Finnish
NGOs. Despite their newness to the Lom&eacute; scene, the critical
comments by Finnish NGOs will be valuable inputs into the ongoing
reflection review process. 
