<html>
<header>
<title>Development cooperation and fighting urban poverty</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H2><center><img src="../images/nar.jpg"><p></a>
Development cooperation and fighting urban poverty</h2>
<h4><i>NAR Secretariat</i>
<p>
Source: <i>In Brief: Information from the NAR</i><br>No. 7, March 1994</h4>
<h5>The full text of the report in English, as well as a list of other publications, are available free of
charge from the Council's secretariat: E-mail: nar-dgis@dgis.minbuza.nl</h5>
</center>
<hr>
<b>In march 1994 the National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) presented its report
nr. 103, `Development cooperation and fighting urban poverty' to the Minister for Development
Cooperation, J.P. Pronk. This summary contains a description of the problem as the Council has identified
it, the results of an analysis of the problem and of policy, the Council's conclusions and its recommen-
dations for the policy of the Minister for Development Cooperation. </b>
<p>

<h3>The growth of towns and urban poverty in the Third World</h3>

According to projections by the United Nations, 51% of the world's population will live in towns and cities
in the year 2000 and as many as 65% in the year 2025. The total population of the world will be 8.4 billion
in the year 2000, 4.4 billion of whom will live in the towns of developing countries. Primary and medium-
sized towns in developing countries will grow explosively, especially in Asia and Africa. Because of their
unbalanced demographic structure - large numbers of young migrants and a high excess of births over deaths
- the population in towns and cities will continue to grow faster than in rural areas for a long time, even if
migration to towns declines. 
<p>
A growing percentage of the urban population of Latin America, and of Africa and Asia, live below the
poverty line. Between 1970 and 1980, the population of greater Sao Paulo rose by 44%, but that of the
working-class districts went up by 446% in the same period. More than a third of urban residents in Asia
(1985) live below the poverty line and the figure is as high as 86% in Bangladesh. Even in the rapidly
expanding economies of South and East Asia more than 10% of the urban population live below the poverty
line. 
<p>
Absolute poverty in the world, measured in terms of income, is still worst in rural areas. According to
statistics the level of provisions and facilities is higher in urban than in rural areas. However, a growing
number of the urban poor are affected by a concentration of inter-related poverty factors. According to their
own perception of their circumstances the urban poor see "vulnerability" as the main feature of their
existence. They often have no access to provisions such as education, health care, proper housing and credit
and other facilities for work and income. In most Third World towns and cities a large percentage of the
workforce is unemployed or working in temporary jobs. The growth of the workforce - the population
between 15 and 65 years of age - is usually faster in towns than that of the urban population as a whole.
The demand for labour by the government authorities and large and medium-sized business declined sharply
in the eighties in a number of developing countries. The fall in real wages in the public sector and major
private sector companies and the large numbers of unemployed have also caused incomes to drop in the
informal sector. The levels of protection for employees have fallen dramatically.
<p>
The urban poor do not have social networks, nor do they have any influence on political decision-making
processes or say about the circumstances in which they live. The urban authorities do not usually have the
management capacity or the resources to deal with the complex problems effectively. Nevertheless, many of
the urban poor actually succeed in raising their standard of living. In a number of towns, the residents of
slum areas have successfully formed self-help organisations, often for highly specific purposes such as
housing and water. The appalling living conditions of poor people in towns also create psychological and
social problems in the form of stress, alienation, instability and insecurity, heightened by the disappointment
of expectations which have failed to materialise and the discrepancy between incomes and spending
opportunities in towns. This situation often leads to social unrest, forms of violence and crime in which
young people are both victims and offenders, child abuse and violence against women in the home.
<p>
<h3>The most affected groups</h3>

The vicious circle of marginalisation in towns is worst for three groups of poor people:
<ul>
<li>Mothers, especially breadwinners who are heads of poor households i.e. women-maintained
households. The repercussions of a poor diet, bad health, living conditions in slums, and long hours at work
and travelling to and from the workplace are worst for pregnant women with jobs.
<li>Street children. Children and young people up to the age of 24 represent 55.8% of the total population
of developing countries and 65% in Africa (1992). The low family incomes of the poor, their limited access
to work and the disintegration of the family mean more children end up on the streets. Estimates suggest the
world total amounts to tens of millions. The most vulnerable are once again girls aged between 12 and 16
and pre-teenagers. Street children are left to fend for themselves and many end up in crime and prostitution.
They are abused by the drugs mafia and in Latin America they are exposed to violence by the police and
death squads.
<li>Unemployed young people. Unemployment is especially high among young people up to the age of
25. They have little access to the informal sector and small companies. The young also have to compete
with older people who have lost their jobs in the formal sector.
</ul>
<p>
<h3>Existing policy to fight urban poverty</h3>

The Council's report examines the policies of a large number of players who are attempting to fight urban
poverty. The Council notes that the policy priorities of developing countries, multilateral donors and the
Netherlands Minister for Development Cooperation do not always coincide. The authorities of developing
countries only approach the problem of the urban poor as a separate issue as an exception. Even an
organisation like the World Bank places its efforts to reduce urban poverty in the context of general urban
development. The priorities of Netherlands policy such as work and incomes, the human settlements sector
and improving public administration are no different from those of the  multilateral organisations, although
the strong emphasis of current policy on direct measures to fight urban poverty is an exception.
<p> 
To summarise, the Council has the following comments about Netherlands development policy:
<ul>
<li>Development policy to fight urban poverty is formulated as a flanking policy, not only in relation to
the policy of virtually all the relevant multilateral organisations, but also in relation to the policy of most
developing countries.
<li>Policy as a whole does not focus explicitly on problems of unemployment among young people and
their lack of training, the position of women in towns and the problem of urban environment, nor on special
opportunities for Netherlands policy to solve problems in secondary towns. Publications do not suggest that
the Women and Environment Spearhead Programmes have integrated urban aspects into their activities. In
the view of the Council this means that an important area of policy - unemployment among young people -
is not receiving attention.
<li>The Council endorses the importance of programmes by the Netherlands Finance Company for
Developing Countries (FMO) and the Retired Managers Assignment Programme (PUM) to generate
employment in developing countries.
</ul>
<p>
<h3>Basic premises</h3>

The Council's most important conclusion is that a special policy needs to be formulated in view of the
nature and rapidly growing urgency of urban poverty. The Council's basic premise is that policy to reduce
urban poverty is an integral part of Netherlands development policy as a whole. 
<p>
The Council considers that Netherlands bilateral aid to fight urban poverty should be confined to cities
which have no more than one to two million inhabitants, if only because the Netherlands can not call on the
expertise required to administer very large cities. In view of the structural nature of the problem, the choice
of towns will involve long-term cooperation with "concentration towns". The Council also thinks that the
three most important target groups for Netherlands policy which is designed to fight urban poverty should
be women-maintained households, unemployed young people and street children.
<p>
Formulation of Netherlands policy in this area should be based on a broad and integrated vision and a
process approach. In view of the inter-related nature of the problems, attempts to solve urban poverty will
require simultaneous policy interventions at various administrative levels and of different kinds: human
resource development to raise productivity, improvements in administration and management, macro-
economic policy, creating facilities, promoting the participation of the urban poor and helping them to form
their own organisations, investing in economic activities and infrastructure, combined with improving the
urban environment.  
<p>
The Council attaches great importance to stimulating economic growth as a necessary, though not in itself
sufficient precondition to fight poverty in general and urban poverty in particular. It believes productivity
must be raised in many developing countries, despite the apparent contradiction between this objective and
the possibility of unemployment as a result of short-term and long-term increases in productivity. 
<p>
The Council considers that Netherlands policy to fight urban poverty must make allowance for the extent to
which national development policies of governments of recipient countries allow for the effects of such
policies on the urban poor. Using this criterion, Netherlands policy can make choices to flank or support the
policy of governments or multilateral organisations, and to support certain types of activities such as those
of local NGOs. The Council considers that in countries where national governments do not pursue a
redistribution policy, NGOs should be supported which are trying to help the poor, with the aim of
persuading governments to revise their policies.
<p>

<h3>Policy recommendations</h3>

The Council recommends intensifying the Spearhead Programme for Fighting Urban Poverty in order to
achieve the integrated approach which it advises in its recommendations. 
<p>
If possible the Council recommends that towns should be chosen using an urban poverty index.
<p>
The Council makes a distinction between direct and indirect forms of fight ing urban poverty. Direct
measures to fight poverty means activities which are undertaken in cooperation with or on the initiative of
target groups. Indirect measures to fight poverty include activities designed to improve situations which
partly determine the lives of the target groups, over which they have no say or influence.
<p>

<h4>Direct measures to fight poverty</h4>

The Council recommends promoting direct measures to fight poverty in towns by continuing to provide
NGOs with direct or indirect assistance to encourage the poor to form their own organisations and to take
care of street children. It makes good sense to carry out policy to help unemployed young people in
cooperation with the Netherlands joint financing organisations (MFOs), both sides of Netherlands industry -
unions and employers' organisations - and SNV, all of whom are already involved in such activities. The
Council recommends examining where these organisations can see opportunities to contribute towards the
training of young people and the level to which the local private sector can be involved in such activities.
<p>
The Council recommends that the Netherlands should contribute to the creation of temporary safety net
constructions of the kind used in Bolivia and Jamaica. Steps must be taken to ensure that a Social Develop-
ment Fund meets the conditions which are necessary to ensure that the available funds benefit the target
groups in particular. Although people who depend on wages in a number of countries are among the
vulnerable groups when they become unemployed, in the Council's view they do not occupy an exceptional
position in this respect.
<p>
The Council recommends that the policy dialogue with developing countries on the problems of the urban
poor should take the following considerations into account in relation to the living conditions in working-
class and slum areas:
<ul>
<li>increasing the feasibility and sustainability of activities by involving the population in planning and
implementation;
<li>providing housing rights and land rights and improving the urban infrastructure by making safe
drinking water and sanitation available and refuse collection facilities;
<li>creating opportunities for self-help activities connected with agriculture - such as crops and small
livestock - or making such activities legal in working-class districts;
<li>providing advisory services which will help to persuade small and medium-sized companies in
working-class districts to implement process improvements which will result in less industrial waste and
improve working conditions, especially those of the target groups in such companies; and
<li>improving the quality of the services provided by the urban authorities. 
</ul>
<p>
<h4>Indirect measures to fight poverty</h4>

The Council recommends supporting the policy of the World Bank and the IMF to improve the economic
structure and macro-economic policy in recipient countries. Allowance should be made for the consequences
of this policy for the urban poor. On the basis of an analysis of the effects, flanking activities can be
undertaken, through bilateral channels  if necessary, especially in concentration towns.
<p>
The Council considers that cooperation between UNCHS, UNDP and the World Bank in the Urban
Management Programme merits further support and recommends examining how far it is possible to make
allowance  at the implementation stage for the choice of towns by the Netherlands and the deployment of
Netherlands expertise in this field. In connection with the shortage of resources of the urban authorities the
Council recommends investigating how far the Netherlands can become involved in the World Bank's
Urban Development Loans, especially the parts which relate to improving the urban infrastructure.
<p>
The Council recommends examining the conditions under which Netherlands companies would be willing to
invest in economic activities in concentration towns selected by the Netherlands. In the Council's view, the
demand for products of small businesses is largely determined by the incomes of people who work for large
and medium-sized companies and for government authorities.
<p>
The Council recommends investigating whether opportunities can be created through bilateral or multilateral
channels to stimulate credits for housing by means of local currency loans. It is still important to continue
existing policy in order to support initiatives in the field of credit unions, often through NGOs.
<p>

<h3>Research</h3>

The Minister also asked the Council to examine the need for research to increase the effectiveness of policy
to fight urban poverty. The Council has identified thirteen areas in which  research can fill existing
information gaps. The Council believes that it is important to involve the perspective of the poor themselves
in each field of research. The five most important areas are as follows:
<ul>
<li>The perception of urban problems among the poor and the survival strategies they have developed as
the basis for policy. 
<li>Regular research in countries which are selected, especially in concentration cities, into the effect of
macro-economic policy on urban poverty. 
<li>The conditions which will allow poor people's organisations to have an effective influence on local
urban policy, for the benefit of the policy of NGOs and local and national authorities.
<li>The role of NGOs and companies in training young people.
<li>The integration and disintegration of groups of migrants in towns and the survival strategy at
household level, especially in women-maintained households.
</UL><p>
<HR>
<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle
