<html>
<header>
<title>Gender and development</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H2><center><img src="../images/nar.jpg"><p></a>
From words to deeds: Gender and development,<br>
the fourth UN World Women's Conference in Beijing, 1995</h2>
<h4><i>NAR Secretariat</i>
<p>
Source: <i>In Brief: Information from the NAR</i><br>No. 12, August 1995</h4>
<h5>The full text of the report in English, as well as a list of other publications, are available free of
charge from the Council's secretariat: E-mail: nar-dgis@dgis.minbuza.nl</h5>
</center>
<hr>
<b>
This was the title of recommendation no. 106, submitted on 22 August 1995 by the
Netherlands'  National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) to the Minister for
Development Cooperation, Jan Pronk.</b>
<p>
The NAR notes with concern the increase in violence, especially sexual violence, directed against
women throughout the world. The Council believes that violence against women and girls would
not be so widespread if it were not based on equally widespread acceptance, on the part of both
society and governments.
<p>
The Council supports the Netherlands Government's present policy, which unequivocally rejects
female circumcision. However, the Netherlands should make efforts to promote the
implementation of international agreements and conventions, if necessary through the use of
coercive measures, to stop or curb increasing violence against women. This view is set out in
the NAR report `From words to deeds', which was commissioned by the Minister for
Development Cooperation in the run-up to the fourth UN World Women's Conference to be held
between 4 and 14 September 1995 in Beijing.
<p>
The Council focuses its recommendations on gender and development on three themes: women
and poverty, women and human rights, and women and decision-making. These provide a
framework within which a look is taken at all the `Critical Areas of Concern' set out in the draft
programme of action of the fourth UN World Women's Conference. The Council consistently
bases its recommendations on the need for a transformation of existing gender relations. This
means that gender-related issues have consistently to be integrated into general policy. Men
should be emphatically reminded of their responsibilities in the process, so that women can
realise their sexual and social rights. It is crucial that the World Women's Conference results in a
genuine plan of action for women: `Not words, but deeds'.
<p>
The Council sees the promotion and implementation of human rights, notably economic, social
and cultural rights, as a strategic method of linking the results of a number of UN conferences.
The Council urges greater recognition of the universality of human rights, inter alia through the
adoption of a code of conduct governing the extent of the restrictions which governments are
permitted to impose on them. Furthermore, the Council argues that the supervisory mechanisms
to enforce compliance with ESC rights should be strengthened and the scope for individuals to
appeal against violations of such rights expanded. The last point is crucial to women, if they are
to achieve greater autonomy and more just relations between the sexes. The Council also
recommends that calls be made in Beijing for the adoption of a right of petition in respect of ESC
rights by making states party to the 1966 International Covenant on Economic, Social and
Cultural Rights (ICESCR). Moreover, the Council supports the Dutch Government's efforts to
promote the adoption of an additional Protocol to the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms
of Discrimination Against Women, which would accord both individuals and states the right of
petition.
<p>
The Council notes with approval that it is now recognised that improvement of women's
position is a goal in itself and not simply an instrument to other ends. Nevertheless, such an
improvement can help to resolve international problems such as poverty, environmental
degradation, violence, unemployment and social disintegration.
<p>
It is against this background that the NAR has made a large number of recommendations, both
for the fourth World Women's Conference and in the context of Dutch policy on development
cooperation. They include:
<ul>
<li>renewal of the social sector: restructuring programmes for developing countries should take
account of their potentially negative impact - both direct and indirect - on the position of
women; in a number of countries (particularly developing countries) the economic position of
women has done nothing but deteriorate, influenced by such factors as a fall in real wages; new
technologies have often resulted in an increased workload and less favourable working
conditions for women, who still have to combine work outside the home with domestic duties;
<p>
<li>conventional statistics and economic data, in which female labour has scarcely figured up
to now, should reflect the quantitative and qualitative contributions made by women to
development; the visibility of their contribution is an essential condition if their economic
situation is to be improved;
<p>
<li>defining sexual rights: at the 1994 Population Conference in Cairo these were discussed
only in the context of women's health and reproduction; the Council feels a broader framework
is needed, and defines sexual rights as follows:
<p>
<ul>
<li>`Sexual rights (sexual in the sense of `sexuality', rather than `gender') could be understood
to mean the right of individuals - women and men - freely to interpret sexuality in their own
way, free from coercion, discrimination or violence, without this resulting in a violation of the
rights of others, sexual or otherwise.'
</ul>
<p>
<li>participation of women in political and social decision-making; the Council rejects `parity
democracy' (reserved seats in representative bodies), since it places women in a separate
domain; the important thing is to remove obstacles to participation by taking measures in the
fields of education, health care, work, child care, media and culture, and to redistribute
responsibilities between women and men;
<p>
<li>an international equal opportunities task force, which should be given a coordinating role
within the UN, with duties that would include reinforcing existing agencies in the fields of gender
and women in development; the World Women's Conference should modify the preliminary
studies for the `Agenda for Development' proposed by the Secretary-General of the UN; at
present they have too little to say about gender and women in development; in the context of
the proposed UN reforms, systematic attention should also be paid to a review of personnel
policy and `corporate culture' with a view to furthering the participation of women; the Council
is dubious about the value of target figures in isolation;
<p>
<li>an increase rather than a reduction in resources for Dutch policy on gender and
development; to be maintained after the review of Dutch foreign policy;
<p>
<li>priority for the implementation and evaluation of the impact of Dutch policy on gender and
women in development, rather than for the drafting of new policy; although the Netherlands was
one of the first to develop much of the policy and many of the instruments in this field,
operationalisation of activities and programmes has failed to keep pace. The Council warns of
the risk of producing too much policy; 
<p>
<li>strengthening the position of women in conflict prevention and settlement; many women
and NGOs are active throughout the world in the cause of disarmament and peace; at present
insufficient advantage is being taken of this potential resource.
</ul>
<p>
In an earlier comment on the UNDP's 1995 Human Development  Report (published on 16
August 1995), which referred, inter alia, to the use of a `gender inequality index', various
Council members drew attention to the risks of measurement and quantification without
sufficient operationalisation of activities which really increase women's opportunities and
potential.
<p>
The Council hopes that the fact the Conference is being held in Beijing will have a positive
impact on thinking in China on democratisation and human rights, especially its policy on
population. This policy has seriously undermined women's right of self-determination in respect
of their own bodies and their right to choose the number of children they wish to have and when
they wish to have them, by subjecting them to measures such as enforced abortion.
<p>
The NAR does not regard this fourth World Women's Conference as the last of its kind. Despite
the problems attendant on such a huge operation, another such conference should be placed on
the agenda for the year 2000, so that UN member states are made to comply with their
reporting obligations and NGOs given the opportunity to question governments on their progress.
<p>
<HR>
