</DOCHDR>
<html>
<header>
<title>Population and development: The road to Cairo '94</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H2><center><img src="../images/nar.jpg"><p></a>
Population and development:<br>The road to Cairo '94</h2>
<h4><i>NAR Secretariat</i>
<p>
Source: <i>In Brief: Information from the NAR</i><br>No. 8, March 1994</h4>
<h5>The full text of the report in English, as well as a list of other publications, are available free of
charge from the Council's secretariat: E-mail: nar-dgis@dgis.minbuza.nl</h5>
</center>
<hr>
<b>
At the beginning of March 1994 the 104th report of the National Advisory Council for Development
Cooperation (NAR) was presented to the Minister for Development Cooperation, Mr J P Pronk. The report
deals with the relationship between population and development and is part of the preparation for the
International Conference on Population and Development which is to be held in Cairo in September
1994.</b>
<p>
<h3>Summary of the problem and the issues addressed in the report</h3>

How can the Netherlands contribute towards formulating and implementing population policy within the
framework of Dutch development cooperation policy? The Minister for Development Cooperation requested
the NAR to produce a report as part of the preparation for the International Conference on Population and
Development to be held in Cairo in September 1994. The Dutch delegation will be expected to present a
standpoint on abortion, the relationship between women's right not to have children and demographic aims
and the relationship between the rights of women and the responsibilities of men. The report covers these
issues.
<p>
Population policy affects people in their most intimate relationships, beliefs and values and survival
strategies, which makes it a difficult and often emotionally-charged subject. Nevertheless, it seems that
international agreement is being reached on the need to slow down the world's population growth. This is
closely related to growing interest in sustainable development in that population growth is placing an
increasing burden on the environment. However, unsustainable patterns of production and consumption are
equally harmful. The essence of the problem lies in the interrelationship between population growth and
patterns of production and consumption which are characterised by unequal distribution of resources and
power.
<p>
For the poor, children can represent security for the future. At the same time, however, it is the poor who
have limited reproductive choice owing to lack of access to family planning services. In addition, limited
access to education, health care and the labour market are further factors which lead to high fertility rates.
Population policy must therefore be embedded in strategy for combating poverty and vice versa. It is
difficult to fight poverty if the population is growing at a consistently high rate. This situation is making it
increasingly difficult to improve the lives of large sections of the population. It is clear that population
growth and poverty are interrelated.
<p>
However, population growth is not always the only problem or indeed the main problem. Geographic
distribution, the aging of the population and migration all affect population structure and give rise to
problems. Urbanisation too is becoming an extremely urgent problem. There are therefore many aspects to
the population problem and more than one solution is required.
<p>
The fertility rate, or the number of children born to each woman, varies widely depending on the
socioeconomic position of women, their cultural and religious environment and prospects, and, naturally,
those of men. However, inequality between men and women in both personal and public life is a major
influence on reproductive patterns. The joys and responsibilities of childbearing and the rearing of children
are very unequally distributed in most countries. The way in which population policy is formulated and
implemented tends to reduce women to instruments of birth control policy. Women's autonomy is restricted
and furthermore, they are burdened with the full responsibility of reducing the rate of population growth.
The needs of women are not considered enough when population policy is translated into family planning
programmes.
<p>
It is now recognised that family planning is no longer only a means of keeping the population rate down, but
that it forms part of a package of measures aimed at improving the reproductive health of women.
Reproductive health care includes the provision of contraceptives, information on the prevention, diagnosis
and treatment of sexually transmitted diseases and other infections, and services to deal safely with
unwanted pregnancies. Recent information from organisations active in the field of population policy such as
UNFPA, the World Bank and the Population Council, reveal that they now use qualitative rather than
quantitative factors (including treating people with respect and providing good guidance) to measure the
success of their family planning programmes.
<p>
The trend in international debate is to place these facilities in a broader perspective: family planning is only
one means of slowing the population growth rate. After all, this growth is a result of the fertility rate and of
demographic momentum (the increase in the number of men and women of childbearing age as a result of
the rise in the birth rate of the previous generation). Family planning is effective only where there is a
desire to reduce the fertility; it has no effect on the other factors of growth. This means that population
policy must also be included as an aspect of broader socioeconomic policy, while education and health
policy must be matched to the aims of population policy. A woman's education is still the most accurate
indicator of the number of children she will bear: the more education, the fewer children.
<p>
Infant mortality is also a factor which causes uncertainty. More funds should therefore be allocated to
education and health and socioeconomic policy should ensure that the allocation of tasks between men and
women is changed. Provisions for old age not only influence the number of children people have but also
meet the needs of the increasing numbers of old people in developing countries. The aging of the population
requires that the special needs of the elderly, of whom women form a high percentage, be taken into
account when funds are allocated. Urbanisation calls for facilities for reproductive health which are
appropriate to the specific living conditions and varied patterns of sexual and reproductive behaviour in the
cities.
<p>
<h3>Conclusions and recommendations</h3>

People must be given access to good health care and reproductive health care facilities so that they are able
to decide how many children they wish to have. This applies particularly to women who have only limited
control over their sexual relations and cannot take their own decisions on fertility. The fact that girls and
women have only limited access to education and the traditional allocation of roles in family life define the
framework within which they can make choices on having children. Legislation in many countries only
serves to reinforce the limited choice they have.
<p>
The Council believes that family planning should be part of reproductive health care. It is essential that
family planning programmes offer a wide range of high quality services. If the wrong type of birth control
is prescribed (for example the pill where there are contraindications or the IUD where there is an infection
present) or not enough information provided on side effects, women are going to be very reluctant to
participate in programmes. In addition to birth control, diagnosis and treatment of sexually transmitted
diseases and infections of the reproductive tract should be provided. Reproductive health care services
should also be available to young people and single women. Information campaigns must make men aware
that they are responsible for their sexual behaviour and their fertility, and the consequences thereof.
<p>
Safe abortion should be included in this package. Unwanted pregnancies may result from the failure of
contraceptive devices or from the lack of effective birth control methods. However, they are often the result
of violence perpetrated against women: rape either by members of the family or others or during a war
situation. The Council is of the opinion that governments should be made aware of their responsibilities
towards women's health and that they should make safe abortion available by legalising it.
<p>
The Council objects on paying target groups to limit fertility on grounds of principle and would emphasise
the enormous practical problems involved in applying this instrument. In practice there is no cost-effective
method of guaranteeing that this type of instrument would not be open to abuse, given the context of
corruption, poverty and the low status of women in which it would be applied. The Council is, however, in
favour of refunding some expenses, for example travel expenses, incurred in visiting a family planning
clinic. This would make services more accessible.
<p>
The Council recommends more support for research in order to broaden and improve the range of
contraceptives available. This applies particularly to research into male contraceptives. The Council also
recommends support for research into methods over which women have control, for example, a gel which
provides protection against HIV infection. Two forms are being developed: one provides protection only
against HIV and the other is also a contraceptive. The Council believes that research into immunological
vaccines for women is less desirable as there would be risks involved in their use and women would have
little control over such methods.
<p>
When population policy is formulated specific ways of giving greater power to the grassroots should be
sought. The Council is of the opinion that substance should be given to mechanisms for ensuring
participation in population programmes. The assistance of advisory or supervisory committees which
represent private organisations, NGOs and women's organisations in particular should be sought in
formulating and implementing programmes. Ways of evaluating participation should also be built into policy
programmes.
<p>
It is the Council's view that frank debate with the Roman Catholic church should take place on the
consequences of its doctrine on sexuality and contraception.
<p>
The Council would point to the common aspects in the approaches of environmental and women's
movements. These are clear if one examines critically the present patterns of development from a sustainable
development perspective. It is not possible to alter these patterns without changing the existing balance of
power and inequality. Survival strategies and the participation of the poor are central features of this type of
approach. Common strategy should be geared towards achieving political undertakings to spend more money
on a broad, integrated approach to population issues.
<p>
As far as the dialogue on population issues between the governments of the industrialised countries and the
developing countries of the South are concerned, the North should not evade its responsibility for sustainable
development. Unsustainable patterns of production and consumption in the North are placing a
disproportionate burden on the world's resources. The population issue should not result in a new
conditionality being introduced into development relations, but in equal dialogue.
<p>
Two members of the Council, who are also members of the working group which prepared the report,
support most of the report but have different views on a number of points, under which are also included
the idea to actively propagate a broad and consistent strategy at the Cairo conference and the offer to
elaborate on the operationalisation of a broad population policy in a future recommendation. The most
important different views can be summarised as follows:
<ul>
<li>The most serious problem by far is still rapid population growth and problems such as urbanisation
and the aging of the population are merely extensions of the main problem. Attention should therefore be
devoted primarily to population growth.
<li>The recommended measures are therefore unlikely to succeed in alleviating the population problem.
While growth is still so rapid, all acceptable means should be deployed to reduce it, including providing
target groups with financial rewards to reduce fertility. This should be subject to certain safeguards.
<li>Clearer priorities should be set, particularly relating to the nature and extent of family planning
facilities and related information campaigns.
</ul>
<p>
<HR>
<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle
SRC="../images/nar.jpg"> <i>Updated on January 22, 1996</i><p>
