<html><head><title>Planned Parenthood Challenges 1996/1</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><img align=left hspace=3 src="../ippf_pix/ippf_logo.gif"><h3>International<br>Planned<br>Parenthood<br>Federation</h3><i>The material that follows has been provided by <a href="../ippf_info.html">IPPF</a></i><br clear=left><hr><h1 align=center>Speaking out for youth in Kenya</h1><h3 align=center>by Joseph Karueru</h3><img align=left border=1 hspace=10 vspace=10 width=200 height=123 src="p31.jpg"><br>The issue of youth sexuality and reproductive health in Kenyaprovokes emotional and passionate reactions from concernedparties. Everyone agrees that young people are experiencingserious sexuality and reproductive health problems, manifestedby increasing numbers of school drop-outs due to teenagepregnancies, increased incidence of sexually transmitteddiseases (STDs) among adolescents, abortions and other socialrelated problems like drug abuse and family communicationbreakdown.<p>But attitudes to the appropriate responses differ.  There arethose groups who feel that providing any form of education andservices to young people on these matters will encouragepromiscuity and immorality among them. This standpoint ismainly shared by groups spearheaded by the Catholic Church. Other groups believe in empowering the youth with appropriateinformation on these matters to enable them make responsibledecisions.  <p>Some of the groups in the latter category have come togetherunder the Kenya Youth Initiatives Project to advocate foryouth reproductive health information and services in Kenya,adopting the slogan TETEA VIJANA, which is Swahili for 'SpeakOut For Youth'. The campaign initiative is spearheaded byYouth Serving Organizations in Kenya through the auspices ofthe National Council For Population and Development (NCPD)with the Family Planning Association of Kenya (FPAK) takingthe lead.<p>In 1992, a number of agencies including FPAK undertook acountrywide youth survey on behalf of the Government.  Amongits findings was one that the current environment forundertaking youth sexuality and reproductive health programmesin Kenya is hostile, confirming the protracted stalematebetween those for and against family life education for youth. Following the study, the Government launched a countrywideintervention, the Kenya Youth Initiatives Project, to addressits recommendations. <p>Although the family planning association had been in theforefront of supporting youth sexuality and reproductivehealth initiatives, the organization still lacked completeconsensus and there existed some hesitation and ambiguityabout what form youth services should take.  So FPAK organizedan open forum for staff and volunteers to review facts andfigures on the magnitude of the youth problems and FPAK's rolein resolving the issues, and come up with a common approachfor FPAK. At the end of the workshop the vast majority of theparticipants believed that FPAK should deliver information andservices to youth and provide leadership in advocating foryouth reproductive health.<p> Subsequently FPAK adopted a policy to provide reproductivehealth information and counselling to young people aged 10-24who are not yet sexually active in order to assist them indelaying the onset of sexual activity; to provide reproductivehealth information and services to the young people who aresexually active to help them prevent reproductive healthrelated problems; and to support the government of Kenya inintroducing Family Life Education (FLE) in schools, byactively undertaking FLE activities for in-and-out of schoolyouth, parents, teachers and other community and opinionleaders.  <p>With the youth policy in place, FPAK could confidentlyspearhead the implementation of the Kenya Youth InitiativesProject.  A project advisory committee was constituted, drawnfrom all youth serving organizations in the country, andchaired by the National Council for Population andDevelopment. As a first step, the issues and the problems thatlay ahead had to be considered. The legislative and policyenvironment of the issue had to be studied, and the perceptionand opinions of policy makers and public opinion leaders hadto be understood. The conclusions were that Kenya has nonational youth policy; that there are several contradictionsand discrepancies in Kenyan law governing social and medicalissues of the young people; and that Kenyan law is not clearon the definition of the child and the youth.<p>Furthermore, an opinion survey conducted with seniorpolitical, administrative and opinion leaders at local andnational levels showed that most of them were aware of theproblems young people experienced in relation to sexual andreproductive health and supported the provision of informationand services aimed at reducing these problems. However, mostof them were fearful of speaking openly for fear of politicaland social repercussions. Nevertheless, some of the leaders inthis study admitted encouraging their adolescent children touse condoms if they went out.<p>FPAK  developed a "Leaders Advocacy Strategic Pack",  anattractive package of IEC materials containing a set of fivefactsheets with well-illustrated and facts and figures onyouth sexual activity, teenage pregnancy, HIV/AIDS and otherSTDS, abortions and harmful practices facing girls; a booklet,with text and graphics on the same issues; and a wallchartwith coloured graphics.<p>In order to encourage leaders to make the time to read thematerial, and ensure it made enough of an impression on themthat they subsequently took action, district youth advocateswere recruited.  Each advocate would sensitize theirdistrict's leadership, by giving presentations on youthsexuality and reproductive health, and distribute the advocacystrategic pack.  They would report back so their interactionswith leaders could be collated at the project secretariat.  Atotal of 39 district advocates, chosen by a district selectionpanel, underwent a six-day intensive training course onadvocacy skills, conducted by Johns Hopkins University andAdvocates for Youth.  <p>In October and November 1995, the National Council forPopulation and Development (NCPD), with funding from theUnited Nations Population Fund, conducted five regionalPopulation Conferences, with the theme `Population andSustainable Development'. The major purpose was to discuss andreceive recommendations from leaders on the review of thecountry's population policy guidelines of 1984. Through theinitiatives of the KYIP project, youth reproductive health waspushed as a main item for discussion. Using the advocacystrategic pack, the participants were taken through the litanyof youth reproductive health problems, their social andmedical consequences and the need to put in placeinterventions which can help reduce the sufferings of theyouth. The youth agenda provided the most spirited debate onwhat needs to be done. At the end of the conferences, it wasclear that Kenya needed a youth reproductive health policy.<p>For a long time, it had not been possible to create a forum onyouth sexuality, but in March 1995 FPAK brought togetherpeople of divergent views on youth programmes in a one-dayworkshop. Among those represented were the Kenya Government(with keynote addresses by the Vice President and Ministerresponsible for Population issues and the Ministry ofEducation); the Catholic Church; Muslim leaders; and theNational Council of Churches of Kenya.<p>Though there was no general consensus, it was clear there wereseveral areas of shared interests.  It was agreed that regularforums of such nature be organized to encourage dialogue andfind ways and means of exploiting the common ground foradvancement in this matter.<p>In July 1995, the Kenya Youth Initiatives Project co-sponsored a national youth workshop for the National Councilof Churches of Kenya (NCCK) and this attracted over 100 youngpeople and over 400 senior clergy including bishops andmoderators of the Protestant Churches in Kenya. The workshop'sagenda centred on the role of NCCK in addressing reproductivehealth problems.  Presentations examined these problems asthey affect the welfare of the youth, and looked at thereligious standpoint on these matters. There were also opendiscussions in groups and agreement was reached that NCCKwould make a commitment to support the move to introduceFamily Life Education in schools and support pragmaticinterventions which aim at improving the health and well-beingof youth in Kenya. It was also emphasized that the memberchurches should play a more active role in promoting thesexual and reproductive health of young people. Indeed thechurches were requested to do more teaching and less preachingon these issues.<p>From an analysis of media coverage of youth reproductivehealth issues, it was apparent that either the mass media wasignoring or did not understand the seriousness of the issuesat hand. The coverage provided was scanty and did not provokethe readership of these publications to take any action.Forums to sensitize and brief the senior editors andjournalists of these publications were conducted and facts andfigures including implications and consequences of the youthsexual and reproductive health were presented and discussed.As a result the print media gave a commitment to giveprominence to these matters in a manner that would attract theattention of those who are in the position to initiaterelevant programmes and policies. It is evident that sincethese interventions there has been a dramatic shift towardfavourable coverage of these issues.<p>However, the project is aware that still greater efforts willbe needed to sustain the current momentum of a more receptiveenvironment in favour of youth sexuality and reproductivehealth information and services.<p><hr><p>©Copyright IPPF<br><font size=-1>Picture: &copy;IPPF </font><hr><img align=left src="../ippf_pix/ippf_logo2.gif"> <a href="index.html">PPC 1996/1 Contents</a><br><a href="../index.html">IPPF Home Page</a><hr></body></html>
