<html>
<HEADER>
<TITLE>DSA European Development Policy Study Group</TITLE>
</HEADER>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><img align=middle src="../images/eu.jpg"><p>
<h2>Report of the Inaugural Meeting<br>of the DSA European Development Policy Study Group<br>Manchester, 12 February 1996<p></h2>
</center>
<H4 align=center>Stephen Dearden, Department of Economics, Manchester Metropolitan University<br>Cavendish Street, Manchester M15 6BG, UK<br>Fax: (44)-161-2476302<br>E-mail: <a href="mailto:s.dearden@mmu.ac.uk">s.dearden@mmu.ac.uk</a></H4>
<hr>

Two papers were discussed.
<p>
<a href="lis_sum.htm">Ruth Lister</a> reviewed the performance of Lom&#233; IV and discussed the long-term prospects for this Coinvention. She noted the emphasis upon structural adjustment and the switch of priority from micro-economic projects to macro-economic change. Despite the greater importance of trade than aid to the ACP's, their trade preferences appear to have been of limited value and the margins of preference will significantly decline under the Uruguay Round.
<p>
Lom&#233; aid has been criticised for the slowness of its disbursement and both Stabex and Sysmin schemes are seen as having major inadequacies. Dr. Lister was also critical of the unclear relationship between the EU and the Member States and the weaknesses of the Commission's own internal organisation. Finally, she examined the Mid term Review and the "Horizon 2000" review of development cooperation policy. The failure of the latter to address the future of the Lom&#233; Convention is indicative of the lack of political support within the EU for its continuation. The role of France was seen as crucial in sustaining any support for its renewal.
<p>
Aidan Cox (ODI) reported on their recent <A HREF ="../../ecdpm/projects/aidsum.htm">comparative study of development aid</a> across the Member States of the EU. They found that the management costs of small projects were high, requiring six times as many staff. He argued that each Member State should specialise in its area of comparative advantage, but that this would require a common aid evaluation system. Unfortunately, their work suggests that all EU States share weaknesses in the same areas - eg. rural development. He was critical of the EU Commission for failing to address institutional issues, evaluate aid, or learn from experience. The Commission and other donors could also benefit from greater decentralisation of decision making and authority to their field officers.
<p>
He argued for a reorientation of EU aid towards the low income LDCs. This implies a reorientation of assistance towards South Asia and Sub-Saharan Africa away from countries such as Israel and Singapore and away from smaller LDCs such as Jamaica. The findings will be published in June 1996 by the ODI under the title - "How European Aid Works: A Comparison of Management Systems and Effectiveness."
<p>

<hr>
