<html><head><title>The Troubles We've Seen</title></head><body bgcolor="#000000" text="#A8A8A8"><center><img height=76 width=304 hspace=8 vspace=8 src="ophuls_pix/writing_war.gif"><img height=52 width=481 hspace=8 vspace=8 src="ophuls_pix/writing_troubles.gif"><center><img height=2 width=520 src="ophuls_pix/troubles_line.gif"></center><p><img height=120 width=197 hspace=8 vspace=8 src="ophuls_pix/killme.gif"><img height=120 width=196 hspace=8 vspace=8 src="ophuls_pix/typewriter.gif"><img height=120 width=198 hspace=8 vspace=8 src="ophuls_pix/running.gif"><img height=120 width=198 hspace=8 vspace=8 src="ophuls_pix/shooting.gif"><img height=120 width=197 hspace=8 vspace=8 src="ophuls_pix/bunker2.gif"><img height=120 width=198 hspace=8 vspace=8 src="ophuls_pix/ophuls.gif"><p><img height=2 width=520 src="ophuls_pix/troubles_line.gif"></center><center><h2>A four-hour epic study of war correspondents at work from French film-maker Marcel Ophuls</h2><h3><a href="ophuls.mov">Click here for a preview (Movie file, 1.2Mb)</a></h3><h3>First journey: 2 September at 9pm on BBC2 (UK only)<br>Second journey: 9 September at 9pm on BBC2 (UK only)</h3></center><p><center><img height=2 width=520 src="ophuls_pix/troubles_line.gif"></center><p>It was in 1977, while he was working for CBS-News, that Marcel Ophuls first conceived of <i>Veillees d'Armes - The Troubles We've Seen </i>. It would be, in his words, 'one of my international marathon documentaries - certain to be my last'.  <p>In this film Ophuls at first intended to reflect on the major conflicts of this century, showing how journalists were in the front line, both in the sense of sharing the danger of the action and in the sense of being the first witnesses to history. It was the struggle between power and the media - self-censorship, jingoism, the thirst for a scoop, the exploitation of suffering, the taste for showmanship - which would be Ophuls' subject. Unsurprisingly CBS, 'seeing my enthusiasm, were quick to back down'.<p><center><img height=2 width=520 src="ophuls_pix/troubles_line.gif"></center><p><img align=left height=120 width=197 hspace=12 vspace=8 src="ophuls_pix/bunker.gif">When Ophuls finally gathered enough finance to begin the project he was convinced that its centrepiece would be a report from some contemporary frontline, observing the journalists of our time in the full practice of their profession. It was what he called 'my coathanger principle' - a device about which to dispose his stories. He would travel to a conflict of our times, plot nothing but lean back and allow reality to come as it would. And on this material he would hang his story. In December 1992, still without much of the finance to mount the film, he boarded the night train to Munich with a cameraman friend. He was bound for Sarajevo as, he subsequently confessed, a naive tourist going to a reputedly very dangerous place without much idea of what was going on.<br clear=left><p>As the film emerged from the cutting room, it was clear that Ophuls' coathanger had become something much more substantial. The contemporary no longer illustrated the past. It was the history - the anecdotes about Capa during the Spanish Civil War or Hemmingway during D-Day - which now served the present. Ophuls has made a film about the seige of Sarajevo, the place where he discovered censorship is a simple matter of shooting journalists in the street. From it he has drawn his lessons about the life and death of truth in the line of fire.<p><center><img height=2 width=520 src="ophuls_pix/troubles_line.gif"></center><p><img align=left height=120 width=197 hspace=12 vspace=8 src="ophuls_pix/inn.gif">Ophuls visited Sarajevo five times during 1993 and much of what has eventually become the two films takes place in the city's Holiday Inn. He accompanies the <b>BBC's John Simpson,</b> the <b>New York Times' John Burns</b> and <b>FR2's Stephane Manier</b> on their sorties through the city and into the hills beyond. There are charged encounters with others within the hotel itself - with <b>Paul Marchand, a French radio journalist</b> who despises the armoured-car safety of his colleagues and with <b>Marine Laroche-Joubert</b> who is bitterly critical of French newscasters safe in their studios and earning five times as much<img align=right height=140 width=196 hspace=12 vspace=8 src="ophuls_pix/burns.gif"> as she does. And there are Ophuls' own forays into the city's life and death - the journalist crouching in the sniper-scarred wrek of the city's newspaper offices and the actor whose legs were blown away but who is confident he will again play Shakespeare. Ophuls even goes out of his way to interview <b>Serb president Slobodan Milosevic</b> and </b>Bosnian Serb Vice-President Nikola Koljevic.</b> There are, besides, conversations with <b>veteran war correspondent Martha Gellhorn</b> (who tells of stowing away on a D-Day boat but having her material scooped by Ernest Hemmingway) and with editors, cameramen, photographers and reporters who covered conflicts in Palestine, the Gulf and elsewhere.<br clear=right><p><center><img height=2 width=520 src="ophuls_pix/troubles_line.gif"></center><p><img align=left height=137 width=199 hspace=12 vspace=8 src="ophuls_pix/laughing.gif">But the heart of these films is a restless odyssey in the bitter Sarajevo cold through the sharp moral conflicts which beset the coverage of war. Ophuls confronts the seriousness of the conflict by reflecting on the ironies he finds around himself. Are these men and women in it for fun? Does reporting make any difference? Doesn't it simply feed off itself - making the death of a journalist headline news while the daily suffering of everyone else is unnoticed? Isn't there something ridiculous about men and women at the heart of a terrible seige who find time to gripe about their pay? Can the suffering of war's victims be faithfully understood by professionals who wear flakjackets and ride amoured cars and who take a plane for Thailand when their duty is over?<p><center><img height=2 width=520 src="ophuls_pix/troubles_line.gif"></center><p>For Ophuls the Frenchman, the reporting of war is also a challenge to the integrity of the TV networks at home. With characteristically boyish humour he exposes the cosy relationship between French TV chiefs and politicians, the empty showmanship of new anchormen, the superficiality  of the Paris editors and the meanness of channels which pour cash into gameshows but who will not purchase any protection for crews in sniper alley.<p>Ophuls' sympathy in <i>The Troubles We've Seen </i> emerges from this kaleidoscope of experience. His anger is for those who gloss over suffering. His wit breaks out in absurd yet pointed quotations from the cinema in which his early years were spent. 'All God's Children Got Guns' sing the Marx brothers in one moment among many in this pair of films which could have come from no other <i>auteur.</i> But above all it is the generosity and the courage of the reporters in the Holiday Inn which stays in the mind. <p><center><img height=2 width=520 src="ophuls_pix/troubles_line.gif"></center><p><h2>Marcel Ophuls</h2> <img align=right height=135 width=150 hspace=8 vspace=8 src="ophuls_pix/marcel.gif">Marcel was born in Frankfurt in 1927, but his family fled the Nazis - in 1933 to Paris and in 1941 to the States. He returned to Paris in 1950 but has remained on the move ever since. His first work was in the cinema - once in <i>Lola Montes </i> as Assistant Director to his father Max. He has produced radio plays, worked as a news reporter and made documentaries in France, Germany and the States. His breakthrough came with <i>The Sorrow and the Pity, </i> seen around the world but only broadcast in France twelve years after its completion. It was followed by an account of the Troubles in Northern Ireland in the ealy 1970s and <i>The Memory of Justice </i> on the Nuremburg Trials. <i>Hotel Terminus </i> was made after his return to France in 1979 and was as much a film about Ophuls himself as about his subject, <b>Klaus Barbie.</b> It was described as uncompromising, laughing in the face of horror, outraged at the silence which covers the uprooted, the stateless and the innocent children.<br><br clear=left><center><img height=2 width=520 src="ophuls_pix/troubles_line.gif"></center><p><img align=left width=104 height=54 hspace=12 src="../owo_logos/online_logo_border.gif"> <a href="tv_current.html"> This week's TV</a><br>  <a href="radio_current.html"> This week's radio</a><br><a href="../index.html"> Home Page</a><br clear=left><br></body></html>
</DOC>
