<html><head><title>Amnestys' letter to the NGO Forum on women</title><!!keys: ></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#oooooo" link="#238e23" vlink="#4a766e"><img src="amnesty_pix/amnesty_logo.gif"><br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="amnesty.html">  Amnesty International</i></a><hr><h2>Letter from Amnesty International to the NGO Forum on Women 1 September 1995</h2><h3>Members of the Facilitating Committee<br>NGO Forum on Women</h3><font size=+1>Dear Members,</font><p>The NGO Forum at this World Conference on Women provides an historic opportunity for women from around the world to join together to achieve the goal of the conference -- Equality by the Year 2000.<p>The hopes and expectations of the activists at this conference are especially high since this is the first world conference on women in a decade, and as such offers a chance to dramatically change the situation of women as we enter the next century. <p>The debates and activities organized by the women's groups themselves will stimulate an important debate around the crucial issues facing women today. The caucus discussions around the Platform of Action will hopefully lead to a strong and clear demand from the Forum to the official conference on the action that is needed to improve the lives of women internationally. <p>As we enter the third day of the NGO Forum, however, there are still serious questions being raised and problems encountered by those attending the Forum. Until those questions are put to rest and the problems resolved, I fear that the real issues at the Forum will not get the attention they rightly deserve.<p>The first issue is the unhealthy atmosphere created at the Forum by the heavy security presence.<p>Conflicting messages continue to be sent to the organizations at the Forum: we have been told alternately that demonstrations are allowed only in the schoolyard in Huairou, that demonstrations are allowed anywhere in the Forum compound, and that regardless of where demonstrations are held they won't be allowed if they are deemed by the authorities to be "anti-China".<p>Other examples that Amnesty International and other delegates to the Forum have experienced include: workshops being monitored by security officials who take notes and photographs of participants and have attempted to confiscate workshop materials. These conditions at the Forum have been accompanied by some delegates being followed by security officials within the forum compound, and heavy and constant security presence and surveillance in hotels, which extends to participants not being allowed to receive guests. <p>This presence is often described as necessary to ensure the safety of participants at the Forum; however, the effect is not to create a sense of security but to instill a deep feeling of insecurity among Forum delegates. Our fear is that these intimidating tactics will not allow participants to exchange views freely and debate fully the issues that have brought them to this conference from around the world. And we have to ask - is this extreme level of security really necessary for a conference that can in no way threaten the security of the state. <p>The second issue is of access to the Forum. While we understand that it is not the role of the NGO Forum organizers to grant visas to participants, it is still astonishing that only 26,000 visas were apparently granted out of some 36,000 applicants. In the past few days leading up to the start of the Forum, we have heard many stories of participants being frustrated in their attempts to get visas and others simply not receiving them. <p>It is our view that the NGO Forum should seek and obtain from the Chinese authorities detailed explanations regarding those participants who were denied the right to participate in this world gathering. It is indeed regrettable that those women at the grassroots who have been at the forefront of all the advances achieved in the fields covered by this Forum have been denied the opportunity to share experiences with their sisters. <p>And finally, the issue of facilities, organization, and access to information through independent newspapers. For two days running, a significant number of Forum participants have been excluded from joining in key events because of inadequate facilities. First the opening ceremony and then the opening plenary session. Participants have told us about rooms that are too small and equipment that is faulty or inadequate. And facilities and access for people with disabilities are wholly inadequate.<p>I am setting down these concerns at the start of the Forum in the hope that you will be able to address them quickly. Until they are solved, we fear that the crucial issues that must be debated by the women at this Forum will be overshadowed by anger, apprehension and confusion. <p>In yesterday's issue of Forum 95 you were quoted as saying that "protesters are free to use any area in the forum site as the rules of the United Nations demands, and we will go by that". As well you offered assurances that freedom of expression will be guaranteed and that clarification of this issue has been obtained from the Chinese government. <p>I would urge you to do everything within your power to ensure that the opportunity for real freedom of expression prevails at the Forum to ensure the vital contribution of everyone at this conference.<p>Sincerely,<p>Pierre Sane<br>Secretary General<p><hr>©Copyright: Amnesty International September 1995<hr> <a href="index.html"><img src="amnesty_pix/amnesty_logo2.gif"> Amnesty International</a><hr></body></html>
