<header>
<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Europe</title>
</HEADER>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><IMG align=middle SRC  = "../images/dk.jpg"><h3>Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy in Denmark
</h3></center>

This information is drawn from the report of a survey (1993-1994) carried out by ECDPM on behalf of the
National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) of the Netherlands.
<br> 
<h5><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/nar.jpg" border=1> Source: Kooij, A. and R. Mevis. 1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen European Countries</i>. The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The report is available from: NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The Hague, the Netherlands.
</h5>
<hr>
<h3>Contents:</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org">Organisation of Danish Development Cooperation</a>
<li><a href="#ins">Institutional Framework</a>
<li><a href="#adv">Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</a>
<li><a href="#ngo">Non-State Sources of Advice</a>
<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"><IMG align=top SRC = "../images/acro.jpg"></a></a>
</ul>
<p>

<a name="org"></a><hr><h3>Organisation of Danish Development Cooperation</h3>

Danish official development assistance, which started in the early 1960s, was based on political, economic,
and charitable motives. According to an opinion poll of February 1993 80 per cent of the population has a
positive attitude towards development assistance. The Government is in the process of expanding the support
base for development cooperation in Danish society. For cooperation in policy formulation, the organisation
of aid and its implementation contacts are being built up between the Government, business and industry,
trade unions, voluntary and professional organisations, research institutions and public sector institutions. 
<p>
Denmark's net official development assistance amounted to US $ 1.392 million in 1992, which was 1.02 per
cent of GNP, increasing slightly to 1.03 per cent in 1993. Since the 1960s disbursements of development aid
have been divided rather equally between bilateral and multilateral channels. In 1992 multilateral aid
constituted 41 per cent of the ODA. An additional 6 per cent of ODA was channelled through the EU. In
1993 ODA will amount to 0,97 per cent of GNP.
<p>
Development policy is an integral part of Danish foreign policy. In the light of global political changes,
Denmark is in the process of evaluating its experiences and adjusting its international development policy
and the organisation of its aid programme. The main objectives of a new policy are laid down in the 1994
strategy plan 'A Developing World, Strategy for Danish Development Policy towards the Year 2000'. 
<p>
Since DANIDA's (Danish International Development Assistance) Plan of Action of 1988, Denmark is in the
process of reducing the number of programme countries from 67 to 20 in 1994. Over half of the bilateral
aid is directed towards Africa (1992). Aid to Asia has declined in 1992, while allocations for Latin
America, for non-country specific aid and for receiving refugees in Denmark have risen. 
<p>
Per programme country a long term strategy is to be elaborated. In 1989 Parliament choose three new
criteria for the selection of programme countries: the potential for poverty alleviation, the potential to
influence development policy, and the potential for Danish business interests.
<p>
<a name="ins"><hr><h3>Institutional Framework</h3></a>
<p>
Danish official development assistance is based on the 1971 International Development Cooperation Act and
has since been laid down in many strategy and policy papers. Since 1990 the Danish Ministry of Foreign
Affairs has been divided into two separate pillars: a North Group and a South Group (the latter covering the
developing countries). Thus reflecting a geographical integration of all relevant international cooperation
components rather than the traditional functional one. DANIDA ceased to exist, although the name is still
used for the South group. The regional sub-divisions in the two groups are responsible for all aspects of
Denmark's bilateral relations with a given country: political, aid, economic, and commercial relations. Since
the beginning of 1993, the Ministry is not only headed by a Minister of Foreign Affairs but also by a
Minister for Development Cooperation. The Minister of Foreign Affairs is responsible for EU policies,
including EU development aid policies. The administration is not only responsible for policy formulation,
but also for implementation. 
<p>
Within the South Group in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs a Division for the General Coordination of
Development Assistance is responsible for policy planning. The Ministry of Finance also participates in the
formulation of Denmark's aid policy. Additionally, under the Environmental Framework arrangements have
been made with the Ministry of Environment for the policy development and funding of environmental
protection assistance to specific countries. It is not known wether these arrangements have been finalised,
nor into what detail. Priorities for the distribution and the use of the funds of all Danish international
cooperation will be worked out annually by a interministerial committee.
<p>
In March 1994 the new comprehensive strategy plan, A Developing World, Strategy for Danish
Development Policy towards the Year 2000, was presented and approved by Parliament. A summary is
translated into English. Sector, country and overall policy papers generally are published and translated into
English and made available to a wide public.
<p>
Evaluations are conducted frequently, on projects and programmes, themes and such components as NGO
development cooperation and on multilateral aid. Many evaluations are conducted by external consultants
and firms. Feedback to DANIDA's operational units is done through informal discussions. Since 1982 a
relatively small evaluation unit was created within DANIDA. Its autonomy has recently been strengthened.
Evaluation reports are being summarised and published in order to inform the Danish public.
<p>
<hr><a name="adv"><h3>Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</h3></a>
<p>
There are two advisory bodies for development cooperation policies: the Council for International
Development Cooperation (R&#229;det), which focuses on policy and the Board for International
Development Cooperation (Styrelsen), that focuses on policies and projects. This is a very common structure
in Scandinavian countries. The members of both bodies are appointed by the Minister for Development
Cooperation. Council and Board have a common secretariat at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs in the person
of an official of the Policy Planning Division. The secretaryship of both Council and Board is a part time
occupation. Results of the discussions in the Council and the Board are not published.
<p>
Both Council and Board are established according to the 1971 International Development Act. The formal
mandate of the Council is to follow the Board's activities.
<p>
<h4>The Council for International Development Cooperation</h4>
<p>
The Council has 75 members, appointed for three year periods. They represent all sections in Danish society
that have an interest in development cooperation: representatives of church-organisations, industry and
agriculture, trade unions, the sciences, banking, development NGOs, ministries, as well as individual
experts on development cooperation, and members of Parliament.
<p>
In addition to following the Board's activities, the Council also is formally appointed to discuss the annual
budget before it is sent to Parliament. Furthermore the Council discusses policy plans in their final stage
before they are sent to Parliament, and it reviews development activities on the basis of the formulated
policies. The 1994 Strategy Plan for the Year 2000 for instance was discussed with the Council before it
was officially published and sent to Parliament.
<p>
The Council meets about six times a year, of which one meeting is spent on discussing the annual report of
the Board, and another on discussing the annual budget for development cooperation. The Council is a body
for consultation, that discusses policy matters with the Minister; it does not write recommendations.
Council-meetings are chaired by the Minster for Development Cooperation. The press can be present at
these meetings. Amongst other things, the Council appears to function as a platform for discussion with all
parties involved in development cooperation. 
<p>
<h4>The Board for International Development Cooperation</h4>
<p>
The Board has nine members, appointed for three year periods. Members are representatives of the private
sector, business, industry, and consultancy, as well as representatives of NGOs, and the research
community. They are appointed on the basis of their personal capacity.
<p>
The mandate of the Board is to assess those projects and programmes of DANIDA that exceed 5 million
Danish Krona. Additionally it discusses development cooperation policies, in a similar way as the Council
does. Like the Council, the Board receives policy plans in their final stage before they are sent to
Parliament. The Board meets at least once a month. It cannot take up subjects at its own initiative.
Otherwise than the Council, the Board appears to be quite involved in the internal administrative process of
handling aid projects and programmes. 
<p>
Parliament has a standing Committee for Foreign Affairs that also deals with development cooperation
matters. Parliament as well as the Committee are very actively involved in development cooperation.
<p>
Until the beginning of the 1990s a Nordic Council of the Ministers of Development Cooperation of
Denmark, Finland, Iceland, Norway and Sweden met bi-annually to discuss policy issues. Adjacent to these
meetings advisory meetings were organised of parliamentarians and researchers from the five countries. One
of these advisory meetings was a seminar Human Rights and Democracy held in Helsinki. The proceedings
were published in English. It is not known whether these meetings will be continued.
<p>
<HR><h3>Non-State Sources of Advice</h3></a>
<p>
In 1992 almost 20 per cent of the Danish bilateral programme was disbursed through NGOs. The eight
largest organisations received 86 per cent. The Ministry maintains an active policy dialogue with the NGO-
community, amongst others on the increasing involvement of Danish Industry, the financing of the reception
of refugees in Denmark and of increasing emergency aid. 
<p>
According to a 1991 OECD survey in Denmark ten institutes qualify as 'Development Research and
Training Institutes'. In 1969 Parliament established by act of law the Centre for Development Research
(CDR), based in Copenhagen. It is an independent institute financed by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. The
Centre undertakes many consultancy studies and research work for the Ministry. 
<p>
Denmark also has a Research Council. It advises the Evaluation and Research Department of the South
Group in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs on research and evaluation. The Council has 15 members who are
appointed for a two year period. 
<p>
The Danish business community will become increasingly involved in the formulation of development
strategies and the identification of programmes amongst others through annual meetings with DANIDA.
<p>
<hr>
<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="../images/logo.gif"></a>
<i>Updated on November 7, 1995</i><br>
