<a href="index.html"><img border=0 align=right width=183 height=163 src="pix/sublogo.gif"></a>
<small>The material that follows has been provided by <b><a href="../index.html">International Institute for Environment and Development (IIED)</a></b></small>
<hr>


<h3>Forests and EC Aid: an agenda for sustaining both trees and people<p>EC Aid and Sustainable Development Briefing Paper, No. 10, 1996</h3>



<I>Since 1992, international action aimed at improving forest management has accelerated. This Briefing Paper looks at forest problems and provides an outline of the policy framework and strategies for the EC’s development cooperation to forests</I>. 
<p>
<H3>Why are forests important?</H3>

Forests provide many benefits. Rural populations in many countries depend on forest resources for part of their livelihoods, and poorer people among them do so in particular. There are also national and international demands for forest goods and services such as watershed protection, timber and non-timber products, biological diversity and carbon storage. Forests thus have multiple values, many of which cannot be provided by any other land use. Yet these values are being undermined. 
 
<H3>What are the problems?</H3>

Forests everywhere are in trouble. Deforestation in tropical forests is calculated by the FAO to have proceeded throughout the 1980s at an average rate of 15 million hectares (0.8 percent of forest cover) a year. Millions of additional hectares were degraded by inappropriate logging practices and fuelwood collection. Temperate forests are seriously degraded by pollution and over-harvesting. Whilst these immediate effects are on trees, the problems caused are for people. Globally, the main physical forest problems are:
<ul>
<li>Declining quantity and quality of forests. This is because wood, fuel and food are being harvested at rates faster than forest regeneration; because remaining growing stock is often poorly managed; and because many forests are being cleared to make way for other land uses.
<p>
<li>Environmental degradation of forest areas. Forest exploitation and clearance can create interlinked problems; notably soil erosion, watershed destabilisation and micro-climatic change. These threaten the soil and water base for agriculture. Industrial air pollution, particularly common in some temperate forests, also reduces forest health.
<p>
<li>Loss of biodiversity.These problems are contributing to a rapid reduction in ecosystem, species and genetic diversity. This lowers the world’s biological potential for improving material, food and medicine production. With tropical forests being perhaps the major repository of biodiversity, forest abuse in tropical regions is causing particular concern.
<p>
<li>Climate change. Forests play a major role in carbon storage. It is probable that the cumulative effect of global forest loss and environmental degradation will be a net contribution to regional and global climate change. This could bring many problematic side-effects: sea level rise, risks to food supply, declining productivity of soils and the quality and quantity of fresh water, inviability of current land uses and protected areas, and human health problems.
</ul>

<H3>Who are they problems for?</H3>

Replacement or alteration of forests by other land uses has produced economic and social benefits in many countries. In particular, the clearance of forest for agriculture has been deliberate and has been looked upon as advancing possibilities for development, either by increasing food security or providing cash crops to fuel income growth. Yet there are costs. The problem is that those who reap the benefits generally do not pay the costs. The main costs for people are:
<ul>
<li>Loss of cultural assets and knowledge. The culture and knowledge of many peoples, which are not always documented, and which have evolved through long periods of nurturing the forest, are diminishing as forest area, access, and traditional rights are reduced.
<p>
<li>Loss of livelihood. Forest loss and degradation are affecting the livelihoods of forest-dependent peoples - particularly poorer groups who may not have significant agricultural land, and who depend on forests for “social security”. 
<p>
<li>Rising inequality. Increasing concentration of control and access to forest wealth in fewer hands is removing development options for the majority of people in many countries. Those who lose their forest livelihoods and become marginalised may be forced to create social and economic problems elsewhere, such as in cities. 
</ul><p>
Each country, and each forest within it, may experience a different combination of forest-related problems. It is people in developing countries who bear the brunt of these problems.Yet the wasting of forest assets is occurring on an international scale, and the causes of forest problems are to be found at all levels: local, national and global.

<H3>What are the causes?</H3>

It is important to distinguish the direct agents from the underlying causes of forest problems. The direct agents which bring about problems for tropical forests include: slash-and-burn cultivation by small-scale farmers; settled agriculture and cash crop production; clearance and burning for grazing; timber harvesting; woodfuel harvesting; clearance for forest plantations; infrastructure construction (mining, dams, roads, etc).
<P>
Often, several factors work together. For example, road development encourages timber exploitation, which opens the forest for agricultural settlement and fuelwood salvaging. About half of all logged tropical forests are eventually cleared by farmers. The importance of these agents may differ according to regions. In Africa, the major agent of deforestation is shifting agriculture after timber harvesting; in Latin America, agriculture often precedes logging operations; in South-East Asia, logging may be the central agent of deforestation due to its intensity. 
<P>
The root causes of forest problems are more complex and entrenched. These are the policy, market and institutional “signals”, to which the direct agents of deforestation and forest degradation respond. Many signals arise at national level, either within the forestry  sector or outside - notably in agriculture and industrial development. Or they are a result of national macro-economic policies. Other signals are set at local levels, often due to fundamental inequities in rights and access to resources. Further signals are set internationally, such as trade policies, debt and structural adjustment requirements.
<P>
These signals either “push” groups into the forest, by creating difficult economic or social conditions outside the forest; or they “pull” groups into the forest, by attracting them with excess profits. Many policies and market conditions effectively undervalue forests, and do not provide long-term incentives for the groups “pushed” or “pulled” into forests to look after forest assets. 

<H3>Making the transition to sustainable forests</H3>

The challenge is to tackle the root causes of forest problems, and create the conditions that encourage the recognition, and management, of forest assets with multiple values. The transition to sustainable forest management requires action at international, national and local levels. Since the late 1980s, the EC and its Member States have made a number of internal and international commitments to support that transition in developing countries.

<H3>What are the EC’s international commitments?</H3>

During the 1980s the EC and Member States were heavily involved in development and support of two major international forestry initiatives: the International Tropical Timber Agreement (ITTA) and the Tropical Forestry Action Programme (TFAP). Support has been given to a wide range of national initiatives within the TFAP framework.. 
<P>
The 1992 Rio Earth Summit produced a surge of forest-related commitments for the EC and its Member States, including the Rio Declaration on Environment and Development, the Agenda 21 action programme, the Forest Principles, the Framework Convention on Climate Change, and the Convention on Biological Diversity. In 1994, the EC signed the Desertification Convention. 
<P>
The non-legally binding Forest Principles represent, for the first time, a global consensus on all forests, and not just those of the tropics. They constitute a political document, affirming general values. They call for sustainable forest management of all types of forest, with conservation and development being accorded equal importance. The Principles are not an operational plan, and need to be interpreted in conjunction with Agenda 21, notably Chapter 11 on Deforestation. 
<P>
The Biodiversity Convention requires large areas of forest to be set aside for conservation, and provides for benefit-sharing of any exploitation of forest biodiversity. The Climate Change Convention emphasises the value of carbon storage in existing forests, the sequestration of carbon in growing forests, and the dangers of deforestation. Various Joint Implementation schemes have followed, in which forest conservation and afforestation is paid for by power-generation utilities to offset some of the environmental costs of CO2 generation (see Briefing Paper No. 6 on Climate). The Desertification Convention calls for national action plans which recognise the importance of trees and local participation in addressing dryland degradation (see Briefing Papers <A HREF="bp4_gb.html">4</A> and <A HREF="bp5_gb.html">5</A>). 
<P>
In 1995, the Commission for Sustainable Development (CSD), set up following Rio to oversee implementation of Agenda 21, established an ad hoc Intergovernmental Panel on Forests, with the objective to promote multi-disciplinary action at the international level consistent with the Forest Principles. The EC and its Member States are involved in many discussion and negotiation processes which feed in to the Panel. The IPF is composed of government representatives, with inter-governmental and NGO groups as observers and will report to the CSD in 1997.
<P>
The second ITTA, came in to force at the beginning of 1996. All EU countries have indicated that they will ratify ITTA II, which calls for sustainable management of forests and trade from sustainable sources by the year 2000.  

<H3>The EC’s policy response</H3>

The Commission’s Communication to the Council of October 1989 on the conservation of tropical forests set out the main elements of an EC strategy in this field, while the May 1990 Development Council Resolution on tropical forests established a basis for the use of european development instruments in tropical forest conservation. The European Parliament has exerted continual pressure on the EC and Member States to provide more and better development assistance for tropical forests, and in 1991 the Budget Line for tropical forests was established. Conservation and sustainable forest management are also recurring themes in the new generation of bilateral and regional cooperation agreements with developing countries in Asia and Latin America (ALA). 
<p>
Two developments in late 1995 bring new commitments on tropical forests: 
<ul>
<li>The signing of the revised Fourth Lomé Convention with a Protocol on Sustainable Management of Forest Resources. Lomé IV identifies deforestation as a serious problem and points to the need for joint action. The Protocol establishes a number of priority areas for assistance including: biodiversity conservation, sustainable management of production forests, reafforestation, local capacity building and the development of buffer zones. Particular attention is given to the importance which timber products play in the economies of the ACP States.
<p>
<li>Adoption by the Council of the Regulation on Operations to Promote Tropical Forests. The Regulation includes priorities similar to the new Lomé Forests Protocol and provides a legal basis for the execution of the allocations of the Budget Line supporting initiatives in tropical forest areas.
</ul><p>
Following a concerted process of strategy development, the EC is currently preparing a new Communication to address the developments and changes of national and international emphasis since 1989. The following section outlines strategic areas likely to be reflected in the new Communication.

<A NAME="fig"><H3>How can the EC support developing countries?</H3></A>

Better management of forests should not wait for the outcome of debates around the world on what constitutes “sustainable forest management”. Neither should it wait for all framework conditions at country level to be present before taking action. What is needed in most countries is “sustainable-enough” forestry, which demands choosing what should be sustained - and for whom - and moving towards it through processes which identify and build on policies and practices that work. (<A HREF="fig10e.html">See Box 1</A>).
<p>
In programming and planning for EC development cooperation, the following main approaches should be considered:
<ul>
<li><I>Country-driven processes and wider involvement in decision-making</I>
Support is often needed for processes of country-specific planning for forests and land use. These include: identification of forest stakeholders and their perspectives; development of institutions, e.g. round tables or permanent commissions; and methodologies for reconciliation of competing claims and building consensus.
<p>
<li><I>Recognising capacity and building institutional options</I>
Potential capacity to deliver better forest management is often poorly recognised. Organisational options which build on negotiated roles for government and non-governmental sectors need support, as do forestry training approaches which produce a new kind of forester - one who can deal with the multiple dimensions of forests and can mediate between different stakeholder interests.
<p>
<li><I>Reorienting influences from outside the forestry sector</I>
Support is needed for activities which integrate inter-sectoral issues and try to ensure that better forest management is complemented by such influences as: macroeconomic policy; agricultural pricing and marketing; energy policies and forest land settlement schemes.
<p>
<li><I>Working policy processes and instruments</I>
Support is needed for processes and institutions which link policy with on-the-ground realities, and for analysis of market instruments, regulations and taxes which effectively communicate the scarcity and value of forest resources, and the full costs of forest use.
<p>
<li><I>Securing rights and devolving management</I>
Government departments often have theoretical control of a huge area of forest, but have few resources to manage it. Modes of support which secure the rights and promote the forest management abilities of farmers and forest communities are needed. These include collaborative approaches at local levels amongst government agencies, communities and the private sector.
<p>
<li><I>Complementary land uses</I>
Other land use systems can be used in achieving forestry objectives. The range of forest values can be spread over the forest and agricultural landscape through support for land use planning and sustainable agricultural systems at local level.
<p>
<li><I>Better operational management of forests</I>
Governments may need support for establishing a national permanent forest estate. This does not have to be all under government ownership, and assistance may be needed to allow negotiation of appropriate degrees of control by state and non-state actors. Natural forest management may be appropriate on previously logged or degraded forests, and priority of support should be given to community-based and controlled initiatives.
<p>
<li><I>Integrating biodiversity conservation with development</I>
In many countries, natural forests are limited in area and many should become “protection” forest. Yet protected areas are likely to remain viable only if they are supported within a broader integration of conservation with development. This may involve the linkage of protection areas to spatial and temporal zones for development of non-consumptive and sustainable consumptive enterprises. 
<p>
<li><I>Reforestation and on-farm trees</I>
Plantations are a complement to, not substitute for, natural forests. Support linked to plantation exercises should aim to secure social and environmental benefits through outgrower schemes, natural forests integrated in plantation mosaics, and multiple-species plantations. Support for trees in farming systems is usually best done through provision of advice, credit and infrastructure, with management and marketing decisions left to farmers. 
<p>
<li><I>Local processing, trading and forest certification </I>
Local processing initiatives based on timber from well-managed sources may be important to stimulate economic development and employment prospects. Support may also be needed for developing consensus on market-based incentives, including certification, which can provide both improved market security and raised standards of forest management if carefully developed.
<p>
<li><I>Making information and research more useful</I>
Information and research for better forest management has been weak in many countries, particularly at the policy, legal and institutional levels. Support is needed for a mix of good science, economics and participatory approaches to obtain and integrate information about forests and forest values with policy and planning cycles.
</ul><p>
The EC and its Member States have played major roles in international initiatives to combat deforestation and define what sustainable forest management entails. Europe has also traditionally  provided the largest aid flows in the field of forestry. The new agenda of broader participation in setting goals, of redefining roles, and of building on the forest management capacities of a wider range of players, is a challenge for which collaboration in Europe has great potential to address.
<p>
<I>This Briefing Paper was prepared by James Mayers, Research Associate in the Forestry and Land Use Programme of IIED. He has worked for 10 years on projects and policy processes which foster collaboration for forest management. The Forestry and Land Use Programme undertakes research with partners in developing countries on policy, capacity and information for sustainable forest management.</I>






<p>
<hr>

