<html><head><title>IIED European Programme - EC Aid and Sustainable Development</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#009999" alink="#999999" vlink="#99CCCC"><a href="index.html"><img border=0 align=right width=183 height=163 src="pix/sublogo.gif"></a><small>The material that follows has been provided by <b><a href="../index.html">International Institute for Environment and Development (IIED)</a></b></small><hr><h3>The Desertification Convention: the strategic agenda for the EU<p>EC Aid and Sustainable Development Briefing Paper, No. 4, 1995</h3>

<I>For the last 20 years, the international community has struggled to provide answers to an often misunderstood phenomenon known as ‘desertification’.  In October 1994, a new International Convention on Desertification (ICD) was signed.
<p>
This is the first in a series of briefings designed to stimulate reflection by European policymakers on the challenges and opportunities provided by the Convention.   Future briefings on the ICD could include: promoting participation in natural resource management; decentralisation and land tenure; climate change and desertification; national planning and programming; and European Union best practice in development cooperation on desertification and policy options
</I>. 
<p>
<H3>Introduction: Drylands and Desertification</H3>

Drylands make up a third of the world’s surface and provide a home to some 900 million people.  The cradle of ancient civilisations and at the hub of trading systems through the ages, they have also been the source of many valuable crops and animals. Dryland regions have always been subject to variable rainfall and drought, bringing years of plenty followed by years of want. Over the past two decades, there has been rising concern about longer term degradation in  dryland regions which would render them less able to support life in future. This degradation has been termed ‘desertification’.
<p>
Desertification includes a range of problems, such as loss of soils through water and wind erosion; declining soil fertility; a loss of vegetative cover; increasing vulnerability to drought; and a general reduction in the diversity of plant and animal life.  Set against this vulnerability to degradation, drylands systems are also recognised as being remarkably resilient to wide extremes in rainfall and resource use.  
<p>
The incidence of dryland degradation and of resilience varies greatly from place to place, according to the nature of the resources in question, pressures on their use, and institutions for their management.  This local variability is the reason why new approaches to combatting desertification are focused strongly at the local level.  
<p>
As will be explained below, desertification is not about advancing deserts.  While sand dune movement can pose a problem in certain sites, the main threat faced by dryland regions is not at the desert margin but in farming areas where heavy pressures on land can lead to the progressive decline in productive potential.

<H3>The ICD: a new start?</H3>

Over the past 20 years, international efforts to tackle the problems of desertification have had mixed success.  Following the UN Conference on Desertification, held in Nairobi 1977,  a number of plans of action to combat desertification were established at national and regional levels.  However, these plans had little or no impact on the ground, and were often no more than a list of projects seeking funds.  It is now recognised that successful dryland management depends on providing local land users with incentives and firm rights over their resources. Getting national policy right is much more important than preparing detailed plans that will not be implemented.  Hence, the ICD suggests a number of policy changes needed to achieve more sustainable resource use, such as increased security of land tenure.

<H3>Negotiating a Global Convention</H3>

The International Convention to combat Desertification was first proposed during the preparatory committees for the UN Conference on Environment and Development (UNCED), held in Rio, June 1992.  The call for the Convention evolved from the dissatisfaction felt by many African countries at the way in which their particular concerns had been treated during preparations for UNCED.  As a result, a formal commitment was made at Rio to negotiate and agree a Global Convention to combat Desertification by June 1994.  While global in scope and intention, it was acknowledged that particular attention would need to be paid to Africa, because of the poverty of many dryland African countries and lack of alternative livelihoods for their peoples.
<p>
<center>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<tr><td><center><h4>Global Environmental Agreements</h4></center>
<p>
These agreements are legally binding.  Signatories cede power to an international body, allowing the monitoring of actions covered by the agreement, and the imposition of sanctions should the conditions of the agreement not be met.
</td></tr></table>
</center>
<p>
After five sessions of the International Negotiating Committee, the Convention text was agreed in June 1994, along with four regional annexes, a resolution on urgent action for Africa, and a resolution on the interim period prior to the ICD’s entry in force.  The Convention was signed in Paris in October 1994 by over 80 states, including 13 of the 15 Member States of the newly expanded EU, as well as the European Community.  
<p>
The interim period will last from June 1994 until the first meeting of the conference of the parties, probably some time in early 1997.  The reason for this interim period of two to three years is due to the time taken for national governments to ratify their adherence to the convention by passing legislation through their national parliaments.  A minimum of fifty such ratifications is needed for the ICD to enter into force.  The first COP will be held six months after the fiftieth ratification of the Convention is notified to the UN.
<p>
During the interim period, it is planned to hold several meetings bringing together representatives of national governments and international agencies.  It is unclear what agenda such meetings will follow, given that the negotiations of the ICD were completed in June 1994.  The first of these interim meetings was held in January 1995 in New York, the second in August 1995 in Nairobi, and the next is scheduled for early 1996.

<H3>Desertification or dryland degradation? </H3>

The term ‘desertification’ has had a troubled history, and has acquired a range of meanings that have served to confuse discussion of what is at stake. Desertification was defined at the Rio Earth Summit as:
<ul>
<I>land degradation in arid, semi-arid, and dry sub-humid areas resulting from climatic variations and human activities</I>
</ul><p>
Hence, desertification means dryland degradation, and they both include a number of processes which lead to the impoverishment of soils and vegetation, such as through erosion of soils, and loss of soil fertility.  Both human and climatic factors are important in such degradation processes, the long dry season and occasional droughts rendering more difficult the recovery of dryland ecosystems.  
<p>
<center>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<tr><td><center><h4>The Convention Document</h4></center>
<p>
The main Convention text is made up of 40 articles spread across 32 pages.  Six main sections cover:<ul><li>Introduction and definitions (Articles 1-3)<li>General obligations of different parties, the priority given to Africa, and the ICD’s relationship to other conventions (Articles 4-8)<li>Action programmes, scientific and technical cooperation and supporting measures, including financial provisions and mechanisms (Articles 9-21)<li>Institutions for implementing the convention (Articles 22-25)<li>Procedures for implementation, settlement of disputes, amendments, and voting rights (Articles 26-32)<li>Final provisions, concerning signature, ratification, entry into force and withdrawals (Articles 33-40)</ul><p>There are four regional annexes of varying length and complexity treating: Africa, Asia, Latin America, and the northern Mediterranean region. The African annex provides detailed guidance on preparation of programmes of action to combat desertification (at national, sub-regional, and regional levels), and coordination mechanisms to ensure greater collaboration between donors, NGOs, governmental structures and local community organisations.  The other three regional annexes are much briefer.<p>The Resolution on Urgent Action for Africa, agreed in June 1994, encourages governments to begin implementing the ICD immediately, even though ratification of the Convention is still a couple of years away.  Amongst the measures proposed within the resolution are the following:<ul><li>all countries to disseminate information about the Convention, to promote public awareness about the ICD and the actions to which different parties are now committed<li>affected country governments to start preparing National Action Programmes to combat Desertification, building on existing plans where possible.<li>developed countries to support the preparation of NAPs, establishment of partnership arrangements, and specific measures identified within such programmes.</ul><p>The Resolution on interim arrangements sets out the necessary measures to enable work to continue on the ICD, continuing the mandate of the interim Secretariat until the first COP and  making provision for the 6th meeting of the negotiating committee to be held in January 1995.<p>The Secretariat remains an independent entity for the time being, based in Geneva, and with the task of making arrangements for meetings, compiling and transmitting reports submitted to it, and facilitating urgent action for Africa.<p>The committee on science and technology will be established by the COP and will be composed of government representatives competent in the various fields relevant to desertification.  At the same time, the COP will set up an independent roster of experts, to be called upon for work on specific topics.
</td></tr></table>
</center>
<p>
Many people prefer to use the term dryland degradation, since it is less liable to mislead.  ‘Desertification’ conjures up in the mind an image of an advancing desert, whose progress must be halted by establishing a physical barrier, such as a belt of trees.  Despite the popular image of an advancing desert, there is no evidence for this happening.  Instead, the desert frontier shifts over time, depending on the rainfall received that year.  In a drought year such as 1984, the desert advances as plants fail to germinate and others die, while in a year of heavy rainfall, such as 1988 and 1994, the desert retreats, as grasses and shrubs re-establish themselves.  There are localised problems of sand dune movement which need to be tackled where this threatens a village, road, or waterway.  However, compared with the progressive decline in the potential of dryland farming areas, sand dune encroachment is of far less significance in terms of people affected, and the costs of lost productivity.

<H3>What is the real problem?  </H3>

Figures on rates of desertification are hard to come by.  In the past, the UN Environment Programme has tried to put together data on the incidence and severity of desertification at regional and global levels.  However, it is widely admitted that the data are extremely poor.  Little or no data exist from which to measure trends in degradation over a reasonable stretch of time.  Instead, we have to rely on proxy measures, such as crop yields, to estimate trends in underlying productivity.  However, crop yields are clearly strongly determined by a range of other factors - amount and timing of rainfall, labour spent weeding, pest attacks, and so on - which means they are not very useful for measuring rates of degradation.  The underlying causes of dryland degradation vary:<ul>
<li>At <I>field level</I>, baring of soils through ploughing,  lack of measures to conserve soils;
<li>At <I>village or district level</I>, pressure on land available for cultivation, absence of technical support, lack of credit;
<li>At <I>national level</I>, poor security of tenure over land and water, policy bias towards urban populations, few alternative employment opportunities; and
<li>At <I>international level</I>, high levels of debt, weak prices for export crops.</ul>

<H3>A local level approach</H3>

While national and regional action plans have brought little progress for ordinary people, at local level numerous successful examples of dryland development exist.  These successes tend to involve a number of common elements such as working in collaboration with local people and helping them to build on their skills according to their priorities. The intention of the ICD is to replicate such success stories more widely by requiring that the various parties involved change their way of doing business.  In general terms, the ICD sets out a code of good practice for national governments, bilateral donors, multilateral agencies, and non-governmental organisations, which tries to build on more promising approaches to drylands development.
<p>
<center>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<tr><td><center><h4>Lessons from Past Experience</h4></center>
<p>
An increasing body of project experience now demonstrates the importance of certain factors.  Successful projects tend to:<ul><li>adopt a flexible, learning process approach, which allows projects to change course as circumstances change<li>build on local skills<li>place highest priority on local people’s needs<li>provide secure rights over resources to poor people, and significant benefits<li>depend on well-trained and motivated staff, who are committed to working alongside poor people, often in harsh conditions.</ul>
</td></tr></table>
</center>
<p>

<H3>What will the Convention mean in practice?</H3>

The ICD contains a host of highly challenging commitments for both affected countries and developed country donors, such as the EU (see box).  If followed, the commitments would have far-reaching implications for the exercise of power, allocation of resources, and decision-making process in these countries.
<p>
<center>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<tr><td><center><h4>The Convention Commitments</h4></center>
<p>
“<I>Signatory governments of affected countries promise to provide an enabling environment ... facilitate the participation of local populations ... encourage initiatives and the assumption of responsibility by local communities. ... and provide secure tenure for local populations.<p>Developed country signatories undertake to actively support the efforts of affected countries ... provide substantial resources..... avoid duplication..... facilitate access to appropriate technology .... strengthen capacities... and develop an informal process of consultation and coordination among themselves</I>”.
</td></tr></table>
</center>
<p>
The Desertification Convention provides an important opportunity for governments of affected countries to consolidate donor support for drylands development.  It is essential that they seize this opportunity and demonstrate their desire to follow the commitments made under the Convention.  While the main initiative needs to remain in the hands of national governments, <I>donor agencies have a vitally important role to play, in encouraging a flexible, process-led approach, and demonstrating a willingness to pool interests and resources in support of the national government’s agenda</I>.
<p>
Ultimately, however, action by national governments and donors will be useless unless it sets a general framework within which local people - herders, farmers - are encouraged to act.  The commitments under the ICD are designed to facilitate action by land users, by strengthening their ability and motivation to tackle dryland degradation.   But local people will only have an interest in making long term investments where they have secure rights to their land, and where they can see clear benefits from such activities.
<p>
The central commitment within the ICD is preparation of National Action Programmes to combat desertification, building on existing environmental plans and strategies where possible.  Such programmes are meant to:<ul> 
<li>be prepared in a consultative and participatory fashion 
<li>emphasize integrated local development programmes 
<li>propose a range of actions needed to strengthen capacity within decentralised structures, and
<li>promote education and training for local populations.
</ul><p>
<H3>Making planning work</H3>

While the ICD text provides a challenging series of commitments, phrased in excellent rhetoric, careful thought is needed to ensure that such rhetoric is carried through into practice.  A close look at past experience shows that many a well-laid plan brings poor results, for a variety of reasons.  These include: 
<ul>
<li>competition amongst donors and their respective plans, programmes, and strategies; 
<li>institutional wrangling between ministries over which will be responsible and therefore receive funds; 
<li>lack of interest in and ownership of such environmental plans by recipient governments; and 
<li>no attention paid to involving local people and organisations in formulating programmes and policies.</ul>
<p>
If the Desertification Convention is to bear fruit, the governments of affected countries must be convinced of the need for National Action Plans, and their preparation through consultation and participation.  This will only happen if governments, donors, NGOs, and ordinary people have more information about the Convention and the opportunities presented by this agreement.
<p>
Important questions remain concerning the implementation of the Desertification Convention.  These questions include:
<ul>
<li>What is meant by a participatory planning process? Who needs to participate and how? Does it matter?
<li>How will National Action Plans to combat Desertification be integrated into the other planning initiatives currently under way, such as National Conservation Strategies, Forestry Action Plans, and National Environmental Action Plans?
<li>What linkages exist between climate change and desertification?
<li>How important are technical issues, as opposed to socio-economic factors in combatting desertification?  Why are land tenure and decentralisation such central elements within the Convention?
</ul><p>
<H3>Finding the EU role</H3>

The EC and its Member States have historically been the largest source of development finance to combat desertification, particularly in Africa.   It is now almost ten years since the launch of the European Action Plan to Combat Desertification.   The ICD provides a challenging strategic agenda for how the Community could support the sustainable management of drylands, particularly in the next phase of the Lomé Convention.  European policymakers now need to assess the implications of the ICD for future aid programming.
<p>
<I>The author, Camilla Toulmin, is Director of the Drylands Programme, at IIED. She is also a Member of the International Panel of Experts on Desertification established by the United Nations to advise the negotiations of the International Convention to combat Desertification.</I>
