<html><head><title>IIED European Programme - EC Aid and Sustainable Development</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#009999" alink="#999999" vlink="#99CCCC"><a href="index.html"><img border=0 align=right width=183 height=163 src="pix/sublogo.gif"></a><small>The material that follows has been provided by <b><a href="../index.html">International Institute for Environment and Development (IIED)</a></b></small><hr><h3>The Desertification  Convention - what will it mean on the ground?<p>EC Aid and Sustainable Development Briefing Paper, No. 5, 1995</h3>

<I>The international Convention to Combat Desertification (CCD) lays out an impressive agenda of action for developing countries and donor agencies.   This second Briefing Paper on the Convention examines what it could mean on the ground and points to lessons from the past from implementing soil and water conservation projects</I>. 
<p>
<H3>Implementing the Convention</H3>

The CCD contains a number of key themes for tackling the growing problem of dryland degradation in developing countries.  As the text says, attention will be paid to:
<ul>
<li>achieving effective participation by both women and men at local, regional and national levels, including farmers and pastoralists and their representative organisations in policy planning, decision-making, implementation and review of national action programmes;
<p>
<li>realising increased flexibility in project design, funding and implementation, in keeping with the experimental, iterative approach that is needed for particpatory action at the local community level;
<p>
<li>encouraging a policy of active decentralisation as well as the assumption of responsibility by local communities; and
<p>
<li>adjusting the institutional and regulatory framework of natural resource management to provide security of tenure for local populations.
</ul><p>
The issue now for developing countries and donors is to translate these aspirations into action.  The UN Conference Halls are a long way from the hot and dusty field of a farmer in the Sahel.  So, will the commitments made by government delegates bring any real changes on the ground? And what can we do to try and make it happen?
<p>
Here, we tackle 12 of the most important questions to be answered.

<H4>1. What does desertification really mean?</H4>

Desertification is seen by many as desert advance. But this represents only a fraction of the problem. The greatest threat to the livelihoods of farmers and pastoralists in developing countries is the degradation of land often hundreds of kilometres away from any desert. Consequently, measures to combat deserti-fication are those that improve the stability and productivity of dryland farming and pastoral systems, within a context of great  climatic, economic and institutional variability.  This means taking action to conserve soil and water resources, improve soil fertility and develop better grazing management practices.

<H4>2. What is new about the Convention ?</H4>

The Convention represents a culmination of thinking and practice over many years. Experience has shown that farmers need more secure tenure rights over their land, and that it makes sense to involve local people in planning projects. It is also clear that donors can act in a competitive and uncoordinated fashion, proposing rival plans and initiatives to different ministeries. What the Convention does is bring these lessons of experience together in a coherent form, giving clear guidance based on more promising approaches to dryland management.  

<H4>3. What time frame are we working within ?</H4>

The Convention to Combat Desertification was agreed in June 1994, and more than one hundred governments have now signed it.  Almost all African governments are amongst the signatories and 13 of the 15 member states of the EU, in addition to the European Commission itself.  It is not expected to come into force until 1997, because of the time needed for at least 50 governments to ratify the Convention through their own parliaments.  But  following the agreement of the Resolution on Urgent Action for Africa, pilot activities are already under way, with Mali as the first case in Africa.

<H4>4. How can a Convention make a difference to dryland farmers and herders?</H4>

It will only make a difference if the governments concerned decide to take it seriously.  Formally, an international convention is legally binding on those governments which sign it.  In practice, the adherence of signatory governments to any convention may be less closely observed.  Being realistic, the Convention will not change overnight the situation faced by many millions of land users throughout dry Africa.  
<p>
However, there are a sufficient number of affected countries and donor governments who have expressed strong support for the Convention, so we have a good base to start from.  It lays out firm commitments which could bring substantial benefits to ordinary land users throughout the continent.

<H4>5. Why should anyone abide by the Convention, especially since there are no enforceable targets, and no extra funds?</H4>

It is true that there are no extra funds promised by the Convention, unlike the Climate Change Convention or that on Biological Diversity, where funding is provided through the Global Environment Facility.  However, desertification is a rather different sort of problem. Indeed, many observers thought that negotiating a convention was the wrong way to approach this kind of issue.  What we have in this new convention is essentially a ‘code of good conduct’ for recipient governments and donors.  The text expresses the desire of signatories to follow certain guidelines regarding the right policy framework for encouraging more sustainable dryland management, and for how aid is delivered.  
<p>
A code of conduct may have few teeth.  It depends rather on people having an interest in doing better and being seen by others to do better.  The desire to set a good example to others can be a powerful incentive to develop new strategies and methods of work.  Also, signatory governments of affected countries which fail to follow the guidelines laid down by the convention may find it increasingly difficult to persuade OECD donors to give aid funds.  In every developed country, aid money is getting tighter.  Priority is likely to be given to recipients who can demonstrate a willingness to act upon the commitments which they have signed up to.

<H4>6. What have African governments promised to do?</H4>

Various things, including a review of policy in fields such as land tenure,and administration, with a view to transferring power to control land from government hands to local communities and their institutions.  They have pledged to pursue a far more participatory style of decision making and planning of activities. These and other activities are to be incorporated into a national action programme to combat desertification.  

<H4>7. What is the purpose of another environmental action programme ?</H4>

During the 1980s, many developing countries drew up tropical forest action plans, national environmental action plans and national conservation strategies. There are concerns that the CCD could add to this planning overload. However, these national action programmes are not meant to replace existing strategies but, rather to ensure, where necessary, a particular focus on questions of dryland management.  They are not meant to be a formal document listing all of the projects which the government wants to see funded.  Instead, the national action programme needs to direct attention to a series of policy changes, institutional reforms, and broader programmes which need to be under taken to ensure that land users have a greater incentive to invest in their land.

<H4>8. What commitments are donors to fulfil?</H4>

It is clearly recognised that the primary responsibility for improving dryland resource management lies with the affected country.  Donors need to provide support to their efforts by making longer term funds available for national action programmes, and ensuring that such funding is provided in a more flexible fashion.  Donors have also agreed that they will endeavour to coordinate their activities more effectively, to avoid contradictions between their approaches.

<H4>9. How can the commitment to greater participation and decentralisation in project development be accommodated within donor programming ?</H4>

This is one of the most pressing issues for donors such as the EU to resolve. In the short-term, donors need to identify the options for increasing flexibility and participation within existing procedures. Many of these already exist.  The challenge for donors is to share successful country level experience.

<H4>10. What are the national policy preconditions for successful implementation ?</H4>

National governments need to provide a secure environment within which farmers and herders have a firm interest in improving their land. The main actors must be local farmers and herders. Governments and donors must not think it is their job to interfere in telling people what they should be doing.  
<p>
Rights to manage resources must be clearly defined, so that herders have an interest in managing grazing for the longer term  Its no good their establishing systems for setting aside reserve pasture areas, if others can come in from outside and make use of these resources.  In the same way, villagers need to feel secure that their rights to manage woodland and grazing will be respected if people from elsewhere try to come and make charcoal, or settle and start clearing land without the agreement of local people.

<H4>11. What can be done at the local level?</H4>

There are various possibilities.  One is to review land tenure codes to ensure that the allocation of responsibility for land management to the local level is matched by equivalent rights, which ensure that people can control who has access to resources, and on what terms.  A second, and important innovation which is developing in certain Sahelian countries is the drawing up of ‘local conventions’ by a grouping of 5 to 10 villages which share common resources.  These conventions specify the terms on which villagers can cut wood, clear land, and have access to pasture within the overall area.  At the same time, these local conventions lay out the fees which must be paid by outsiders wanting to come and cut wood or pasture their animals within the overall territory of this grouping of villages.  What is very important is that the local administration is now willing to recognise these conventions as constituting a legal basis for supporting villagers’ rights.

<H4>12. What does people’s participation mean in practice?</H4>

Several things. First, a commitment to work more slowly and involve local people and their organisations in discussion from the earliest stage in whatever activity is planned, listening to their views, and building on their knowledge and skills.  Second, investment of resources and time in training - training of local people, project, government, and donor staff in participatory methods for community level planning.  There are a number of participatory techniques available and an increasing body of trainers with experience in this field.  Third, a commitment to invest in building the capacity of local people and organisations to take charge of decisions which affect them through the development of literacy and numeracy skills, access to credit, transfer of powers to control land, and so on.


<H3>Learning from Soil and Water Conservation</H3>

Based on the lessons learned from the past, the Convention offers a promising way forward for all people concerned with poorer parts of the world, and a way of ensuring more effective aid delivery.  It focuses on community-based initiatives and provides practical guidance for planning and project design.  
<p>
While the drylands of the world face certain particular problems, they also have considerable potential, if managed correctly.  We can show plenty of examples of success stories where things have gone right with soil and water conservation.  The Convention provides basic ground rules for ensuring that we have a greater chance of success, and have an aid programme to be proud of.
<p>
In the past, many soil and water conservation (SWC) projects failed because they introduced techniques which were not acceptable to the land users, were technically inappropriate and often required too much maintenance.  During the colonial era people were forced to construct conservation works and after independence they were bribed into it through the systematic use of “food-for-work”.   Where projects systematically used heavy machinery to construct conservation works, the “beneficiaries” tended to assume that as these works were constructed by government, it was also up to the government to maintain them.  Land users were always instructed, but never consulted about what could be done to reverse land degradation.  Where they had devised themselves a range of techniques, these were usually completely overlooked or just ignored.
<p>
When conservation works (terraces, bunds, check dams, cut off drains, etc.) are not well designed or maintained, they fall apart within a few years and they then accelerate erosion rather than reducing it.  Lack of adequate upkeep has been the rule and not the exception.    
<p>
Donor agencies continued to fund poorly performing SWC projects partly because projects were never adequately monitored.  Costs were not matched against real benefits. Whereas most SWC projects assessed the costs of the technical package they promoted, they often only had a vague idea about the benefits that would be generated.  It was not uncommon that projects were believed to be successful, because one simply added each year the number of hectares treated.  In this way impressive figures could be shown.  However, one never deducted the number of hectares treated, but not exploited by the “beneficiaries” or for the number of hectares where conservation works became non-operational after 3 or 4 years.  Finally, experience has also shown that in virtually all cases SWC activities stop as soon as donor funding is withdrawn.
<p>
Since the middle of the 1980s, there has been a shift in thinking about how SWC should be done,  influenced by developments in countries like Burkina Faso.   For more than a decade earth bunds had been constructed on the Central Plateau of Burkina, but these were neither maintained nor expanded.  An OXFAM-funded Agroforestry Project in Yatenga had started to test contour stone bunds in 1979, essentially an improved traditional technique.  Farmers reacted enthusiastically to this and a training programme was initiated at village level to train farmers in the principles of stone bund construction.  Many farmers constructed stone bunds spontaneously on their own fields.  

<H3>Simple and efficient techniques</H3>

The lessons drawn from this experience were that conservation techniques have to be simple, low-cost, efficient and require minimum maintenance in order to be acceptable to land users.  For the first time the ability to replicate was identified as an important design criterion for SWC projects.  Unless the majority of land users undertake SWC on their own fields, the battle against land degradation cannot be won.  In the West African Sahel, a small range of natural resource management techniques can be found which are adopted spontaneously by land users.  They include:
<ul>
<li>contour stone bunds
<li>improved planting pits (zay or tassa)
<li>half moons (demi-lunes)
<li>mulching
<li>compost pits
<li>natural regeneration
</ul><p>
Since the early 1980s, there have been great technical breakthroughs in the Sahel.  In Burkina Faso, Niger and Mali, thousands of hectares of degraded land are now rehabilitated each year, as a result of field experiments by project staff and farmers (see box).
<p>
<center>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<tr><td><center><h4>Case Study: Improved planting pits in Niger</h4></center>
Since 1988, IFAD has been funding a SWC project in Niger’s Illéla district to promote simple, low-cost SWC techniques, which can easily be mastered by land users.  In 1989 the project organised a visit by 10 of its farmers (including three women) to the Yatenga region in Burkina Faso.   There they were impressed by the use of improved planting pits to rehabilitate degraded land.  These techniques resembled those they knew traditionally, but which were unimproved and only applied at a small scale.  <p>
Upon return, they treated four hectares of degraded, barren and badly encrusted land 
with astonishing results.  In 1990, a drought year,  farmers treated 70 hectares.  On the fields treated with improved planting pits (tassa) yields were in the order of 300 - 400 kg. of millet and sorghum/ha.  Elsewhere, yields were far lower.  As a result, the number of hectares treated in 1991 increased strongly (between 400 and 500 ha).  Since 1990, about 8000 hectares of degraded land have been rehabilitated in the Illéla district alone by farmers without any external support.  The IFAD-project provides training and a minimum of material support, but its extension agents are completely overtaken by the enthusiasm of farmers.<p>Farmers in neighbouring districts (Tahoua, Konni, Madoua) are now adopting tassa.  Projects in other parts of Niger have begun organising field visits for their farmers to Illéla district.  As a result farmers in the region of Ouallam (North of Niamey) have recently adopted this technique.<p>The IFAD SWC project in Illéla district is unique also in the sense that it has systematically collected yield data for the various techniques it promotes and data are now available for a period of four years, including a drought year (1992) and a wet year (1994).<p> In 1994, the average yield of millet on fields treated with tassa and manure was 969 kg/ha and on fields with tassa and manure plus fertilizers 1486 kg/ha.  A farmer who owns a piece of degraded land spends 40 - 60 days digging improved planting pits on 1 ha.  If he hires labour it will cost him 30.000 CFA/ha.  Assuming a yield of 700 kg of millet/ha at a value of 80 CFA/k, his gross benefit will be 26.000 CFA in year 1.  It will be substantially higher in the following years when he will only have to slightly excavate the pits.  These rehabilitated fields add substantially to food security at household level.<p>In districts adjacent to Illéla, other SWC projects have introduced much higher cost packages ($400 per hectare and more), which produce yields on average lower than those obtained in the improved traditional planting pits. The yields are lower because there is an imbalance between the size of the area rehabilitated with heavy machinery and the capacity of the farmers to manager adequately and exploit this land.  They simply do not have sufficient manure to fertilize these fields or labour to weed the crop.  Simple techniques which build on local practice offer a cost effective way for rehabilitating land.  Donors should examine how to support this process of adoption.
</td></tr></table>
</center>
<p>
The systematic use of simple SWC techniques by farmers on their own fields is an indispensable first step in the battle against land degradation.  It leads to an intensification of land use and it improves household food security.  However, it is not sufficient as  it does not address the degradation on non-cultivated village lands, which is exactly where “village land use management projects (gestion de terroirs)” try to innovate.
<p>
Donor agencies can facilitate and accelerate the adoption of these simple and effective SWC techniques through the funding of farmer-to-farmer exchange visits, farmer training (men and women) and well targeted material support. A high priority is the introduction of local means of transport, like donkey carts, which are manufactured in the region, thereby strengthening non-farm employment.     
<p>
Much has been achieved in the last 10 years in the Sahel in the field of SWC.  The challenge is still considerable, but at least we know better than in the past what to do and how to do it. 
<p>
<I>The authors of this Briefing Paper are Camilla Toulmin and Chris Reij.  Dr Toulmin is Director of the Drylands Programme, at IIED.  She was also a Member of the International Panel of Experts on Desertifi-cation established by the United Nations to advise the negotiations of the International Convention to combat Desertification.  Dr Reij is a senior staff member at the Centre for Development Cooperation Services at the Free University, Amsterdam.  He has been involved for over 15 years in the design and implementation of projects and policies to combat dersertification particularly in the Sahel.</I>
<p><hr><small>©Copyright:IIED 1995</small><p><TABLE BORDER=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="index.html"><img src="pix/home.gif" width=100 height=43 alt="Home Page"></a></TD></TR></TABLE></body></html>
