<header>
<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Europe</title>
</header>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><IMG align=middle SRC  = "../images/gr.jpg"><h3>Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy in Greece
</h3></center>
This information is drawn from the report of a survey (1993-1994) carried out by ECDPM on behalf of the
National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) of the Netherlands.
<br> 
<h5><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/nar.jpg" border=1> Source: Kooij, A. and R. Mevis.
1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen
European Countries</i>. The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The
report is available from: NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The
Hague, the Netherlands.
</h5>
<hr>
<h3>Contents:</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org">Organisation of Greek Development Cooperation</a>
<li><a href="#ins">Institutional Framework</a>
<li><a href="#adv">Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</a>
<li><a href="#ngo">Non-State Sources of Advice</a>
<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"><IMG align=top SRC =
"../images/acro.jpg"></a>
</ul><p>

<hr><a name="org"><h3>Organisation of Greek Development Cooperation</h3>

Official development cooperation in Greece started in the late 1980s. It has a very low profile among the
media and the public, whose attention is focused on domestic economic problems. 
<p>
The volume of Greek official aid has risen sharply since its recent start. In 1991 total aid amounted to less
than US $ 4 million, while in 1993 it had risen to more then US $ 20 million. Greece still receives an
amount of ODA of more then US $ 30 million. Contributions are made to multilateral institutions and to EU
aid programmes. Greece is not a DAC-member.
<p>
<hr><a name="ins"><h3>Institutional Framework</h3></a>
<p>
Responsibility for the aid programme rests with the Ministry for Foreign Affairs. In 1992 a Directorate for
Development Cooperation and Special Economic Affairs was set up within this Ministry. The Directorate
does not have the overall authority for development cooperation. In addition, departments of the Ministries
of Foreign Affairs, Trade, Finance and Education also deal with issues related to development cooperation
policy. Interministerial coordination of aid efforts and policy is presently wanting and technical expertise is
apparently low.
<p>
More than half of the aid volume is spent through a growing number of recently created private
organisations. These are mainly NGOs of which the Red Cross stands out by a wide margin. Aid from
NGOs has also been supported quite substantially by EU funding.
<p>
<hr><a name="adv"><h3>Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</h3></a>
<p>
There is no advisory structure for development cooperation in Greece. The growing number of NGOs
involved in development cooperation are lobbying with the Government for a more clear and coherent
development cooperation policy. They are also concerned with raising public awareness of development
problems.
<p>
The Greek Parliament does not seem to take a great interest in the problems of the South, or the growing
aid budget of the Government. Not many questions are asked on the subject. Parliament does not receive an
annual report on development assistance.
<p>
<a name="ngo"><HR><h3>Non-State Sources of Advice</h3></a>
<p>
There seems to be no research community focused on development cooperation. The ten Development
Research and Training Institutes mentioned by the 1991 OECD/EADI survey do not specialise in Third
World development problems.
<p>
<hr>
