<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Europe</title>
</header>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><IMG SRC  = "../images/nl.jpg">
<h3>Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy in the Netherlands
</h3></center>
This information is drawn from the report of a survey (1993-1994) carried out by ECDPM on behalf of the
National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) of the Netherlands.
<br> 
<h5><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/nar.jpg" border=1> Source: Kooij, A. and R. Mevis.
1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen
European Countries</i>. The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The
report is available from: NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The
Hague, the Netherlands.
</h5>
<hr>
<h3>Contents:</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org">Organisation of Dutch Development Cooperation</a>
<li><a href="#ins">Institutional Framework</a>
<li><a href="#adv">Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</a>
<li><a href="#ngo">Non-State Sources of Advice</a>
<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"><IMG align=top SRC =
"../images/acro.jpg"></a>
</ul><p>

<hr><a name="org"><h3>Organisation of Dutch Development Cooperation</h3>

The Netherlands development cooperation is based on several types of motives. The importance attached to
new international relations in foreign policy after a colonial past, a strong religious sense of solidarity with
poor people, and commercial motives relating to the position and economic characteristics of the
Netherlands. Official bilateral development cooperation started in the early sixties, built also on a long and
active church-related NGO-tradition and on an active and critical governmental support since World War II
for the functioning of the UN institutions. The first Minister for Development Cooperation was appointed in
1965. Parliamentary and public support for development cooperation has always been very strong, and at the
same time watchful. The Dutch media play an active role in public monitoring. Although domestic issues
appear to become more predominant in the attention of the public, a large part of the population is actively
and often personally involved in development cooperation. 
<p>
Net official development assistance of the Netherlands in 1992 amounted to US $ 2 753 million, being 0.86
per cent of GNP. Multilateral disbursements amounted to about one-third of ODA over the years, usually
equally shared by the UN, the Bretton Woods institutions and the EU. Multilateral ODA grew in 1991 and
1992, recovering the earlier one third share (23 per cent of ODA plus 9 per cent to the EU in 1992), but
dropped in 1993 to an estimated 28 per cent of ODA. 
<p>
Presently a discussion is conducted about the future contents and financial targets for Dutch development
cooperation. In 1967 the Netherlands have set themselves a total aid budget target (the 'ceiling') of 1 per
cent of the net national income (NNI), in 1977 set at 1.5 per cent of NNI (roughly 1.2 per cent of Dutch
GNP). Since 1990 a decrease set in and a growing number of other expenses that "contaminated" ODA and
non-ODA parts of budget: growing emergency aid to non-DAC countries, aid for Eastern European
countries, peace-keeping activities and reception and care of refugees in the Netherlands. The actual total
'ceiling' in 1993 reached 1.39 per cent of NNI (= 1.10 % of GNP) including 0.81 % of GNP for ODA
with an estimation for 1994 of 1.42 per cent NNI (0.8 per cent of GNP). In 1992 the ceiling was left. These
developments resulted in an effective reduction of the available volume for assistance to developing
countries.
<p>
<hr><a name="ins"><h3>Institutional Framework</h3></a>
<p>
The Netherlands' official development cooperation is not laid down in an organic law. It started in 1964 as
an annex to the budget of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, of which it still a part. The Minister for
Development Cooperation is a Cabinet Minister without portfolio; he has no budget or staff of his own. The
Ministry of Foreign Affairs includes a Directorate-General for International Cooperation (DGIS). Officials at
the DGIS are integrated with the Dutch Foreign Service. Parts of the development budget of DGIS are
implemented by the Cabinet of Netherlands-Antilles and Aruban Affairs, by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs,
and by the eleven other ministries. Voluntary multilateral contributions are under the responsibility of the
Minister of Finance, but only after consulting the Minister for Development Cooperation).  
<p>
The core structure of the DGIS is a three-dimensional matrix, organised around sectors, countries and
channels (bilateral, multilateral and NGOs), supplemented by functional departments and sub-departments
according to specific implementation modalities. The total lay out reflecting the firm (and sometimes
complex) set of objectives, points of attention, criteria and tests per programme, project and country. Over
the years the administrational set-up of the DGIS has been changed several times, under influence of
changing policy priorities and efforts to improve efficiency, effectiveness and financial accountability. Since
some time actions are undertaken to simplify procedures.
<p>
Preparation, formulation, implementation, monitoring and evaluation of activities are, for the majority,
either sub-contracted to external consultants, firms or independent institutions and NGOs, or to several -
government related- institutions. Moreover, the Netherlands promote spending of cooperation funds in the
Third World, use and support local capacity and follow Europe-wide tendering procedures. The Government
intends to focus more on priorities set by developing countries, and on local implementation and capacity
building. Among the government funded organisations that implement specific programmes are: the Centre
for the Promotion of Imports from Developing Countries (CBI) that stimulates imports into Europe from
LDCs; the Netherlands Finance Company for Developing Countries (FMO), a bank for the development of
the private sector in the Third World; the SNV-Netherlands Development Organisation for project and
personnel assistance. A number of government programmes exist with a wide range of NGOs for various
policy areas, based on long term block grant contracts (see further 3. Other Actors). For emergency aid
Dutch and international NGOs are sub-contracted. Direct funding by the DGIS to NGOs in the Third World
and to International NGO-networks does occur. The DGIS has programmes for cooperation with Dutch
industry and banks, that are relatively limited in volume and number. The Netherlands Investment Bank for
Developing Countries (NIO) handles financial programme aid for which the developing country concerned
has full executive responsibility.  
<p>
The Policy Planning Section of the DGIS concentrates on long term strategic policies as well as mid and
long term budget planning. Country and sector policies are designed at the desks concerned with a large
input from the embassies and local expertise. Approximately 70 sector specialists and technical advisers
have been appointed at embassies and at the DGIS. Within the DGIS matrix many consultations take place
between the various departments, with or without external advisers and/or on the basis of external studies.
Implementation of the earlier mentioned policy changes generates a greater need for internal and external
policy coordination.
<p>
There are several instruments for coordination of the Netherlands development policy. International
environmental concern and peace-keeping activities are increasingly becoming subjects for interministerial
policy coordination. Besides the bilateral consultations between the DGIS and the ministries on the above
mentioned budget items for which the Minister for Development Cooperation acts as policy coordinator, two
important interministerial committees operate. Ministers who are responsible for a certain policy area that is
subject to interministerial coordination, cannot take a decision without consulting other ministers, or without
discussion in the Cabinet. The Minister for Development Coordination is responsible for coordination of
development policy. He appoints the members of the Interministerial Coordination Committee for
development Cooperation (COCOS), which prepares the discussions for the Ministerial Council for
Development Cooperation (ROS) that is chaired by the Prime Minister. Both committees meet frequently.
The Minister for Development Cooperation is also a member of the Council for Economic Affairs that
prepares Cabinet discussions about economic, financial, monetary and social policy. DGIS participates in
meetings of the Council for Trade Policy and in the Coordinating Committee on International Environment
Issues. 
<p>
The Independent Operations Review Unit (IOV) at the DGIS reports directly to the Minister. IOV reports
are sent to Parliament, and they are translated and published. IOV activities are to be distinguished from
ongoing project and programme evaluations (annually: 150) which are an obligatory component of the
project cycle. IOV studies influence DGIS policy. 
<p>
<hr><a name="adv"><h3>Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</h3></a>
<p>
In 1964 the National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) was installed, following the
example of the Belgium Government. Its installation was motivated by the wish to develop a consistent
development cooperation policy and to involve as many sections of Dutch society as possible in its aid
policy. The Council provides policy and scientific advice to the Minister for Development Cooperation, and
through him or her to the Netherlands Government. As a Sector Council for development cooperation, the
NAR may address its recommendations also to other Ministers. The Council generally advises on topics of
mid- to long term policy. Occasionally matters of more immediate relevance are treated. After its installation
in 1964, the Council used to comment on the annual budget for development cooperation.
<p>
The NAR has 70 members, who are appointed on the basis of their personal expertise, their active interest
in development cooperation, and their availability for advisory work. NAR members come from many
sectors of Dutch society, a.o. industry and banks, religious organisations, politics, universities and research
institutes, labour unions. The composition of the Council is meant to include the ideas on development held
in Dutch society as a whole. The chairperson and the members of the Council are appointed by the Minister
for Development Cooperation for a period of four years, after which they can be reappointed. The NAR
may make reports on its own initiative or at the request of the Minister; around 80 % of the NAR reports
were prepared on request by the various ministers. Thus the NAR may be considered to have two main
functions, 1) to provide information not directly available at the DGIS, and 2) to function as a bridge
between government and society. The functions of chairperson, vice-chairperson and special activities of
NAR-members are renumerated.
<p>
The NAR is assisted by an official secretariat, which forms part of the Policy Planning Section of the DGIS.
At the secretariat, headed by a Secretary, currently work five persons. The Council has its own budget,
provided by the MFA.
<p>
The Minister for Development Cooperation is bound to respond to NAR recommendations. The written
reply of the Minister is sent to the Chairman of the Council and to Parliament. In preparing a
recommendation, the Council may organise hearings, sub-contract additional expertise, undertake studies,
and organise conferences. Recommendations are written by working groups of Council members and
finalised in a Plenary Meeting of the Council. A recommendation may be followed up by conferences,
discussions and other publications. In addition the Council prepares position papers and commentaries on
current issues in development cooperation. 
<p>
Since its start the Council has produced around 135 policy recommendations and reports on a wide range of
subjects. Currently it prepares recommendations on technology and development; on conflicts, security and
development; on an interministerial discussion paper about the 'joint implementation' (i.e. of emission
reduction measures) of the Framework Convention on Climate Change (1992). The Council is preparing
recommendations for the UN International World Conference on Women and Development (1995), for the
UN Social Summit (1995). Recent recommendations are: on the UN International Conference on Population
and Development (1994), on urban poverty combating, on development cooperation after the Treaty of
Maastricht, on norms and policy of the Dutch development cooperation. 
<p>
NAR recommendations, commentaries and other reports are summarised, translated in French and English,
and distributed to a wide public in the Netherlands -and abroad-, including Parliament. The NAR issues an
annual report and a publications list. 
<p>
Regular consultations between the administration and representatives of institutions and organisations in
Dutch society are an essential part of the Dutch political system. Advisory councils have a long tradition in
the Netherlands. There are presently 135 permanent and temporary advisory councils in the Netherlands.
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs has seven advisory councils (including the NAR), a.o. on human rights,
peace and security, and research. Recommendations by several Councils on the same subject area(s) are
coordinated. The presidium of the NAR annually discusses its work with members of both Chambers of
Parliament, with the Minister and with the Director-General of the DGIS. Several members of the NAR are
also involved in the work of other advisory councils. 
<p>
The Government has decided to reduce the number and the status of Dutch advisory councils, within its
efforts to renew and streamline administrative structures and procedures. Councils will have to focus on
advisory tasks, which will be separated from consultation processes. Within a new set-up the Parliament
may also directly request advice from these councils.
The annual budget for development cooperation is discussed extensively in both Chambers of Parliament.
The Minister has regularly discussions with the Standing Commissions of the Second Chamber of
Parliament. Till 1993 with the Standing Commission for Development Cooperation, thereafter with the
Standing Commission for Foreign Affairs. 
<p>
<a name="ngo"><HR><h3>Non-State Sources of Advice</h3></a>
<p>
The Netherlands have an extensive network of NGOs, in nearly all sectors of society, that follow
government policies critically. The NGO-community for development cooperation plays an active role in
policy formulation, implementation and development education. The numerous development NGOs can
roughly be classified in 3 groups. Firstly the 4 Co-financing Organisations CEBEMO, HIVOS, ICCO and
NOVIB, the trade-unions FNV and CNV, the employers associations VNO and NCW (for management
assistance), the Organisation for Cooperation in Development Research and Education (NUFFIC, for
international education), the Foundation for Communication (the media), the Union of Dutch Municipalities,
the Hindu-Islamic HIMOS, and the expert-sending organisation PSO. These are all umbrella organisations
for large numbers of NGOs that are involved in development policy cooperation through long term
arrangements with the Government. Secondly, more than 300 local and national NGOs and action
committees involved in development cooperation on a project-by-project base and third, NGOs for
development education receiving support from the government funded NCO (National Committee for
Development Education).
<p>
When the budget for development cooperation is up for discussion in Parliament, representatives of the
NGOs are consulted by the Standing Committee on Development Cooperation. Since 1965 the DGIS has
built up an effective working relationship with the NGOs, which includes formulated formal procedures for
implementation, monitoring, consultation, evaluation and policy dialogue. Meetings between the Minister, or
representatives of the DGIS, with representatives from NGOs and boards are held monthly. Important
developments in developing countries are regularly discussed. 
<p>
Areas of concern for the Dutch NGOs in the current discussion with the Government are amongst others:
the consequences of the new development policy for the availability of funds for long term structural
development in the poorest countries, the claims other ministries might lay on the budget for non-
development purposes (in the Netherlands).
<p>
The 1991 OECD/EADI survey qualifies 48 institutes in the Netherlands as Development Research and
Training Institutes, some of which cooperate in the NUFFIC for training of foreign students. The Advisory
Council for Scientific Research in Development Problems (RAWOO), a sector council in 1990 installed by
the Minister for Development Cooperation, of Education and Science, and of Agriculture, Nature
Management and Fisheries, advises the Government on research policies for development cooperation. Its
main activity is to assess project proposals for research.
<p>
<hr>
<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="../images/logo.gif"></a>
<i>Updated on November 7, 1995</i><br>
