<html>
<header>
<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Europe</title>
</header>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><IMG align=middle SRC  = "../images/pt.jpg"><h3>Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy in Portugal</h3></center>
This information is drawn from the report of a survey (1993-1994) carried out by ECDPM on behalf of the
National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) of the Netherlands.
<br> 
<h5><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/nar.jpg" border=1> Source: Kooij, A. and R. Mevis.
1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen
European Countries</i>. The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The
report is available from: NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The
Hague, the Netherlands.
</h5>
<hr>
<h3>Contents:</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org">Organisation of Portuguese Development Cooperation</a>
<li><a href="#ins">Institutional Framework</a>
<li><a href="#adv">Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</a>
<li><a href="#ngo">Non-State Sources of Advice</a>
<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"><IMG align=top SRC =
"../images/acro.jpg"></a>
</ul><p>

<hr><a name="org"><h3>Organisation of Portuguese Development Cooperation</h3>

Portuguese development cooperation started in the late 1980s after Portugal joined the European
Community, from which Portugal still receives considerable assistance. In 1991 Portugal rejoined the DAC,
after it had left the organisation in 1974 when it requested to be considered a developing country.
Development cooperation, constituting a substantial part of Portuguese foreign relations, is based upon its
historic links, common language and economic interests in former colonies. However, since some time
efforts are undertaken to transform these policies, activities and their administration into a broader and more
structural model of development cooperation. There is a small but growing public support - and press
attention - for the latter type of development cooperation. The majority of the Portuguese population
perceives that it has an obligation towards the former colonies where previously about ten per cent of its
population lived, but also sees Portugal as a country not yet sufficiently developed itself.
<p>
Net official development assistance almost doubled since 1989 to US $ 302 million in 1992, which was 0.36
per cent of GNP, mainly through debt-rescheduling operations. Forecasts on the aid volume are difficult,
since relevant data are absent, but it will certainly be lower in the years after 1992. 16 per cent of ODA was
channelled through the EU in 1992, while multilateral aid, excluding EU contributions stood at 4 per cent.
For the coming years total multilateral ODA should stabilise on 25 per cent.
<p>
<hr><a name="ins"><h3>Institutional Framework</h3></a>
<p>
Portugal does not have a written charter for development cooperation, nor a central aid budget. Aid is not
clearly distinguished in the distinct budgets of the various ministries involved in development assistance. The
aid administration could be characterised as decentralised. The Ministry of Foreign Affairs is responsible for
formulating development cooperation policy. The Minister of Foreign Affairs has delegated his authority to
a State Secretary for Development Cooperation. The government institutions responsible for development
assistance are presently being reorganised, in order to create a centralised aid administration. There used to
be a Directorate-General for Cooperation (DGC, since 1979), responsible for the bilateral socio-cultural,
scientific, and technical sectors of bilateral assistance. The Institute for Economic Cooperation (ICE, since
1976), an autonomous body responsible to both the MFA and the Ministry of Finance, is in charge of
financial, economic and entrepreneurial activities, including refinancing operations and most multilateral
contributions. In 1990 the Ministry of Finance and the Ministry of Foreign Affairs together accounted for
almost 90 per cent of total ODA disbursements, with a rapidly growing share of the Ministry of Finance.
<p>
These DGC and ICE will merge into a new Agency, the Portuguese Institute for Cooperation (ICP), the
head of which will be the coordinator of all development cooperation activities, including those parts that
presently are under the responsibility of other Ministries.
<p>
Many ministries and institutions are involved in parts of the aid programme, dating back to the period when
they had direct ties with their respective counterparts in the former colonies. About ten per cent (1990) of
total ODA was shared by the Ministries of Planning and Administration, Youth and Mass Media,
Employment and Social Security, Education, Health, Defence and Internal Administration, and Public
Works, Transport and Communications. Depending on the area of work, their activities are sometimes
coordinated by the ICE or the DGC. In 1991 a Fund for Economic Cooperation (FCE) was established for
extending financial support to the PALOP's and other developing countries - falling within the general
development cooperation framework - and to promote Portuguese direct investments and trade related
projects. The Credits Insurance Company (COSEC) operates in all foreign countries for the insurance of
Portuguese investments.
<p>
It is not known whether a (central) policy planning unit for development cooperation does exist. In 1985 an
Interministerial Commission for Cooperation (CIC) was set up for the coordination of the aid programme. It
has only met three times since. The CIC includes representatives of DGC, ICE, and the other ministries
involved in aid. In the envisaged reorganisation of the administrational set-up, the CIC will be revitalised,
and start with regular meetings on sector-policies, and possibly merged with the CCC.
<p> 
Presently, in consultations with the developing countries concerned, two year 'framework programmes' for
cooperation are worked out. Common norms for handling of aid requests have been worked out by the DGC
and the ICE. Within the new set-up streamlining of procedures and the elaboration of planning, assessment
and evaluation mechanisms are foreseen. 
<p>
<hr><a name="adv"><h3>Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</h3></a>
<p>
An Advisory Commission for Cooperation (CCC) was created in 1985. It includes representatives of the
implementing bodies and ministries, including the COSEC, the Investments, Trade and Tourism Agency
(ICEP), the Agency for Investments and Entrepreneurial Participation (IPE), as well as various trade and
investment associations. Parliamentarians and NGOs are not represented, only commercial interests. The
CCC has never met since its creation, although it was supposed to meet twice a year. Also the CCC might
be revitalised within the re-organisation of the aid administration and possibly be merged with the CIC. Both
the CIC and the CCC are chaired by the Secretary of State for Development Cooperation.
<p>
In addition, the Portuguese Association for Economic Development and Cooperation (ELO) has to be
mentioned. ELO is a non-profit organisation founded by the private sector, and funded by Portuguese
business communities that work in Lusophone countries. It acts as the Development Cooperation Agency of
the private sector. One of ELO's objectives for the coming years is to ensure the improvement of the
contacts between the Government, the NGOs and the private sector. It is very much in favour of the
establishment of a transparent consultative structure between these three actors. It has asked the Government
to take initiatives in this direction. ELO considers attention for the social, cultural and scientific aspects of
development cooperation essential for effective economic cooperation. It is of the opinion that available
knowledge and information on these aspects should be coordinated.
<p>
In Parliament the Commission on Foreign Affairs regularly receives reports of the DGC and the ICE.
However, there is no regular scrutiny by Parliament.
<p>
<a name="ngo"><HR><h3>Non-State Sources of Advice</h3></a>
<p>
In Portugal 36 NGOs are involved in development cooperation. They only get a limited support from
government funds; their development work is for the greater part co-financed by the EU. Since 1985 there is
a representative Platform of NGOs with an Executive Committee. Recognising the importance of the role of
NGOs however, the Government has initiated discussions with the NGOs on the possibilities for establishing
a more structural and effective mutual relationship. NGOs demand more transparency of Government aid
policies and procedures and more information on Government aid activities. The Government also finances
directly NGO activities in developing countries.
<p>
According to the 1991 OECD/EADI survey in Portugal 12 institutes are involved in development research
and training. It is not known to what extent they participate in government cooperation activities.
<p>
<hr>
<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="../images/logo.gif"></a>
<i>Updated on November 7, 1995</i><br>
