<html>
<header>
<title>Institutional Framework for Development Cooperation in Austria</title>
</header>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><hr><p><IMG align=middle SRC  = "../images/at.jpg"><h3>Institutional Framework for Development Cooperation in Austria</h3></center>
<br> 
<hr><h3>Sources</h3>
<h5><ul><li>Kooij, A. and R. Mevis.
1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen
European Countries</i>. The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The
report is available from: NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The
Hague, the Netherlands.
</h5>
<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"><IMG align=top SRC =
"../images/acro.jpg"></a>
</ul><p>

<hr>
<p>
The legislative basis for Austria's aid programme is the Development Cooperation Act of 1974 and
subsequent Acts in 1977, 1983 and 1989. Development cooperation is not the responsibility of one minister,
but is spread over several ministries. Till 1989 development cooperation was the responsibility of the
Federal Chancellor and thereafter the competence of the Minister of Foreign Affairs. Since 1991 a State
Secretary for Integration and Development Cooperation, who heads the Department for Development
Cooperation in the Federal Chancellery (BKA) is responsible. The State Secretary is responsible for:
bilateral technical aid, co-financing programmes, humanitarian and emergency aid and parts of the
multilateral financial assistance. The financial efforts in these areas however, amount to less than 30 per
cent of the bilateral programme in 1992. The Ministry of Foreign Affairs is responsible for multilateral aid.
The Ministry of Finance is responsible for financial aid (a.o. debt relief) and concessional official export
credits. The Ministry of the Interior is responsible for aid to refugees (in Austria), the Ministry of
Agriculture for food aid and the Ministry of Science and Research as well as the Ministry of Education are
both partly responsible for the scholarship programme. 
<p>
Since Austrian law does not allow the government to carry out its own programmes (principle of
subsidiarity), there is no governmental aid agency for the implementation of project. Implementation is
contracted out to private firms and NGOs or implemented by the federal L„nder and Municipalities.
<p>
The Secretary at the BKA is responsible for the overall coordination, programming and reporting on aid
policies, with the above mentioned extensive limitations. Policy planning is done by a Planning and
Programming which comes under the competence of the Department for Development Cooperation of the
BKA. During the coming re-organisation the number and expertise of the currently small number of staff in
the department will be enlarged and up-graded. 
<p>
To strengthen the coordination of the aid programme an Interministerial Committee for the Coordination of
Aid was established in 1992, including a dozen senior officials of the various ministries. The Committee is
chaired by the Director-General of the Department for Development Cooperation. The Committee can issue
non-binding recommendations only. 

<p><hr>
<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="../images/logo.gif"></a> <i>Updated on November 7, 1995</i><br>
Developer's Note: These pages were developed for use on the Netscape browser. Please address comments on content or style to <a href="mailto:pb@ecdpm.org">Peter Ballantyne</a>, Information Programme, ECDPM</H6>
<HR>
</BODY>
