</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>IIED European Programme - EC Aid and Sustainable Development</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#009999" alink="#999999" vlink="#99CCCC"><a href="index.html"><img border=0 align=right width=183 height=163 src="pix/sublogo.gif"></a><small>The material that follows has been provided by <b><a href="../index.html">International Institute for Environment and Development (IIED)</a></b></small><hr><h3>Climate support: strengthening the EU response<p>EC Aid and Sustainable Development Briefing Paper, No. 9, 1996</h3>

<I>Development agencies have significantly expanded their support for the developing country response to climate change over the past few years (see Briefing Paper No. 6). The UN Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC), which has been ratified by the European Union and its Member States, came into force in March 1994. As a Party to the Convention, the European Union is obliged to act to further the aims of the climate treaty through financial support, technology transfer and capacity strengthening for developing nations</I>. 
<p>
<H3>What is climate support?</H3>

There are two main ways in which nations can respond to the threat of climate change:
<ul>
<li>by reducing emissions to keep the scale of the climate warming as low as possible; and
<li>by preparing to adapt to climate change .
</ul><p>
The reason for this two-fold approach is that the emissions reductions required to avert climate change completely are considerable and some degree of environmental change is inevitable over coming decades.
<p>
The Climate Convention commits all nations to action on both of these fronts. In addition, the major industrialized nations are obliged to support the developing nation response. There are two reasons for this “climate support”. First, the industrialized world is responsible for the bulk of past emissions. Second, the future emissions contribution of the developing world may overwhelm that of the North, further compounding the climate threat. 
<p>
The EU has taken a lead in calling for stronger controls on greenhouse gas emissions, aligning itself with the Alliance of Small Island States (AOSIS) in the climate negotiations. It has yet to take a similar lead as far as climate support is concerned. 
<p>
Specifically, the EU could assist the implementation of the Climate Convention in ACP countries through: 
<ul>
<li>the establishment of inventories of greenhouse gases and sinks;
<li>the preparation and implementation of adaptive climate strategies for countries vulnerable to climate change, particularly coastal regions and small island states;
<li>the promotion of clean and efficient energy sources;
<li>efforts to limit deforestation, the burning of forest and agriculture land, and other carbon emitting land use changes; and,
<li>the introduction of new agricultural practices to reduce methane emissions.
</ul>
In this briefing paper, examples are given of current climate support projects being undertaken by EU Member States and by others.

<H3>Action within the European Union</H3>

Member States are involved in a number of bilateral funding activities. Most are explicitly targeted at supporting developing nations in meeting their current formal obligations under the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change. Some initiatives go further in promoting measures that may be required in future years.
<ul>
<li>The German Agency for Technical Cooperation (GTZ), for example, has set up a programme of national studies for developing countries. Priority is being given to  energy-related national studies. Studies are underway in Tanzania and Zambia, amongst others, and are planned for Namibia, Zimbabwe and the Dominican Republic. See box 1 for further details.
<p>
<li>The Swedish International Development Cooperation Agency, through the Stockholm Environment Institute, is funding a study of adaptive responses to the impact of climate change in India as well as an information dissemination project. The Swedish Government, along with other national and international agencies, has funded a study of African policy options and responses to global climate change.
<p>
<li>The Netherlands Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Development Cooperation is establishing country study programmes in Ghana, Senegal and elsewhere on greenhouse gas inventories, vulnerability assessment, and technology options, policy instruments and costs.
<p>
<li>Denmark has established the Danish Cooperation for Environment and Development (DANCED), based on additional finance, to tackle global environmental problems and implement the Earth Summit agreements. DANCED will concentrate on the themes of urban areas, forests, biological diversity and coastal zones (Southeast Asia and southern Africa). The Danish government has contributed to a climate study undertaken by the Tata Energy Research Institute and a national greenhouse gas abatement study in Zimbabwe.
<p>
<li>The French Global Environment Facility, again based on additional finance, intends to catalyze national aid efforts in the areas of climate change, biodiversity, ozone depletion and international waters. Projects will be integrated into larger sustainable development programmes and focus on capacity-strengthening and training in clean technologies. 
</ul><p>
<H3>Delivering a coordinated response</H3>

Concern has been voiced during the climate negotiations that bilateral initiatives may undercut the aims of the Climate Convention if some degree of coordination, or at least mutual awareness of activities, is not achieved.  In line with the development cooperation provisions of the Treaty on European Union, the EU has a special responsibility to ensure that Community actions and those of the Member States are well-coordinated and complement each other.

Exploring joint implementation

Alongside traditional development assistance projects, industrialized nations are also exploring the potential of “joint implementation” (see Briefing Paper No. 6). Measures to control greenhouse gas emissions and to promote the removal of gases through sink enhancement (such as tree-planting) vary in cost from nation to nation. Cooperation between nations can improve cost-effectiveness as one nation subsidizes measures taken in another, taking credit for the emissions reductions that ensue.

A lively debate has surrounded the issue of joint implementation over the past few years and there has been much discussion concerning criteria for such schemes which will ensure that these projects are effective and do not disadvantage poorer countries. Under the Climate Convention, a pilot phase of projects, or activities, “implemented jointly” is taking place. This particular wording has been adopted to underline the fact that there is no agreement as yet regarding criteria for joint implementation schemes.
<p>
<center>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<tr><td><center><h4>Box 1. Support for the Implementation of the Climate Convention</h4></center>The German Agency for Technical Cooperation (GTZ), on behalf of the Ministry of Economic Cooperation and Development, is currently supporting developing countries in preparing the country studies called for by the Climate Convention.   The programme of activities concentrates on establishing emission balances and on the abatement of greenhouse gas emissions, particularly carbon dioxide mitigation. The regional focus is on Southern Africa and Asia.<p>In Zambia, GTZ has supported an inventory study and survey of mitigation options and political strategies for capacity building, executed by the Ministry of Water and Energy Development with support from the Southern Centre for Energy and Environment in Zimbabwe. The project has covered the estimation of sources and sinks and future emissions trends, the identification of cost-effective options for avoiding emissions and the development of recommendations for national abatement targets.<p>In Tanzania, the Center for Environment, Energy, Sciences and Technology in Dar es Salaam has been undertaking a greenhouse gas mitigation study on behalf of the Ministry of Tourism, Natural Resources and Environment. The study has considered not only technological options for reducing emissions, including cost-effectiveness, but also social, cultural and political aspects of the implementation of these options and the relevance for national energy policy.	<p>The Tanzanian project is part of the first phase of a longer term programme of support for prompt start measures to implement the Climate Convention. During the second phase, from late 1996, the aim is to encourage activities that go beyond the formal reporting requirements of the Climate Convention.  During this latter phase, application-oriented investigations of the technological and political potential to limit emissions will be funded and relevant strategies and policy recommendations will be developed and integrated into sectoral policy and energy planning. Training for local personnel, capacity-building for institutions and networking for major actors will be critical components of this work.<p>	Projects which have positive benefits at the micro- and macro-economic levels-by saving energy or improving energy efficiency-and reduce greenhouse gas emissions will be prioritized.<p>  For example, a study of the use of renewable energies for power supply in Namibia is at the planning stage. The project will consider potential sites for renewable energy plant, design requirements for solar thermal and wind generators, evaluate the economics of selected generating plant and assess environmental benefits.<p>	The Ministry of Transport and Energy in Zimbabwe is supporting plans for a study of the potential for regional power pooling in Southern Africa. The survey will consider the emissions savings that might result from power pooling, technical feasibility, whether or not regional authorities would be prepared to support such an initiative, and the technical, political and administrative pre-requisites if such a scheme is to be successful.<p>	For further information on the GTZ programme, contact: Holger Liptow, Energy Division, GTZ, Postfach 5180, 65726 Eschborn, Germany.
</td></tr></table>
</center>
<p>
The pilot phase covers activities implemented jointly among Annex I Parties (the richer, industrialized nations) and, on a voluntary basis, between Annex I and non-Annex I Parties. Pilot phase activities should:
<ul>
<li>be compatible with and supportive of national environment and development priorities and strategies;
<li>contribute to cost-effectiveness in achieving global benefits;
<li>be conducted in a comprehensive manner covering all relevant sources, sinks and reservoirs of greenhouse gases; and 
<li>bring about real, measurable and long-term environmental benefits related to the mitigation of climate change that would not have occurred in the absence of such activities.
</ul><p>
The financing of these activities should be additional to existing financial obligations and overseas development assistance flows. For the time being, Parties will not be able to claim credit against their own national emissions reduction targets for these projects.
<p>
As of autumn 1995, 17 such projects had been endorsed by the governments of the countries involved. A number of Member States are setting up joint implementation projects with developing countries and have established schemes in partnership with nations in Eastern Europe and the Russian Federation. For example, the Government of The Netherlands has committed NLG12 million annually over the period 1997-99 for (co-)financing pilot projects in developing nations and the same amount for projects in Central and Eastern Europe. The United States is investing in developing nations in Central and South America. The private sector plays an important role in many of these projects, making available additional investment.
<p>
Most existing projects are in the energy field - solar electrification, wind energy, energy saving, compressed natural gas, coal-to-gas conversion - as it is in this area that the most significant gains can be made in reducing growth in greenhouse gas emissions. 
<p>
In Costa Rica, for instance, the construction of 55 windmills (20 MW) began in spring 1995. The Plantas Eolicas project represents the first commercial-scale wind power generation in Central America and is a US$30 million joint initiative between the Costa Rican national utility company, Instituto Costaricense de Electricidad, and three private American firms (with the endorsement of the US Government). It has been estimated that the project will result in the reduction of carbon dioxide emissions by 100,000 tons a year if fossil fuel-generated power is displaced by the wind power that the project produces. The advantages for Costa Rica are assistance with compliance with the Climate Convention, a reliable source of electricity and diversification of supply, the transfer of modern technology, job creation, and risk reduction in investment.
<p>
At present, there are no active joint implementation projects in the regions of Africa or the Pacific. Continued lack of involvement will hinder expansion of clean technology in these regions.

<H3>Progress with the Global Environment Facility</H3>

The Global Environment Facility (GEF) is to operate the financial mechanism of the Climate Convention for a further four years. It has been specified, under the Climate Convention, that projects funded by the GEF should be cost-effective, supportive of national development priorities and focused, at least at first, on enabling activities that would help developing countries implement the Convention.
<p>
As of December 1995, the GEF Work Programme covered funding to a total of US$328 million in the focal area of climate change. Most projects are directed towards supporting developing country responses to the Climate Convention and, to date, tend towards emissions control issues rather than adaptive strategies. There is a strong capacity-building element.
<p>
To cite one example, the Maldives has received US$1 million through the GEF to undertake a greenhouse gas inventory and adaptation assessment project. The objective of the project is to increase the capacity of this small island state in the areas of emissions control and vulnerability assessment. The project involves diffusion of the approach and findings to other small island developing nations so that they can share in the capacity-building exercise.
<p>
In Africa, the Sudan is involved in a US$0.3 million project to strengthen its capacity to respond to the requirements of the Climate Convention. It is also the focus of a US$1.5 million study of carbon sequestration and biodiversity protection through community-based rangeland rehabilitation.
<p>
US$2.5 million has been allocated by the GEF to a household energy project in Mali and US$2 million to a decentralized wind electric power project in Mauritania. Zimbabwe is undertaking a US$7 million photovoltaic project for household and community use.

<p>
<center>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<tr><td><center><h4>Box 2. Climate Action Programme</h4></center>
The South Pacific Regional Environment Programme (SPREP) has established the Pacific Island Climate Change Action Programme (PICCAP) to coordinate and implement all climate and sea level rise activities in the region.   SPREP is the leading environmental agency for the South Pacific region. It is an autonomous intergovernmental organization with members from 26 countries.<p>	The Climate Change Programme focuses on scientific research, impact assessment, response strategies and training, education and public awareness.<p>	Activities are currently underway in the Cook Islands, Federated States of Micronesia, Fiji, French Polynesia, Guam, Kiribati, Marshall Islands, Nauru, New Caledonia, Niue, Palau, Papua New Guinea, Solomon Islands, Tokelua, Tonga, Tuvalu, Vanuatu and Western Samoa.<p>Over the next two to three years, the SPREP Secretariat aims to assist members develop and plan their national climate and sea level change policies as required by the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change.<p>	For further information, contact: SPREP, PO Box 240, Apia, Western Samoa.
</td></tr></table>
</center>
<p>
<H3>The way forward for the European Union</H3>

Alongside the more vulnerable developing nations, the EU has taken the lead in calling for stronger emissions controls under the Climate Convention. Building on this political momentum, it should develop a clear policy stance linking climate and development cooperation. This could build on the growing body of experience with climate support gained through bilateral programmes, the Global Environment Facility and pilot joint implementation projects.
<p>
Three areas emerge as priorities for the future:
<ul>
<li>working towards a coordinated response within the European Union, learning from existing bilateral and international efforts and drawing on the experience of Member States;
<li>engaging in a dialogue with the ACP States to discover their needs and priorities;
<li>integrating climate concerns into mainstream development assistance programming, particularly in the areas of energy, agriculture, forests, industry, transport and coastal zone management. 
</ul>
<H3>To find out more...</H3>

Up-to-date information on the climate debate, focusing on issues relevant to the developing world, can be found in the free quarterly bulletin Tiempo published by IIED and the University of East Anglia (Tiempo, c/o Mick Kelly, School of Environmental Sciences, University of East Anglia, Norwich NR4 7TJ, UK). 
<p>
The most comprehensive source of information on the climate negotiations is the Earth Negotiations Bulletin, published by the International Institute for Sustainable Development, 161 Portage Ave East, Winnipeg, Manitoba R3B 0Y4, Canada.
<p>
The Climate Information Exchange Programme (CC:INFO), established by UNEP and the UNFCCC Secretariat, maintains a database concerning country activities on climate change and support for developing countries. CC:INFO can be contacted at CC:INFO, UNFCCC Secretariat, Palais des Nations, CH-1211 Geneva 10, Switzerland. Information regarding the Climate Convention and related matters can be obtained from the UN Information Unit for Conventions at the same address.
<p>
Joint Implementation Quarterly, a very useful source of information regarding current developments, can be obtained from Foundation JIN, Zernike Science Park Center 2, 9747 AN Groningen, The Netherlands.
<p>
<I>The authors of this briefing paper are Mick Kelly and Sarah Granich. Mick Kelly is a Reader with the Climatic Research Unit at the University of East Anglia and Director of the Climate Programme at IIED. Sarah Granich is an environmental writer and consultant to IIED. With Mick Kelly and Richard Sandbrook, she is editor of Tiempo, a bulletin on climate change and the Third World.</I>
