<HEAD>
<title>Collaboration between CDR and Danida on Aid Impact Research</title>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<hr>
<H3><center><IMG SRC = "../images/dk.jpg"><p>
Collaboration between CDR and Danida on Aid Impact Research:<BR>A Case Method Approach to Discussing the Issues<br>
<i>Lizz Kleemeier</i><p></h3>
<h5>CDR Working Paper 96.4</center>
<p>
<IMG align=left SRC = "../images/cdr.jpg" height=60></a> This paper should be cited as:<br> Kleemeier, L. 1996. Collaboration between CDR and Danida on Aid Impact Research: Between Politics and Technical Rationality. (CDR Working Paper No. 96.4). Copenhagen: Centre for Development Research.<br> E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:cdr@cdr.dk">cdr@cdr.dk</A>
</h5><p>
<hr>
<P>
<H3>Contents</H3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#abs">Abstract</a>
<li><a href="#int">1. Introduction</a>
<li><a href="#dis">2. Discussion of key terms</a>
<li><a href="#res">2.1 Research</a>
<li><a href="#col">2.2 Collaboration</a>
<li><a href="#imp">2.3 Impact of development assistance</a>
<li><a href="#two">3. Two methodologies for stakeholder participation</a>
<li><a href="#fou">3.1 Fourth generation evaluation</a>
<li><a href="#uti">3.2 Utilization-focused evaluation</a>
<li><a href="#cas">4. Case: Collaboration to develop research on project impact</a>
<li><a href="#def">4.1 Defining the research agenda</a>
<li><a href="#app">4.2 Applied research useful in assistance design and management</a>
<li><a href="#appl">4.3 Applied research useful in political accountability</a>
<li><a href="#con">5. Conclusions</a>
<li><a href="#bib">Bibliography</a></ul>
<P>
<a name=abs></a><H3>Abstract</H3>
<P>
<I>The Center for Development Research (CDR) has recently committed
itself to expanding its research on the impact of development
assistance, in part as a means to improve and expand cooperation
with the Danish International Development Agency, Danida. This
paper is intended to facilitate discussion among CDR researchers
and Danida staff about how to structure their collaboration in
developing and designing aid impact research. In doing so, the
paper draws upon state-of-the-art methodologies which professional
evaluators use to involve stakeholders in evaluations of their
projects and programs (Guba and Lincoln 1989, Patton 1986). A
hypothetical example illustrates how CDR researchers could adapt
these methodologies to develop a research agenda, and to develop
specific issues from that agenda into research proposals, in collaboration
with Danida staff. The key methods in this are semi-structured
interviewing and the constant comparative method of analysis.</I>
<P>
<I>The hypothetical case can facilitate discussing among CDR and
Danida staff by giving them a common starting point. By pointing
out what they do and do not like or find feasible in the case,
staff from the two organizations can generate ideas for a mutually
acceptable methodology for collaboration. The paper's conclusions
start this discussion by making explicit two prerequisites for
the methodology described: that CDR researchers will invest considerably
more time in the very preliminary phase of research, i.e., topic
selection; and that CDR's present procedures for approving Research
Council (RUF)-destined research proposals are modified.</I>
<P>
<a name=int></a><H3>1. Introduction</H3>
<P>
The Center for Development Research (CDR) has committed itself
to sending to its governing Board in mid-1996 a plan for expanding
CDR research on the impact of development assistance.  The impetus
to expand research in this area stems in part from an emerging
consensus that Danida, the wing of the Danish Foreign Ministry
which administers Danish development assistance, and CDR, a research
institute affiliated with the Ministry, must collaborate more
and better.  Most observers and participants agree that the two
organizations have not cooperated sufficiently in the past.  Now,
however, a growing number of the people concerned believe that
collaboration should increase and improve.  This was the context
in which the Board urged the CDR to develop a research profile
on aid impact, and CDR pledged to do so.  Thus, aid impact research
at CDR will have the manifest function of contributing to knowledge
about how donor interventions affect the development process,
and the not-quite-latent function of developing a model for collaboration
between CDR and Danida.
<P>
The primary purpose of this paper is to facilitate a discussion
among CDR researchers and Danida staff about how to structure
their collaboration in developing and designing research on aid
impact.  In doing this, the paper draws upon state-of-the-art
methodologies which professional evaluators use to involve stakeholders
in focusing and designing the evaluations of projects and programs.
 Section 3 below summarizes the salient points of two such methodologies:
fourth generation evaluation, as presented by Guba and Lincoln
(1989), and utilization-focused evaluation, as presented by Patton
(1986).  Section 4 presents a hypothetical case of CDR researchers
using elements of these methodologies to collaborate with Danida
in designing research on the impact of Danida rural drinking water
projects.  The concluding section suggests how CDR and Danida
staff can use the case study and other information provided in
the paper to discuss collaboration in regard to aid impact research.
<P>
First, though, the next section reviews the various and sometimes
conflicting meanings or connotations of the three terms which
are key to the discussion: research, collaboration, and aid impact.
 In this paper, each term will have a specific definition or connotation,
as explained in Section 2.  However, CDR and Danida staff could
profitably launch the general discussion of their collaboration
through specific discussions of how they wish to use each term.
 In this respect, as in all others, the paper represents an effort
to raise and structure issues for discussion between the two parties,
and not to give answers.
<P>
<a name=dis></a><H3>2. Discussion of Key Terms</H3>
<P>
<a name=res></a><B>2.1 Research</b>
<P>
Patton, a professional evaluator who will be extensively quoted
later in the paper, conceptualizes research as a continuum along
the dimension of generalizability (Patton 1990, 145-162).  <I>&quot;The
continuum ranges from very basic, long-term research aimed at
theory development and knowledge for its own sake to highly action-oriented
research aimed at solving immediate problems in as short a time
as possible&quot;</I> (Ibid, 158).  In other words, &quot;generalizability&quot;
basically refers to the theoretical aspirations of a particular
piece of research.  One can best explain this through describing
in terms of this concept several points (or intervals) on the
continuum, e.g., basic research and applied research at one end;
formative evaluation and summative evaluation somewhere toward
the middle; and participatory research at the other end.  However,
the reader should bear in mind from the outset that this continuum
is analogous to a spectrum, not a line.  On a line, each point
is discrete and uniquely definable.  In a spectrum, some points
are clearly occupied by one color or another, but at the points
where one color merges into the next, one cannot definitely identify
the color.  Similarly, whether to label a particular piece of
research as &quot;basic&quot; versus &quot;applied,&quot; or &quot;applied&quot;
versus &quot;evaluative,&quot; and so forth may depend largely
on the eye of the beholder.
<P>
In basic research, the researcher aims to develop a theory with
explanatory power in a variety of contexts quite removed from
the original research situation.  The research through its theoretical
contribution, in other words, will lead to very broad generalizations.
 Samuel Popkin (1979), for instance, studies Vietnamese peasants
in order to develop a theory of rational action applicable to
human behavior regardless of setting.  For instance, rational
choice theory is currently being used to predict how U.S. parents
would make schooling decisions if provided with educational vouchers.
<P>
In applied research, the researcher aims to develop theory which
permits generalization across contexts which share certain characteristics
with the original research setting.  Most development research
is therefore applied research, in that it produces generalizations
applicable only in development contexts, and often only in some
sub-set of these.  Hyden (1983), for instance, offers some generalizations
about African subsistence peasants, based on his studies in Tanzania.
 His theory of the economy of affection, however, does not even
apply to Tanzanian farmers.
<P>
Patton places summative and formative evaluations in the middle
of the spectrum.  Formative evaluations make generalizations only
about the specific program, project, policy, etc. being evaluated
(Patton 1990, 156).   A formative evaluation, for instance, might
investigate whether a child health project succeeded in reducing
diarrheal rates and how the various component activities contributed
to this.  Summative evaluations lie closer to applied research
because they investigate whether a program, policy, etc. has been
effective in a specific context <I>and</I> under what conditions
it is likely to be effective elsewhere (Ibid, 155).  For example,
a summative evaluation might make generalizations about the relative
effectiveness of breast-feeding, oral rehydration solutions, and
vaccinations in reducing children's diarrhea.
<P>
At the other end of the spectrum from basic research lies participatory
research in which the objective, as Robert Chambers describes
is, <I>&quot;is less to gather data, and more to start a process&quot;</I>
(Chambers 1994b, 1266).  The researcher aims to mobilize and empower
a given group of people through helping them to gather, analyze,
and use information.  If a participatory researcher worked in
a Vietnamese or Tanzanian village, the villagers in that particular
village in the end should have taken steps to better their lives
based on knowledge which they have gained with the help of the
researcher.  The information is not &quot;generalized&quot; beyond
the use to which those villagers put it in that particular time
period.
<P>
Patton's conceptualization of research is reminiscent of the distinction
which Glaser and Strauss (1967, 32-35) draw between substantive
and formal theories.  Substantive theory provides a framework
of inquiry within a substantive area such as race relations, delinquency,
or education.  Formal theory deals with a higher level of abstraction,
e.g., stigma, deviant behavior, or socialization.  <I>&quot;Substantive
and formal theories,&quot;</I> Glaser and Strauss write, <I>&quot;exist
on distinguishable levels of generality, which differ only in
terms of degree&quot;</I> (Ibid, 33).  In both Patton's work,
and that of Glaser and Strauss, the operative concept is <I>generalizability</I>,
which can vary in degree.
<P>
One advantage of Patton's conceptualization lies precisely in
linking the concepts of research and theoretical generalizability,
both of which are constitutive of social (and natural) science.
 This provides a certain face validity to his conceptualization.
 Another advantage is that Patton's approach elegantly encompasses
very different types of research.  The qualitative research advocated
by Glaser and Strauss, and the participatory research which Chambers
advocates, can both be accommodated within &quot;research&quot;
defined as a continuum along the dimension of generalizability.
 The third advantage to Patton's formulation is that it does not
include extraneous characteristics which would transform the continuum
into a hierarchy.  Different points along the continuum correspond
to different ways of conceptualizing problems, designing data
collection, disseminating findings, and so forth.  Nothing in
this, however, suggests that one type of research is better than
another.
<P>
It is this third advantage which above all justifies adopting
in this paper Patton's conceptualization of research.  &quot;Research&quot;
often becomes an emotionally laden and politically charged symbol
in battles for status, funds, and so forth.  Patton explains how
these battles are fought at a symbolic level, as follows:
<P>
<I> &quot;...researchers engaged in research at various points
along the continuum have very strong opinions and feelings about
researchers at other points along the continuum.  Research can
be a highly political activity that generates opposing opinions
and strong emotions.  Basic and applied researchers, for example,
would often dispute even calling formative and action research
by the name </I>research<I>.  The standards that basic researchers
apply to what they would consider &quot;good&quot; research excludes
(sic) even some applied research because it may not manifest the
conceptual clarity and theoretical rigor in real-world situations
that basic researchers value.  Formative and action researchers,
on the other hand, may attack basic research for being esoteric
and irrelevant&quot;</I> (Patton 1990, 158).
<P>
Patton implies that emotions can run even higher in situations
where persons from academic and professional (&quot;real-world&quot;)
milieux mix:
<P>
<I> &quot;On the whole, within universities and among scholars,
the status hierarchy in science attributes the highest status
to basic research, secondary status to applied research, little
status to summative evaluation research, and virtually no status
to formative and action research.  The status hierarchy is reversed
in real-world settings, where people with problems attribute the
greatest significance to action and formative research that can
help them to solve their problems in a timely way and attach the
least importance to basic research, which they consider remote
and largely irrelevant to what they are doing on a day-to-day
basis&quot;  (Ibid, 158-59).</I>
<P>
This clash between academic and professional values manifests
itself in the contrasting views of CDR versus Danida staff in
regard to research.  CDR staff often articulate a view of research
which makes it more or less synonymous with basic research.  Following
Patton, one can explain this tendency in terms of the academic
norms, values, and attitudes which pervade the organizational
culture at CDR.  A number of the permanent CDR staff have an exclusively
academic background (i.e., employed in universities or research
institutes), while many of the non-permanent staff are students,
recent graduates, or university lecturers.  Their training and
experience, in other words, leads them to value theoretical development
for its own sake.  Danida staff, on the other hand, have largely
professional career patterns (i.e., employed by government or
private sector), although a number of them have graduate degrees.
 They view CDR research as Patton predicts, describing it with
comments such as  <I>&quot;The research undertaken by the Centre
is often not relevant for Danida, nor is it up to date,&quot;</I>
and <I>&quot;The Centre is slow in reacting to Danida's pressing
needs and immediate demands&quot;</I> (Danida 1996, 64-65).  Good
research, for Danida staff, provides answers to the questions
which they confront in their work.
<P>
Patton's remarks about the politics of what will be labelled &quot;research&quot;
are also pertinent to CDR's situation.  In this case, it involves
bureaucratic politics related to the issue of who will set the
work program for CDR researchers.  Due to this, &quot;research&quot;
has become almost inextricably entwined with a notion resembling
academic freedom.  A brief description of the organizational relationship
between CDR and Danida is necessary in order to explain this connotation
of &quot;research.&quot;
<P>
CDR was originally incorporated under a government provision for
ministries, in this case the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, to establish
research institutes in their respective fields so as to <I>&quot;provide
the scientific basis for the decisions made by politicians and
authorities&quot;</I> (SEDIRK 1995).  However, for various historical
reasons, CDR has traditionally enjoyed a high degree of autonomy
from the Ministry, including Danida to which CDR is specifically
&quot;attached.&quot;  One feature of this autonomy has been that
the permanent staff have largely set their own research agendas.
 These research activities are acknowledged by all parties to
be the primary function of CDR staff.  A secondary, relatively
minor, activity of CDR staff has been to act as consultants to
Danida, i.e., to carry out short tasks usually related to the
project cycle.  In other words, a CDR researcher might be a member
of an appraisal, review, or evaluation mission.  CDR staff have
also done consultancies, such as literature reviews, which make
more direct use of the particular skills of researchers.  In all
consultancies, though, Danida staff set the work agenda through
a Terms of Reference which specify the tasks to be completed.
 Danida staff ultimately decide whether the consultants have adequately
fulfilled the Terms of Reference.  
<P>
In this environment, &quot;research&quot; (often used in opposition
to &quot;consultancy&quot;) has become a code word for the prerogative
of CDR staff to use their own judgement in setting their work
programs, and their own standards for evaluating the quality and
completeness of the final product.  A <I>sous-entendu</I> in this
claim for independence is that CDR should play a watch-dog role,
commenting publicly and critically on Danish foreign policy and
development assistance as it affects the Third World.
<P>
For the sake of conceptual precision, this paper will not confound
these organizational issues with the concept of research.  Instead,
they will be considered below in the discussing the requisites
and prerequisites for a viable and productive collaboration between
Danida and CDR staff.  
<P>
<a name=col></a><B>2.2 Collaboration</b>
<P>
This sub-section does not discuss the definition of &quot;collaboration,&quot;
as the concept <I>per se</I> is not ambiguous or otherwise problematic.
 Instead, the sub-section reviews various assumptions about collaboration
between CDR and Danida staff, in order to separate out those assumptions
which are unrealistic or prejudicial, and identify the conditions
for a viable and mutually beneficial collaboration.
<P>
The team which recently evaluated CDR briefly outlined a collaborative
process which, on closer examination, rests on several dubious
assumptions.  The evaluation team recommended,
<P>
<I> &quot;...that the director and relevant research areas [from
CDR] meet with S.1 and the Evaluation and Research department
[from Danida] on a regular basis, to discuss the Centre's involvement
in...research projects, which Danida is interested in having the
Centre undertake.&quot;</I>  (Danida 1996, 68).
<P>
This recommendation rests on three assumptions which will be critiqued
below: CDR can supply researchers and funds to implement research
projects which have been designed without regard to these two
considerations; the Evaluation and Research Department and S.1
(bilateral assistance policy and planning division) can represent
the intended Danida users of the research findings; and these
two offices have a capacity and interest to develop useful research
projects.  
<P>
In regard to the first assumption, it requires a real stretch
of the imagination to envision CDR assigning a researcher to a
presumably long term research project developed by Danida.  At
best, one can imagine CDR would be able to assign a researcher
for a short period, as it has done for Danida consultancies. 
In general, it is more realistic to assume either that none of
CDR's researchers would be suitably qualified for the particular
project, or that the qualified researchers would have on-going
research commitments which preclude more than a token amount of
time to a Danida assignment.  In short, under its present structure,
CDR does not have a large pool of researchers whose current commitments
can be shifted around in order to meet the demands of a client.
<P>
In addition, having Danida staff design the research projects
and send them to CDR for implementation would violate the norms
of the organizational culture at CDR, as explained above.  Unlike
for consultancies, CDR researchers have always retained the primary
responsibility for conceptualization and design of research. 
Unless those norms change, which is difficult to imagine, CDR
staff will not react very positively to research being formulated
and carried out along the same lines as consultancies.
<P>
In regard to the second assumption, the most likely users within
Danida of research findings do not work in the two offices mentioned
above, although staff there could in some circumstances use research
findings in their own work.  The Evaluation and Research Department
has the responsibility to see that evaluations and research within
Danida are carried out, but would generally not make direct use
of the information gathered.  As a policy-making body, S.1 in
principle would use the output from certain research projects.
 However, there are seven other divisions (S.2-S.8) at the same
organizational level as S.1, and these offices have a more immediate
role in policy-making because they have more direct responsibility
for the different segments of the Danish assistance program. 
Also, a good deal of decision-making power over the programs has
been decentralized to the Danish embassies.  Finally, the sectoral
specialists who advise on and oversee the technical quality of
program planning and implementation work in yet another office,
TSA (roughly translatable as Technical Advisory Services).  These
professionals would in fact be among the most likely consumers
of research findings.  
<P>
The exact configuration of intended primary users would depend
on the particular project.  For instance, for an impact evaluation
of a rural drinking water project (the example used below for
the case), it might be the TSA staff who handle water projects,
and representatives from the embassies and S divisions covering
countries in which drinking water has been selected as a sector
for future Danish assistance.  Representatives from the Evaluation
and Research Department and S.1 could hardly be expected to articulate
the information needs of this group.
<P>
The third assumption underestimates the time, work, and expertise
needed to identify useful research questions.  At minimum, developing
a particular piece of research on program or project impact will
require a good familiarity with the literature and experience
in the particular area, and a good sense of who will use the research
and toward what ends.  It does not seem reasonable to expect the
generalist staff in these two offices to take on this additional
task, and execute it with the care and attention required.
<P>
A more productive way to think about the collaborative process
would be to make the three opposite assumptions:  the individual
researcher who will carry out the research will play a key facilitating
role in developing the research topic or agenda; this researcher
will identify and work on developing the research design with
the Danida staff who have a felt need for the research findings;
the process of developing a research topic or agenda requires
time, a methodology (i.e., rules and procedures for its conduct),
and methods for its successful implementation.
<P>
Section 3 will review how evaluators carry out a collaborative
process based on similar assumptions in defining evaluation questions
and designing an evaluation methodology in conjunction with those
whose program or project is being evaluated.  The hypothetical
case in Section 4 provides a springboard for Danida and CDR staff
to discuss whether these state-of-the-art evaluation methodologies
have any relevance for their situation.
<P>
In addition to the above three requisites, successful collaboration
requires a certain attitude toward each other on the part of the
CDR and Danida staff involved.  This is analogous to the prerequisite
attitude which a participatory researcher must have toward the
men and women with whom he or she will collaborate.  In this situation,
a researcher who did not have a great deal of respect for the
local knowledge and experience of these people would not succeed,
despite applying state-of-the-art participatory methodologies
and methods.  For instance, a researcher who said things such
as, <I>&quot;We can't let these people tell us what to research;
that's our job,&quot; </I>or <I>&quot;If these people want us
to do research which benefits them, then they're going to have
to work out detailed research questions and come to us&quot;</I>
would make a poor candidate for participatory research.  A CDR
researcher who said similar things, replacing &quot;local people&quot;
with &quot;Danida,&quot; would best stick to non-collaborative
research.  Likewise, Danida staff who do not believe that research
can answer any questions of value to them in their work should
not involve themselves in collaborative efforts.
<P>
<a name=imp></a><B>2.3 Impact of Development Assistance</B>
<P>
The textbook definition of impact evaluation is as follows:
<P>
<I> &quot;An impact evaluation gauges the extent to which a program
causes change in the desired direction.  It implies that there
is a set of pre-specified, operationally defined goals and criteria
of success; a program that has impact is one that achieves some
movement or change toward the desired objectives&quot;</I> (Rossi,
Freeman, and Wright 1979, 41).
<P>
The appropriate methodology for isolating change which is due
to the program, and measuring the size of that change, is an experimental
or quasi-experimental research design (Ibid, 42; Valadez and Bamberger
1994, 228).
<P>
During the 1970s and early 1980s, donors increasingly adopted
this view of impact and its evaluation, due to the spread of logical
framework analysis (Binnendijk 1989, 208; Cracknell 1988, 80).
 Using a logical framework approach requires an intervention's
designers to specify its activities, outputs, and objectives,
and then give objectively verifiable indicators for each, as well
as state how or from where data on these indicators will be obtained.
 Thus, incorporated into the design of an intervention, are plans
for a evaluation of its impact, fully in line with the textbook
definition of the term.  Furthermore, donors and evaluators worked
on the assumption that the impact of interventions should be tested
using experimental and quasi-experimental research designs (Binnendijk
1989, 209).  
<P>
However, the experience with using this concept and methodology
for studying development assistance impact eventually led donors
to adopt a much broader notion of impact and much greater methodological
diversity.  Two sets of problems with evaluations based on the
logical framework caused this shift. 
<P>
The first set of problems stemmed from the inevitable focus of
the evaluations on the objectives as stated in the logical framework
(Binnendijk 1989, 210, 214).  Over time, these objectives might
have changed or become irrelevant, or never have been realistic
and appropriate in the first place.  Meanwhile, other issues,
such as sustainability, might define more relevant information
needs.  The focus on stated objectives also meant that data on
unintended impacts might not be collected.  In any case, the logical
framework provided little guidance as to what type of unintended
impact to search for, and where and how to do so.  
<P>
The second set of problems related to largely to the practical
problems of carrying out quasi-experimental research on development
projects (Ibid, 210-14).  Many projects failed simply to collect
and analyze the specified data, no small task considering that
quasi-experimental research typically requires extensive data
collection from large random samples of both beneficiaries and
control groups before, during, and after implementation, and relatively
sophisticated statistical analysis once the data has been computerized.
 Second, even when projects did manage to collect and analyze
the data, this process often delivered findings long after they
were needed, or was so poorly executed that the findings were
unreliable.  
<P>
There were also conceptual problems in using quasi-experimental
research.  In principal, policy-makers can generalize from the
findings of quasi-experimental research to select the most effective
approach to achieving a given end.  In reality, an intervention
which had proven effective in one area would not necessarily be
successful in another, because so many variables affecting impact
would differ from one context to the next.  The costs and time
required to do quasi-experimental research are not justified,
if the findings are not generalizable.
<P>
To address the first set of problems, donors broadened the focus
and concept of impact evaluation in a number of ways.  For instance,
impact evaluations looked now at unintended impacts, and impacts
related to objectives which had not been part of the original
logical framework, e.g., financial and institutional sustainability,
environmental protection, private sector development, women's
empowerment, cost-effectiveness.  In other words, an impact evaluation
no longer necessarily implied the textbook definition of looking
at progress toward stated objectives.  In fact, the original objectives
could be evaluated, rather than simply accepted as the standard
against which to judge progress.  Impact evaluations might be
carried out during implementation, instead of only ex-post.  Behind
these innovations lay the recognition that 
<P>
<I> &quot;an evaluation's focus should not be dictated in the
basis of some research design or framework developed by 'outsiders,'
but should instead be based upon a dialogue with the intended
management users regarding their actual evaluation questions and
information needs&quot;</I>  (Binnendijk 1989, 214).
<P>
In response to the second set of problems, donors began to use
quasi-experimental research far more selectively (Valadez and
Bamberger 1994, 258-88; Binnendijk 1989, 216).  Most evaluations,
including impact evaluations, were instead based on methods which
delivered information on a wide variety of issues quickly, simply,
and inexpensively.  Some of these methods, for example mini surveys,
were abbreviated versions of methods used in quantitative research.
 Other methods, such as focus group discussions and other types
of semi-structured interviews, had previously been used to complement
quantitative research.  Information from beneficiaries was also
solicited through a range of innovative and creative techniques
such as ranking, case studies, various approaches to matrix-building,
etc.  New methods to structure observation, for instance transect
walks, were introduced.  
<P>
A number of these methods would be fitted together in a methodology
which could be completed in a matter of weeks or a few months,
in contrast to the years required for quasi-experimental research.
 For example, the United States Agency for International Development
(USAID) commissioned quasi-experimental research to investigate
the health impact of a USAID-funded water project in Malawi (Young
and Briscoe 1986).  The field work required eight months, and
the analysis and report writing another seven months.  By contrast,
USAID also commissioned a series of impact evaluations on water
projects, in which teams spent between two and six weeks on data
collection, and the published reports appeared within about four
to six months.  These rapid methodologies saved money as well
as time.  A USAID evaluator estimated that <I>&quot;a probability
sample survey conducted by a U.S.-based firm is likely to cost
$100,000 to $200,000, whereas four to six studies using rapid,
low-cost methods can be completed for this amount&quot;</I> (Kumar
1987b, 4).
<P>
In short, donors have not rejected the textbook definition of
impact, but they have generally subsumed it within a much, much
broader conceptualization.  USAID and OECD use the following definition
of impact:
<P>
<I> &quot;A term indicating whether the project or program has
had an effect on its surroundings in terms of technical, economic,
sociocultural, institutional, and environmental factors&quot;</I>
(Kumar 1989c, vii).
<P>
Another USAID report waxes even more eloquently on the need to
go beyond the traditional definition:
<P>
<I> &quot;The purpose of impact evaluations then is to explore
the terrain, to review what has happened since an intervention
or policy was tried, to collect impressions about the extent to
which the intervention made a difference, to suggest what problems
remain, and to speculate about alternative designs for similar
programs or projects.  Their function, in other words, is to contribute
to more informed decisions, rather than come to a definitive conclusion
that project X led to result Y, and that Y would not have occurred
in the absence of the project&quot;</I> (White 1986, 4).
<P>
<a name=two></a><H3>3. Two Methodologies for Stakeholder Participation</H3>
<P>
The vast academic literature on evaluation methodology has not
contributed much to the evaluation of development assistance,
because this writing comes out of the very different experience
of evaluating domestic social programs, particularly in the United
States.  The report which the Organization of Economic Cooperation
and Development commissioned from two eminent professional evaluators,
Freeman and Rossi, suffered from the same drawback of attempting
to transfer their skill and experience with American domestic
programs to the totally different context of development assistance
(Cracknell 1988, 76).
<P>
However, the two methodologies which will be described below have
been used for evaluating development projects, and therefore do
not suffer from the same limitations as other evaluation methodologies
described in the academic literature.  For that reason, those
generally interested in studying the impact of development assistance
will no doubt find it profitable to learn more about fourth generation
and utilization-focused methodologies.  Readers should remember,
however, the specific reason for reviewing the two methodologies
here: elements of them can be adapted to the process which precedes
actual research on aid impact, namely to the collaborative development
of research topics and projects in this area.
<P>
<a name=fou></a><B>3.1 Fourth Generation Evaluation</B>
<P>
The label &quot;fourth generation&quot; reflects the contrast
which the authors wish to make with previous generations of evaluations,
in which the evaluator's tasks were respectively to measure, to
describe, and to make professional judgements about a program
under evaluation (Guba and Lincoln 1989, 21-49).  Instead, the
role for a fourth generation evaluator is to help stakeholders
outline the issues which need to be resolved in a program, and
to build commitment among stakeholders toward taking the necessary
action. 
<P>
A fourth generation methodology therefore consists largely of
procedures and methods for interacting with stakeholders to help
them articulate their views on the strengths, weaknesses, and
outstanding issues in a program.  This description of the program,
as perceived by the stakeholders, provides the input for drawing
up an &quot;agenda for negotiation,&quot; i.e., the basis for
discussion among the stakeholders about the program's future.
<P>
In carrying out a fourth generation evaluation, the evaluator
uses qualitative methods similar to those which an anthropologist,
sociologist, or other social scientist might use in a study which
aims to portray how the world looks from the perspective of a
particular group of people.  For instance, an anthropologist would
employ qualitative methods in studying the parallels between mythical
thought and how human communities structure their relations with
outsiders (Silverman 1985, 15).  A sociologist might do a qualitative
study of organizations in order to explain how managers perceive
and select job applicants (Silverman and Jones 1975; Silverman
1985, 14).  Two sociologists developed a new method of qualitative
analysis in the course of research on how nurses perceive, and
therefore relate to, dying patients (Glaser and Strauss 1965,
1967).  The fourth generation evaluator employs this same method,
called the constant comparative method, to construct a description
of how various groups of stakeholders view the program and the
issues facing it.
<P>
The constant comparative method consists of developing empirically
grounded concepts, and eventually theory, through the constant
coding and recoding of qualitative data as it is collected (Glaser
and Strauss 1967, Strauss 1987, Strauss and Corbin 1990, Lincoln
and Guba 1985).  In other words, on a daily basis the researcher
codes interview and observation notes; and each time an incident
is coded under a category, it is compared with previous incidents
coded in the same category.  As Glaser and Strauss (1967, 106)
explain,
<P>
  <I>&quot;This constant comparison of the incidents very soon
starts to generate the theoretical properties of the category.
 The analyst starts thinking in terms of the full range of types
or continua of the category, its dimensions, the conditions under
which it is pronounced or minimized, its major consequences, its
relation to other categories, and its other properties.&quot;</I>

<P>
The qualitative researcher thus constantly reformulates the codes.
 To aid this process, the researcher writes memos to explain the
thinking which lies behind the recoding.
<P>
But whereas the researcher uses this method to develop concepts
and eventually theory, the fourth generation evaluator seeks to
portray the views of each group of stakeholders on the program
(Lincoln and Guba 1985, 339-344; Guba and Lincoln 1989, 151-55,
178-80, 204-013).  To do this, the fourth generation evaluator
starts by collecting data from one group of stakeholders through
semi-structured interviews; then uses the constant comparative
method to develop categories of <I>claims</I> (favorable assertions
about program impact), <I>concerns</I> (unfavorable assertions
about program impact), and <I>issues </I>(actions about which
people disagree) as seen by that group (Guba and Lincoln 1989,
39-40).  Guba and Lincoln illustrate the meaning of these terms
with the following examples: a stakeholder <I>claims</I> that
a particular mode of reading instruction during one school year
results in more than a year's gain in tested reading scores; another
stakeholder is <I>concerned</I> that computer instruction reduces
students's abilities to do computations by hand; and stakeholders
disagree on the <I>issue</I> of introducing AIDS education into
primary schools.  
<P>
The evaluator discusses the emerging categories of claims, concerns,
and issues in subsequent interviews.  In this way, the evaluator
acts as a facilitator, helping the group's members to refine,
change, or modify their initial perspectives.  The evaluator challenges
and probes the stakeholders's initial views through other means
as well, for instance, providing information from the professional
literature and program documents, and describing how the evaluator
or other groups of stakeholders see the program's claims, concerns,
and issues.  Guba and Lincoln aptly characterize this whole data
collection and analysis process as a circle, because the evaluator
will likely have to go back to those first interviewed in order
to discuss with them categories which only emerged subsequently
(Ibid, 152).
<P>
In the process, some of the initial issues voiced by stakeholders
may be resolved.  Others will remain, representing the real tasks
and issues facing the program.  At this point, the evaluator prepares
an annotated list (agenda) of these, including any information
which elucidates them, and facilitates negotiation among the various
groups of stakeholders as to what actions should be taken (Guba
and Lincoln 1989, 214-23).   For instance, in a fourth generation
evaluation of a USAID program in Malawi, the articulated issues
concerned initially the priorities for allocating funds among
various components.  In the course of the evaluation, though,
this was resolved, while a new issue emerged of how to define
the roles and responsibilities of project officers in monitoring
performance.  The evaluator acted as a catalyst and recorder in
meetings on this issue by the working group responsible for project
coordination (Fehnel 1991, 17).
<P>
The rationale and potential for applying a fourth generation methodology
is most obvious when an on-going program requires a diagnostic
evaluation of its problems.  In other words, fourth generation
evaluation was really intended for situations where the stakeholders
in a program wish to decide on how to improve it.  However, elements
of the fourth generation methodology could potentially be adapted
to less obvious contexts, for instance, an impact evaluation of
an already completed program.  In this situation, the stakeholders
are those who have an interest in the evaluation, not the program.
  These stakeholders probably have contending views on issues
such as the purpose of the evaluation, the questions to be addressed,
and possibly even the methods or type of data which should be
collected.  In principle, the constant comparative method, as
modified by Guba and Lincoln, could be applicable to defining,
developing and discussing issues such as these.
<P>
In addition, the case in Section 4 raises the question of whether
CDR researchers could apply this methodology to structure and
facilitate discussions with Danida staff about research topics
and projects.
<P>
<a name=uti></a><B>3.2 Utilization-focused Evaluation</B>
<P>
Patton (1986) shares the view which donor agency staff eventually
adopted as the result of their initial experiences with evaluating
aid:  evaluations must answer the questions which users actually
have, and provide information which they genuinely want.  To achieve
this, Patton argues that evaluators have to consider how each
decision which they make in the course of the evaluation will
ultimately affect the usefulness of the information provided.
 A utilization-focused methodology accordingly consists of procedures
to help the evaluator take those decisions which best enhance
the prospects for the evaluation being utilized.  These procedures
largely boil down to how and why to involve stakeholders in this
decision-making.  
<P>
The primary role of the utilization-focused evaluator remains
information-gathering and analysis, in contrast to fourth generation
evaluation.  However, working with stakeholders to arrive at decisions
which are appropriate to their particular situation, may require
the evaluator to take on additional roles:  collaborator, trainer,
group facilitator, politician, organizational analyst, colleague,
expert, diplomat, problem solver (Ibid, 319).  
<P>
Utilization-focused evaluation grew out of a widespread concern
in the U.S. and Europe during the late 1960s and 1970s that evaluations
were not having much of an impact.  Patton quotes numerous studies
and literature reviews on this subject from the era, one of which
concludes <I>&quot;...the recent literature is unanimous in announcing
the general failure of evaluation to affect decision-making in
a significant way&quot; </I> (Wholey et al 1970, 46 as quoted
in Patton 1986, 23).  
<P>
The situation prompted Patton and a team of researchers to investigate
the reasons why some evaluations proved useful, while others did
not.  Patton's team randomly selected twenty U.S. national health
program evaluations to use as case studies (Patton et al 1977;
Patton 1986, 30-32).  The researchers then extracted from the
literature eleven factors which were supposed to affect the utilization
of a study, and asked the key informants selected for each case
study to comment on these (Patton 1986, 45).  Only one of these
factors, political considerations, emerged as consistently important
in explaining utilization.  
<P>
The other factor which emerged as clearly important was unexpected.
 After having respondents comment on each of the eleven factors,
the researchers asked the interviewees to identify the single
most important factor explaining why an evaluation did or did
not have an impact.  <I>&quot;Time after time,&quot;</I> Patton
writes, <I>&quot;the factor they identified was not on our list.
 Rather, they responded in terms of the importance of individual
people&quot;</I> (Ibid, 46).  The researchers labeled this the
&quot;personal factor,&quot; and Patton describes it as follows:
<P>
<I> The personal factor is the presence of an identifiable individual
or group of people who personally cared about the evaluation and
the information generated.  Where such a person or group was present,
evaluations were used; where the personal factor was absent, there
was a correspondingly marked absence of evaluation impact.  The
personal factor represents the leadership, interest, enthusiasm,
determination, commitment, assertiveness, and caring of specific,
individual people.  These are the people who are actively seeking
information to reduce decision uncertainties so as to increase
their ability to predict the outcomes of programmatic activity
and enhance their own discretion as decision makers.  These are
the primary users of evaluation&quot;</I> (Ibid, 45).
<P>
Given this research finding, a utilization-focused methodology
begins with the identification of the primary users and stakeholders.
 This means locating the particular individuals who have a genuine
interest in the evaluation data, and are willing to take the time
and effort to work with the evaluators.  Patton specifically cautions
against the practice of identifying &quot;audiences&quot; or organizations
as the stakeholders/primary users.  In such cases, the evaluator
winds up speculating about their information needs, and so in
the end, the evaluator decides what information is needed.  The
task, rather, is to find people who can speak for themselves about
the answers they need (Ibid, 52-53).
<P>
Patton also warns against identifying the wrong people, i.e.,
those who are passive or disinterested.  In commenting on the
findings of another research project similar to his own, he writes,
<P>
<I> &quot;Such findings are sometimes interpreted as meaning simply
that the <U>amount</U> of contact between decision makers and
evaluators should be increased.  But our data on the personal
factor suggest that increased contact with the wrong persons (i.e.,
people who are not oriented toward the use of evaluative information)
is likely to accomplish little&quot;</I>  (Ibid, 50).
<P>
Two of the traps which lead to identifying incorrectly the primary
users are to assume the latter are those (1) in positions of authority
or (2) who funded the evaluation.  In the former case, those higher
in the hierarchy may be less appropriate than a lower-level person
who is enthusiastic, interested, committed, assertive, and competent
(Ibid, 51).  In the latter case, 
<P>
<I> &quot;Often, they simply believe that evaluation is a good
thing, ought to be done, helps programs, and keeps people on their
toes.  They do not care about the content of a specific evaluation,
they only care that evaluation--any evaluation--takes place. 
They mandate the process, but not the substance&quot;</I> (Ibid,
54).
<P>
Once the primary users have been identified, the evaluator can
take the optional second step of organizing them into a working
task force.  Alternatively, they can work with the evaluator throughout
the evaluation process on some more informal basis.
<P>
The third step in the methodology involves working with the primary
users to define and assess the questions and issues to be addressed
through the evaluation.  Patton suggests that the evaluator holds
a workshop with the primary users for this purpose, with the evaluator
acting as group facilitator (Ibid, 75-77).
<P>
Some of the characteristics of appropriate questions for a utilization-focused
evaluation are obvious (Ibid, 69-73).  The users have to want
information in order to answer the question, as opposed to questions
to which they already know the answers.  The users personally
have to want the questions answered, as opposed to questions which
they believe someone else may or should want answered.  
<P>
In addition, the questions have to be empirical, that is, answers
are based on data rather than values or judgement.  As stated
above, the role of the utilization-focused evaluator is primarily
to collect and analyze empirical information, which will be used
for the purpose of making judgements and taking action.  The stakeholders
will have the primary responsibility for the latter, even if the
evaluator offers his or her own judgements and recommendations
for action.  For instance, the evaluator will establish whether
a program activity had an impact; whether the impact constitutes
an improvement will vary, depending on who is making the judgement
(Ibid, 70-71).
<P>
Also, good questions are ones which users can indicate how they
would use the answers, once available.  The users may well not
be able to point to a single decision which they would take based
on the evaluation's findings, but they 
<P>
<I> &quot;ought to be able to indicate where their knowledge uncertainties
lie, what activities, actions, and options are clouded by those
uncertainties, and how evaluative information would increase their
potential for doing a better job and making the program more effective&quot;</I>
(Ibid, 74).
<P>
As Patton argues, <I>&quot;If they cannot indicate future usefulness
at the outset, there is no reason to believe that they will be
able to do so after the evaluation&quot;</I> (Ibid, 74).   In
addition, the users have to assess whether, given the expected
use to which the information will put, the evaluation is worth
doing (Ibid, 331).
<P>
The next step in the methodology is to design the actual data
collection process.  If stakeholders are not involved at this
stage, the evaluator risks collecting data in which the users
do not believe, or which they do not accept as valid answers to
their questions.  For instance, it is no good collecting qualitative
data, if the users will only accept quantitative data.  Also,
the evaluator must once again check that the users really will
use the information once available.  Patton advises the evaluator
to hold a session to do a simulated analysis of the data, focusing
on how it would help the users take action.
<P>
<I> &quot;The evaluator prepares for this session by organizing
fabricated results, some positive and some negative, on the most
important issues.  For example, suppose the major outcome variable
for a vocational training program is the job placement rate. 
The evaluator might present data showing a placement rate of 40%
for black participants and 75% for white participants.  The stakeholders
are asked: 'What do these results mean? What actions would you
take based on these results? How would you use these data?'&quot;</I>
(Ibid, 247).
<P>
After the data have been collected, a similar step occurs in which
stakeholders participate in interpreting the findings.  The final
steps in the methodology are for the evaluator to facilitate the
intended use of the evaluation results by the users, and possibly
to disseminate the findings to a larger group of potential secondary
users (Ibid, 331-32).
<P>
Patton (Ibid, 340-44) describes one example of an actual utilization-focused
evaluation, which happens to be of a USAID agricultural extension
project.  Although the evaluation ran simultaneously with implementation,
the former did seek data on impacts.  When the funders decided
the project's future, they would want some indication of the project's
effectiveness and impact.  The evaluators were able to provide
that information when the decision-makers needed it, and that
was critical to securing continued funding (Ibid, 342-43).  In
short, in line with the premises of the utilization-focused approach,
the emphasis was placed on reducing decision-makers uncertainties
about a specific decision, rather than maximizing the quality
of the data on impact for its own sake.
<P>
<a name=cas></a><H3>4. Case: Collaboration to Develop Research on Project Impact</H3>
<P>
Textbooks on social science methods and methodology typically
begin at the point after the researcher has selected a topic or
question for study.  They provide few or no guidelines on how
the researcher should search for a research topic.  When this
very preliminary phase of research is addressed, the assumption
is that it is a largely individual process: the researcher reviews
the academic literature looking for gaps (Silverman 1985, 4-12).
 <P>
This is sound advice.  However, one can envision a supplementary
process particularly in the case of applied research, appropriate
when the researcher wishes to maximize the chances that the research
findings will be useful to a specific group of users.  The example
in this section will illustrate such a process. 
<P>
It proceeds through three stages.  First, a researcher works with
Danida staff to develop a list of research ideas in a given area,
in this case, the impact of rural drinking water projects.  Next,
that researcher develops one idea into a research proposal suitable
for the Council for Development Research (<I>R&aring;det for Ulandsforskning</I>
(RUF)) funding.  Finally, another researcher selects a different
idea from the list, and also develops it into a RUF-destined proposal.
<P>
<a name=def></a><B>4.1 Defining the Research Agenda</B>
<P>
This sub-section describes four steps in a collaborative process
aimed at developing <I>ideas</I> for research.  Under the present
system, researchers who wish to apply for a RUF grant via CDR
first submit a research idea to CDR, whose <I>Centern&aelig;vnet</I>
then decides which ones should be developed into full-fledged
research proposals.  The process by which a researcher develops
an idea is entirely left to the individual.  In the following
case, by contrast, the researcher uses an explicitly participatory
methodology to involve Danida staff in this most preliminary phase
of research.  The steps in this methodology are as follows:
<P>
<OL>
<li>Choose general area of research
<P>
<li>Define relevant Danida stakeholder groups
<P>
<li>Carry out semi-structured interviews and analysis within each
stakeholder group
<P>
<li>Present issues (ideas) paper to CDR and Danida for discussion</ol>

<P>
We will follow Kaj, a researcher who wishes to apply for a RUF
grant via CDR, as he proceeds through the four steps.
<P>
<B>1.  Kaj chooses the general area of research</B>
<P>
Kaj decides to look for research issues related to the impact
of rural drinking water projects.  Kaj alone makes this initial
decision about the general area for research, but based on transparent
and justifiable reasons which meet with the informal approval
of CDR researchers with whom Kaj discusses his choice.  
<P>
Four factors in particular lead Kaj to decide that he should look
for a topic related to the impact of rural drinking water projects.
 First, CDR is in the process of building up its research profile
on aid impact, and thus Kaj believes that research in this area
will carry with it good opportunities for collaboration and interchange
with other CDR researchers.  Second, the explicit principal objective
in Danish assistance to rural drinking water was direct poverty
alleviation, which is in line with the thrust of CDR's planned
research on aid impact.  Third, Danida has funded a large number
of now completed projects and programs in the rural drinking water
sector, hence it provides ample opportunity for finding a suitable
case to study impact.  Finally, Kaj has both research and implementation
experience in this sector, which he feels constitutes an indispensable
background for recognizing central issues for research.
<P>
<B>2.  Kaj defines the (two) groups of Danida stakeholders for
research in this area</B>
<P>
Based on his knowledge of Danida, Kaj immediately defines two
groups of potential stakeholders for his research, the TSA advisers
and the Evaluation Unit staff.  Kaj can imagine how both groups
could make use of information on water project impact in their
work.  However, since TSA advisers and Evaluation Unit staff have
very different roles and responsibilities within Danida, they
require different types of information and would put it to different
uses.  The relevant research issues will be correspondingly different
as well.
<P>
TSA advisers have the responsibility to oversee from a professional
viewpoint the design and implementation of projects and programs.
 TSA advisers, particularly those dealing with water projects,
are potentially interested in information on the impact of past
projects <I>to the extent this can provide lessons for current
and future projects</I>.  The research issues for TSA will likely
stem from the questions and uncertainties they face in managing
current assistance; the advisers are potentially interested in
information from experience to the extent it can reduce these
uncertainties.
<P>
Evaluation Unit staff have an interest and responsibility to see
that TSA advisers get such information, but the former do not
constitute stakeholders or primary users for this kind of information.
 They may help TSA get such information through summative evaluations,
for example, but the Evaluation Unit staff cannot themselves define
what the content of this information should be.  As Patton (1986,
54) explained, they may mandate the process but not the substance
of evaluation (see Section 3.2 above).  
<P>
However, the Evaluation Unit has recently become very obviously
responsible for accounting to the Danish parliament and people
on the effective use of Danish taxpayers's money by Danida.  For
instance, the parliamentary Foreign Affairs Committee in 1994
requested the Minister for Development Cooperation to submit a
report on how and how well Danish assistance is being used to
achieve the overall objective of reducing poverty (Olsen and Udsholt
1995, 42).  The Evaluation Unit is in charge of the series of
evaluations commissioned in order to provide this information
(Danida 1995c, 1995d).  Consequently, Kaj imagines the Evaluation
Unit staff being potentially interested in information on the
impact of past projects <I>to the extent it indicates the effectiveness
with which Danish assistance has been used</I>, in reaching the
poverty alleviation or other objectives.
<P>
Defining stakeholder groups makes the subsequent process of semi-structured
interviewing and analysis more (1) manageable and (2) effective.
 Organizing stakeholders into groups, based on the type of issues
they are likely to identify, makes the process more manageable
in that it breaks it into blocks or phases.  Kaj can prepare for
and immerse himself in interviews around one type or set of issues,
before moving on to tackle the next.  The process is more effective
to the extent it allows the researcher to go into more depth.
 This can include identifying more stakeholders.  For instance,
the TSA advisers might direct Kaj to someone in the &quot;S-departments&quot;
or attached to an Embassy (who Kaj contacts by mail) who has a
particularly good grasp of the issues facing the sector in a particular
country.  The Evaluation Unit might put Kaj in touch with the
consultants working on the poverty alleviation evaluation.
<P>
<B>3.  Kaj carries out semi-structured interviewing and analysis
within each stakeholder group</B>
<P>
Kaj will engage in a process is modeled closely on that of fourth
generation evaluation, in which the role of the evaluator is to
help articulate, develop, and sharpen participants's views of
the issues.  It is therefore in stark contrast to the typical
attitude or approach of an interviewer, who tries to extract the
interviewee's pre-existing views <I>without</I> allowing the interview
process to affect them.  Kaj's interviews have more the character
of one-on-one seminars.  He is not there simply to listen, but
to engage in dialogue.  To do this, he must come prepared to ask
questions, but also to provide information from the professional
literature and program documents, and to share his own and other
informants's views on the emergent issues.
<P>
This has several implications for how Kaj prepares for and conducts
the interviews.  To illustrate this, our case continues with the
story of how Kaj interviews the TSA advisers.
<P>
Before Kaj goes into the first interview, he familiarizes himself
with the on-going drinking water projects and the Danida strategies
for the program countries which will receive Danish assistance
for rural drinking water supply.  Kaj also begins reading about
the issues in rural drinking water supply as seen by other major
donors, such as the World Bank, and described in the professional
literature.  
<P>
The first interview is short and very unstructured.  After explaining
his purpose in interviewing Danida staff, Kaj asks a series of
open-ended questions about a recently completed impact evaluation
of a Danida rural water supply program in Sri Lanka (Danida 1995a,
1995b).  Did the adviser find the report's conclusions about impact
believable?  Did she need and use this information?  Has she heard
anything about the Sri Lanka project, or similar types of projects,
which led her to draw her own conclusions about impact?  What
needs does she have for more information on the impact of rural
drinking water assistance in order to do her job?  This last question
forms the transition to talking about the issues and information
needs which the adviser encounters in the specific projects she
is presently supervising.  Kaj keeps the interview short, because
he will have to go back and re-interview the first respondents
as he gets more information and ideas about how Danida staff view
the possible research issues on aid impact.
<P>
Kaj analyzes this first interview before carrying out a second.
 This involves coding the transcript in terms of possible issues
and writing memos.  This could certainly be done &quot;by hand,&quot;
because the analysis of these interviews will not be as time-consuming
or extensive as in a typical qualitative research study.  However,
Kaj suspects that the actual research will entail extensive analysis
of qualitative data, which could most effectively be handled by
computer.  Therefore, he has investigated software for qualitative
data analysis, and narrowed the options to three: <I>NUD.IST</I>,
<I>Atlas/ti,</I> and <I>Folio VIEWS</I> (Weitman and Miles 1995,
115-128, 217-229, 238-256; <A HREF="http://qsr.latrobe.edu.au" target="_top">http://qsr.latrobe.edu.au</A>).  He decides
to familiarize himself more thoroughly with the capabilities of
<I>NUD.IST</I>, which CDR recently purchased on his recommendation,
by using it to analyze the Danida interview data.
<P>
In the next interview, Kaj asks similar questions, and in addition,
summarizes the views of the first adviser in each question area.
 Kaj also describes a tentative formulation of a research issue,
developed in one of the memos he wrote while analyzing the first
interview data.  Unfortunately, due to scheduling difficulties,
he has to conduct two interviews the same day, and so cannot analyze
the one before going on to the next.  In general, though, he manages
to feed the analysis of one interview into the succeeding ones.
 In the process, his questions become more focused.  The balance
of the interview shifts toward discussing possible issues, rather
than responding to the general questions he used in the first
interviews.  Finally, he goes back to the first advisers interviewed,
to get their views on the issues as they have emerged.  At that
point, he writes up a short description of these issues, and presents
it for discussion at a TSA meeting.
<P>
<B>4.  Kaj presents a final issues paper</B>
<P>
Kaj goes through a process with the Evaluation Unit staff similar
to the one just described for TSA.  He then prepares a final issues
paper, which combines the two early ones and incorporates the
comments which he received on these from the respective stakeholder
groups.  It also includes a brief statement of which issue he
would like to develop into a RUF proposal and why.  He will discuss
this paper formally and informally with representatives from CDR,
TSA, and the Evaluation and Research Department before submitting
his project idea to <I>Forretningsudvalget</I> (FU), the first
step in applying for a RUF grant via CDR.
<P>
<a name=app></a><B>4.2 Applied Research Useful in Assistance Design and Management</B>
<P>
The topic which interests Kaj came up in the discussions with
TSA.  When the water advisers talked about current issues in their
work, it emerged that many of these related to questions about
whether and how to implement a demand-driven approach to rural
water supply, a new and untested strategy which is currently being
promoted by the World Bank in particular.  For much of the past
two decades, Danida and other donors had worked on the assumption
that governments had the responsibility to provide a minimum standard
of drinking water supplies to the rural population.  Donors had
therefore stepped in to assist governments in this role by funding
and implementing huge projects and programs to construct rural
domestic water schemes.  For the past few years, though, the World
Bank had promoted the idea that the communities should have the
primary responsibility to provide and maintain their water supplies,
by buying services from the private sector, while the government
acted primarily in a facilitating role.
<P>
The TSA advisers saw a number of positive points in this new demand-driven
approach to rural water supply.  For one, it meshed well with
the new overall Danida policy to support programs rather than
projects.  Second, it was based on an analysis of past problems
with donor assistance to rural water supply which corresponded
to Danida's experience in the sector.  The major drawbacks were
that there was little evidence to support the claims and assumptions
on which the proposed strategy for future assistance rested, and
that the strategic recommendations themselves were extremely vague.
 Consequently, the final issues paper included several research
topics related to the demand-driven approach.  
<P>
One of the topics concerned how and how well communities and other
local institutions can play the new roles expected of them.  The
demand-driven approach, in water supply as well as other sectors,
presents a series of arguments as to why communities will be effective
and fair managers.  However, the policy documents present little
empirical evidence to support these claims.  Research could establish
the conditions under which communities had successfully managed
water schemes, and how effective and fair this management had
been.  Such information would provide a more realistic basis on
which to design and manage projects and programs which ultimately
depended on community management.
<P>
In the end, Kaj selected this topic as the basis for his research
proposal for a number of reasons.  First, empirical information
could clearly contribute useful information to a discussion of
the issue.  Decisions about some of the other issues required
more judgement and interpretation of existing information, than
gathering new information.  Second, Kaj had the background, skills,
and interest to do the study.  Third, a couple of the TSA advisers
were quite enthusiastic about research into community management,
and interested in keeping in contact with Kaj as he carried it
out.  Fourth, the topic fit into one of the areas at CDR.
<P>
To develop the topic into a research proposal, Kaj needs to define
the research questions.  His preliminary reading in the academic
literature leads Kaj to focus these questions on local institutions:
 what local institutions take on management responsibilities?;
what is the division of labor among local institutions in regard
to scheme management?; and what factors explain the effectiveness
of a particular type of institution?.  In this context, &quot;institutions&quot;
includes both organizations--e.g., village water committees, district
councils, district water departments--and indigenous institutions
such as clan societies and rotating credit groups.  &quot;Local&quot;
refers to anything from a large group to the district/block/prefecture
level.  
<P>
Kaj then sketches out a methodology to answer these questions,
based on carrying out a series of case studies of rural communities
which have successfully managed either a handpumped or gravity
scheme to supply drinking water.  In each community, Kaj will
use observation and interviews to gather information on the individuals
and institutions which perform various operation and maintenance
tasks--preventive maintenance, repairs, operational tasks, revenue
payment, revenue collection, etc.--and factors which seem to explain
why they perform this task.  By comparing this information across
communities/case studies, he hopes to conceptualize better some
of the factors cited in the literature to explain performance,
develop other explanatory concepts, or both.
<P>
Up to this point, Kaj had only discussed his ideas for research
questions and a field methodology with other CDR researchers.
 With something on paper now, he goes back to the TSA advisers
who were most interested in the research.  They agree with many
of his ideas, but also argue for several major changes.  First,
the TSA adviser with an engineering background argues that the
technical quality of operation and maintenance has to be established
at the outset for each case study.  Water flowing from the taps
and pumps on a regular basis does not necessarily mean the system
has been well-maintained.  One has to establish to what extent
a scheme really is successfully managed before attempting to explain
why.
<P>
Second, the advisers do not want the case studies restricted to
communities which received schemes through donor water projects.
 The advisers's main interest lies in getting as complete a picture
of successful community management as possible.  Therefore, they
would like Kaj to look at communities which developed successful
management systems without the benefit of donor assistance.  Third,
the advisers want the research to evaluate community management
in a cross-section of schemes from each Danida project included
in the study.  In other words, in addition to learning something
about the ingredients for success, the advisers also wanted a
rapid indication of whether the particular Danida projects had
widespread or limited success in promoting successful community
management.  
<P>
The first point is the most difficult to resolve, because it points
to Kaj's lack of qualifications to carry out the research single-handed.
 Kaj and TSA finally agree that the latter would finance an engineer
to work with Kaj for one to two weeks per project in doing a rapid
appraisal of the scheme operation and maintenance on a cross-section
of projects.  (This would also address the third point.)  This
engineer will also help Kaj to recruit a local engineer to advise
Kaj on technical aspects of more detailed case studies done in
a few communities.  In regard the second point, Kaj agrees to
include one to two examples of non-donor assisted water schemes
managed by the communities, if any can be identified in the same
geographic area where the rest of the research will be carried
out.  
<P>
Kaj now has to develop the detailed methodology, including methods
choices.  However, the case story will stop short of describing
this, as sufficient discussion issues have already raised.  The
next sub-section will broaden the basis for discussing these,
through presenting a short second case study.
<P>
<a name=appl></a><B>4.3 Applied Research Useful in Political Accountability</B>
<P>
An abridged version of Kaj's final issues paper appears in <I>Den
Ny Verden</I>.  There it catches the attention of a Roskilde University
student, Andrea, who is interested in doing a Ph.D. on the unintended
consequences of donor interventions in rural areas.  Her interest
in the subject comes from a book by James Ferguson (1990), who
argues that even failed development projects serve to expand the
power of the state.  Kaj's final issues paper includes one on
the unintended benefits and costs from donor-finance rural water
supply schemes.  Although it is far from clear that the drinking
water projects will provide evidence in support of Ferguson's
thesis--nor would Andrea wish merely to parrot his analysis--she
decides to develop the issue identified by Kaj into a RUF-proposal.
<P>
This particular issue arose out of Kaj's discussion with the Evaluation
Unit staff.  The latter had initially assumed that research on
rural water supply and poverty alleviation should address the
same broad questions around which a team of consultants had organized
their multi-sectoral evaluation of the impact of Danish aid on
poverty.  These questions did indeed provide a starting point
for the first semi-structured interviews between Kaj, the Danida
staff, and the consultants, but gradually they identified issues
which were much more specific to rural water supply and its presumed
impact on poverty.  The final issues paper includes two such issues,
concerning respectively the health impact of water projects, and
the unintended benefits and costs from the donor-financed schemes.
 It is the second which interests Andrea.
<P>
Andrea contacts Kaj for a briefing on this issue.  Kaj explains
that recent evaluations of Danida water projects had made passing
references to the commercial uses to which some consumers were
putting water, especially on piped schemes.  This situation raises
a number of questions about who really benefits from this infrastructure.
 Do local elites in fact capture the lion's share of benefits
from the schemes?  Does the unintended use of water threaten the
intended benefits, for instance, because the system cannot supply
everyone with enough water for domestic purposes?  Who bears the
costs of maintaining the system?  How do the poor themselves view
the situation?  Finally, and perhaps most interesting, how do
problematic situations come about?  Do local elites so regularly
capture the benefits of the water supply that one must consider
it inevitable, or are there specific socio-economic, institutional,
design, or other factors which encourage such situations?  The
answers to such questions will indicates the effectiveness of
investment in rural water supply as a direct poverty alleviation
measure.
<P>
Andrea next discusses her possible research on this issue with
the Evaluation Unit staff.  Their main concern is that research
be based on case studies of specific Danida projects or programs.
 In other words, while the staff are interested in generalizable
conclusions about rural water supply investment as a means to
alleviate poverty, they also want a clear picture of how Danida
investments in particular have performed in this respect.  Andrea
suggests that &quot;performance&quot; is probably best gauged
in relative terms: did some Danida projects do better than others;
or did Danida projects do better than other donor and non-donor
projects?
<P>
In line with this discussion, Andrea develops a methodology based
on a studying about fifteen schemes financed through the Danida
water project in Tanzania, and about as many again which were
financed by UNICEF, SIDA, and the Tanzanian government.  This
will allow her to say something about the problems in general
with benefit distribution on rural water supplies, and how well
Danida in particular dealt with those problems.  Confining the
research to one country limits somewhat the diversity in local
conditions, and of course eliminates any comparative analysis
of how national level factors may influence the local.  On the
other hand, Andrea can study a greater number of schemes by restricting
the research to Tanzania, which among other things, allows her
to do a more thorough case study of the Danida project, and thus
better meet the Evaluation Unit's demand for information on the
impact of a Danida project.
<P>
<a name=con></a><H3>5. Conclusions</H3>
<P>
The methodology which Kaj and Andrea used rests on (at least)
two premises:  that CDR and its researchers will invest substantially
more time than at present in research topic selection; and that
CDR will modify the present procedures for approving research
proposals to be sent to RUF.
<P>
Collaboration takes time.  Collaboration between CDR and Danida
staff to identify topics for research will add considerably to
the total time required to develop a research proposal.  It is
analogous to the situation when donors added community participation
objectives and components to development projects.  The &quot;hardware&quot;
of projects, e.g., the construction of the water schemes, could
not be completed as quickly once the community had to be involved
at each phase.  Likewise, Kaj and Andrea's approach adds several
weeks, at least, of background reading, data collection, analysis
to the research development process.  
<P>
CDR's present procedures for approving proposals prior to their
submission to RUF would have to be modified in order to accommodate
this.  Collaboration along the lines described above would take
place prior to the first stage of the present CDR process, the
submission of an initial research idea.  Researchers would be
unlikely to invest the weeks of work necessary for collaboration,
if the <I>Forretningsudvalget</I> (FU) and <I>Centern&aelig;vnet</I>
(CN) provide no financial support during this period, and give
no weight to collaboration in the decision of whether to pass
the proposal onto the second stage.  Also, present procedures
do not allow for Danida staff to be on the committee which submits
the recommendation to FU and CN regarding whether or not to approve
the proposal for the second and third phases.  Without this, collaboration
is more likely to harm than help a researcher's chances in getting
a proposal passed.
<P>
These comments on the premises underlying the hypothetical case
demonstrate how it can be used to further discussion on the subject
of collaboration between Danida and CDR.  The story of Kaj and
Andrea does not present a solution or recommendation; rather it
offers a tool for discussion.  By pointing out what they do and
do not like or find feasible in the case, CDR and Danida staff
can generate ideas for a better methodology of collaboration.
<P>
