<title>Development Co-operation Review -- United Kingdom</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><img src="../images/gb.jpg"><p></a>
Development Co-operation Review Series:<br>United Kingdom<br>
<i>OECD Development Assistance Committee</i><p></h3>
<h5>(Summary of Development Co-operation Review Series, Number 1, 1994)<br>
For a copy of the full report, please contact OECD Publications, 2 rue Andr&#233; Pascal, 75775 Paris cedex 16, France
<br>
Home Page: <a href="http://www.oecd.org/dac/index.htm" target="_top">http://www.oecd.org/dac/index.htm</a></h5>
</center><p>
<hr>
<h4>This Report</h4>
The OECD Development Assistance Committee (DAC) conducts periodic reviews to improve the individual and collective development co-operation efforts of its members.
<p>
The peer review is prepared by the Secretariat and involves staff from development agencies in other DAC member countries. A draft report of the team is prepared by the Secretariat and it forms the basis for a review meeting with the member.
<p>
This publication contains the conclusions as agreed by DAC following the review meeting on 24 February 1994, as well as the report prepared by the Secretariat team.
<p>
<h4>Main Points</h4>
Despite a growing budget for aid, the British aid programme, particularly the bilateral component, is under severe pressure. The proportion of aid to gross national product has declined in recent years and budget projections till 1997 show little growth in real terms. A concern discussed in the report is the growing commitment of aid resources to multilateral organisations. Unless total aid resources are increased, the distinctive bilateral programme would be under severe pressure, with consequent impacts on the non-govermental and other organisations that are rely on these funds to a large extent.
<p>
The report reviews the volume and distribution of aid, geograpically and thematically. Special attention is given to the linkages between aid policy and other economic and political instruments for cooperation with developing countries. The organisation and administration of the aid system is described and the evaluation system in reviewed. A description of UK aid to Uganda is included as a way to provide insights into the operation and management of the aid programme.
<p>
<h4>Further Information</h4>
To get a copy of the report, please contact OECD Publications, 2 rue Andr&#233; Pascal, 75775 Paris cedex 16, France<p>
