<html>
<header>
<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Austria</title>
</header>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><hr><p><IMG align=middle SRC  = "../images/at.jpg"><h3>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Austria</h3></center>
<br> 
<hr><h3>Sources</h3>
<h5><ul><li>Kooij, A. and R. Mevis.
1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen
European Countries</i>. The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The
report is available from: NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The
Hague, the Netherlands.
</h5>
<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"><IMG align=top SRC =
"../images/acro.jpg"></a>
</ul><p>

<hr>
<p>
In 1974 an Advisory Council on Development Cooperation (Beirat) was established in order to guarantee a
coordinated development policy and implementation. The Council could advise the Federal Chancellor on
these matters. The ca. 50 members of the Council are appointed by the Federal Chancellor and represent all
major sections in society, including Members of Parliament of the Standing Committee for Foreign Affairs,
representatives of NGOs, industry, and trade unions. It is chaired by the State Secretary for Integration and
Development Cooperation.
<p>
The Council meets three or four times a year. Meetings are held at the request of the State Secretary. The
Council does not write reports or recommendations. It is a panel for discussion with the State Secretary.
Discussions are considered as an input for policy formulation which is executed by the State Secretary and
the officials involved. The Council's main function is preserving the support for development cooperation in
Austrian society. It discusses amongst others: DAC reports, the negotiations with EU and the government's
Three-Year Programme for Development Cooperation. The operational criteria for Austrian development
cooperation were elaborated in 1979 and 1980 by a working group of the Council, based on the 1974 Law.
The Council appears to play a minor role since. The Council has no Secretariat. Members can be contacted
through the Federal Chancellery. The Council does not publish any documents of its discussions and its
present agenda is not known.
<p>
In order to improve its functioning working groups were established in 1992 on environmental questions and
on human rights. In the DAC Aid Review of 1992/93 the Austrian government is invited to reconsider the
role of the Advisory Council with regard to obtaining the necessary support of the population for an
enlarged and improved aid programme. In view of greater efficiency, a reduction of the number of Council
Members should be considered. 
<p>
Parliament has a Standing Sub-Committee on Development Policy (under the responsibility of the Standing
Committee for Foreign Affairs) which sets its own agenda. Parliament apparently does not show great
interest in questions of aid. Debates on government reports submitted to Parliament have been held
belatedly. In 1988 Parliament conducted an enquiry into the development assistance, but there has been no
active follow up reported.

<p>

<hr>
