<html>
<header>
<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Europe</title>
</header>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><IMG align=middle SRC  = "../images/de.jpg"><h3>Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy in Germany
</h3></center>
This information is drawn from the report of a survey (1993-1994) carried out by ECDPM on behalf of the
National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) of the Netherlands.
<br> 
<h5><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/nar.jpg" border=1> Source: Kooij, A. and R. Mevis.
1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen
European Countries</i>. The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The
report is available from: NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The
Hague, the Netherlands.
</h5>
<hr>
<h3>Contents:</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org">Organisation of German Development Cooperation</a>
<li><a href="#ins">Institutional Framework</a>
<li><a href="#adv">Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</a>
<li><a href="#ngo">Non-State Sources of Advice</a>
<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"><IMG align=top SRC =
"../images/acro.jpg"></a>
</ul><p>

<hr><a name="org"><h3>Organisation of German Development Cooperation</h3>

German development cooperation started in the 1950s. Initially it was implemented mainly through private
and independent organisations; some of which originally were created for reconstruction purposes in
Germany after the Second World War (for instance the Credit Institute for Reconstruction, KfW in 1948).
Development cooperation is strongly supported by the Government and the public for political and
humanitarian reasons, and been widely debated and discussed. Presently, the rather well informed public
seems to shift its attention towards more structural global problems and the need for changes in the North,
while domestic problems seem to be a greater cause for concern.
<p>
German net official development assistance in 1992 stood at US $ 7 572 million, or 0.39 per cent of GNP.
After a substantial increase in the late 1980s the volume might drop under the DAC average of 0.33 per
cent in the coming years. A fairly constant 30 per cent of ODA is being disbursed through multilateral
channels: in 1992 15 per cent, plus 16 per cent through the EU.
<p>
<hr><a name="ins"><h3>Institutional Framework</h3></a>
<p>
Official development cooperation is not based on an organic law. Development aid is regulated through
various specific laws. The competency for development cooperation of the Federal Government and the
Federal States ('L&#228;nder') is laid down in the chancellor's decisions of 1962 and 1988. The Federal
Government is responsible for the overall policy, planning and coordination, the States have declared
themselves responsible for assisting in the implementation of projects, training in Germany, and providing
experts and research facilities.
<p>
Technical and financial development cooperation is the responsibility of the Minister for Economic
Cooperation, who is a full member of Cabinet, and who heads the Ministry for Economic Cooperation and
Development (BMZ, created in 1961). There is also a State Secretary for Development Cooperation.
General political relations with developing countries are the competence of the Ministry for Foreign Affairs,
external economic relations (including trade) of the Minister for Economics and monetary policy is the
competence of the Minister for Finance. Budgets for development cooperation need the approval of the
Ministers for Foreign Affairs and Finance before the are sent to Parliament. After the Unification and the
abolishment of the Ministry for Economic Cooperation of the former GDR Affairs (MWZ, founded in
1990), a temporary service was set up in Berlin, which is to be integrated into the BMZ. 
<p>
In 1990 about a quarter of total ODA was provided by other departments: the Ministry for Foreign Affairs
(mainly for cultural and humanitarian assistance), and the Federal L„nder (mainly for scholarships (imputed
students costs) and technical assistance), other federal departments (mainly the Ministries for Finance, for
Agriculture and for Economics) and the KfW, a credit institute for capital assistance. Formulation of aid
policies is BMZ's responsibility. However, all major projects and programmes are submitted by BMZ to all
other ministries that might be interested, in particular the Ministry for Foreign Affairs, the Finance
Ministry, and the Ministry for Economics. 
<p>
Implementation of aid is mainly subcontracted to two autonomous institutions: the German Agency for
Technical Cooperation (GTZ), and the KfW. Although most projects are implemented by these two
institutions, outside experts and institutes are often involved. For many sectors there are specialised
institutes - a.o. voluntary sending organisations and NGOs - that are involved in implementation,
independently and/or in cooperation with the Government, for instance the DEG (German Corporation for
Investment and Development), a promotion institute for cooperation between private enterprises. Various
channels of assistance and instruments are integrated in one country policy, project or programme.
<p>
Within the BMZ the Division for Regional Development Policy is amongst others responsible for country
related planning and coordination, while the Division for Targets and Planning for Development Policy
amongst others elaborates the principles and objectives of sectoral and inter-sectoral policy. 
<p>
In addition to BMZ eleven other departments, with which BMZ has long standing arrangements, manage
certain parts of ODA. In order to improve the, sometimes difficult, relationship between the BMZ and GTZ,
new organisational management structures for both institutions were implemented in 1988. However, the
final authority of the Minister for Economic Cooperation and Development still seems to be limited.
Interministerial communication appears to be ad hoc, and often limited to implementation level.
<p>
Basic policy papers were formulated successively in 1971, 1980 and 1991, when new criteria and indicators
were written. In addition, BMZ elaborates country concepts and -reports, (cross-) sector policy papers and
guidelines for the selection and assessment of projects, which are regularly up-dated. They are for internal
use only. Evaluations are frequently conducted and analyzed by a special unit in BMZ. They are made
available to the departments concerned and to the implementing agencies. Summaries of evaluations are
published. In 1991 a KfW evaluation report on a large number of projects was also published.
<p>
<hr><a name="adv"><h3>Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</h3></a>
<p>
The BMZ has a Scientific Advisory Council to the Minister for Economic Cooperation and Development
(Beirat). The Council was installed in 1963. It is the task of the Council to advise and consult the Minister
on all issues concerning economic cooperation. The Council is an independent body that expresses its views
either on request of the Minister or at its own initiative in so-called 'statement-papers' or ad-hoc
consultations.
<p>
The nomination of new members is the exclusively the responsibility of the current members. Nominated
members are subsequently appointed by the Minister for a period of six years, that can be extended with one
more term. The members represent various academic fields and practical experiences in development
cooperation. The council presently has 25 members. One of the staff members of the policy planning
division at BMZ acts as the contact person for the Council. In addition, the chairman of the Council may
employ an assistant and a part-time secretary.
<p>
The Council meets three times a year. Discussion papers for the plenary sessions are prepared by small
working groups. During the plenary meetings the papers are discussed intensively. Revised papers are
presented to the Minister for Economic Cooperation and Development as an input into the discussion on
specific topics within the Ministry. Usually the Minister and/or his representatives attend the discussions of
the Council. The distinct scientific background of the members serves to ensure a sufficient input from
relevant sciences and experiences.
<p>
Apart from plenary meetings, the Council occasionally organises symposiums, for which a wider spectre of
participants is invited. Experts from NGOs, governmental agencies or researchers from disciplines not
represented in the Council, give presentations on topics on which the Council envisages to prepare a paper.
The Council does not have a budget. For the financing of activities, e.g. to have research done on its
behalf, it has to submit a request to the Ministry.
<p>
The Council elaborates contributions to the formulation of development strategies and objectives. It does not
deal with problems of management or administration. Recently statements were presented on the EU Sugar
Protocol, the role of NGOs, Agriculture, and on Migration (published). The Council will continue its series
of statements on development cooperation in the 1990s. At the time of compiling this survey decisions
proposals for subjects and forthcoming studies were being discussed. A selected number of statements is
published by the Ministry for Economic Cooperation and Development in the series 'BMZ Aktuell'. These
are in German. 
<p>
Development cooperation is discussed actively in Parliament and in the Standing Committee on Development
Cooperation as well as in the Budget Committee. 
<p>
<a name="ngo"><HR><h3>Non-State Sources of Advice</h3></a>
<p>
Project-cooperation with NGOs traditionally has been considerable in Germany. Of the approximately 2000
national and local NGOs about 150 receive financial government support, amounting to a constant 9 per cent
of total German ODA per year. Roughly four broad categories of NGOs can be distinguished: the numerous
Church-related NGOs that have their own, very substantial, fundraising and co-financing agreements with
BMZ for project-implementation; political foundations: NGOs for political education that are affiliated with
the five political parties, and are 100 per cent financed by the Government; 'other NGOs', not-related to
churches or political parties, organised in the 'Bensheimer Kreis' and local NGOs that are active in
advocacy and solidarity activities within Germany. 
<p>
NGOs are organised in several large umbrella organisations. They have a high profile and considerable
influence on the policy debate through their formal and informal contacts with the Government, politicians
and the press. NGOs share a common concern on many issues with BMZ. However, they lobby for more
policy coherence and a stronger government commitment to poverty alleviation. Although policy dialogues
between BMZ and the NGO community have been intensified, there is no formal consultation mechanism.
NGOs advise the Government on the elaboration of new sectoral and country concepts, and on the
development of effective project approaches. 
BMZ carries out frequent and substantial research in cooperation with research institutes. The German
Institute for Development Policy (DIE), funded by BMZ and the City of Berlin, provides expertise on
development policy and trains German postgraduates in the field of development economics. German
(Technical) Universities provide expertise on a wide range of development subjects. According to the 1991
OECD/EADI survey there are 60 Development Research and Training Institutes in (West-) Germany. It is
not know what has been left of the development expertise that existed in the former German Democratic
Republic. 
<p>
Business interests, a.o. organised in a Working Group on Developing Countries chaired by the Federation of
German Industry, consult periodically with the BMZ.
<p>
<hr>
<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="../images/logo.gif"></a>
