<html><head><title>IIED European Programme - EC Aid and Sustainable Development</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#009999" alink="#999999" vlink="#99CCCC"><a href="index.html"><img border=0 align=right width=183 height=163 src="pix/sublogo.gif"></a><small>The material that follows has been provided by <b><a href="../index.html">International Institute for Environment and Development (IIED)</a></b></small><hr><h3>Sustainable Agriculture and Rural Development: Challenges for 
EU Aid
<p>EC Aid and Sustainable Development Briefing Paper, No. 8, 1996</h3>

<I>At the 1992 Earth Summit, the governments of the world adopted the Agenda 21 action plan which contained a set of priority actions for achieving ‘sustainable agriculture and rural development’ in both the developed and developing countries. According to Agenda 21, the overriding objective is to “increase production in a sustainable way and enhance food security”. Development agencies were assigned an important role at Rio to support national and regional efforts in the South, and best practice is beginning to emerge. This briefing outlines the challenge of sustainable agriculture, identifies the core components of successful policies and suggests some ways forward for EU development cooperation</I>. 
<p>
<H3>The Global Food Challenge</H3>

If current trends in domestic production and consumption do not change, global food production will have to double in the next three decades in order to cover the “hidden hunger” of low-income people in developing countries. This increased demand for food can be met by domestic production, imports (including food aid), or both. Food aid (currently 15 MMT of foodstuffs annually) is unlikely to augment domestic supplies appreciably, except to relieve human suffering during natural or human disasters. Imports of foods, mostly grains, have risen rapidly over the past decade and currently account for nine percent of total grain consumption in developing countries. Any rapid and continuing increase of food imports would divert scarce foreign exchange needed to meet other national priorities. Thus, most developing countries will have to continue to provide the bulk of their national food supplies themselves.
<p>
But this expansion of food production must come at a time when natural resources such as land and water are being degraded and converted to non-agricultural purposes, the earth’s pollution-absorptive capacity is being reduced and wastes are accumulating, when non-renewable resources (minerals and fossil fuels) are being consumed at unprecedented rates, and biodiversity and fragile ecosystems are being destroyed by inappropriate use. For these reasons, the solution to the problem lies in producing more food at lower cost on limited amounts of land, and increasing the income and livelihood options of rural producers. Thus, the five critical global agricultural challenges facing the European Union’s development cooperation efforts are to support developing countries to: 
<ul>
i.	Meet the basic nutritional requirements of 700-800 million persons who go hungry today;
<p>
ii.	Provide food at affordable prices for an additional 100 million people every year (the largest annual population increase in recorded history);
<p>
iii.	Increase food production through greater intensification, diversification and productivity per unit of land (as expansion is no longer feasible in most of the world);
<p>
iv.	Create pricing, marketing and distribution mechanisms and policies that ensure that poor people gain; and
<p>
v.	Do all of this in ways that conserve natural resources and biological diversity, and strengthens local livelihoods.
</ul><p>
Can these challenges be met? In theory, yes. There are no major biophysical and technological constraints to achieving the necessary yield gains. In practice, however, there are severe economic, environmental, political and social obstacles.

<H3>Making the Transition</H3>

To prevent food insecurity and reduce poverty in the coming decades, technical solutions alone will not be sufficient. There is now agreement that a new agricultural revolution is required which increases the choices, assets, and power of the rural poor of developing countries. This revolution will be based on an array of strategies which, taken together, are known as Sustainable Agriculture and Rural Development or SARD. The rudiments of SARD were described in Agenda 21 and are already being practised and refined by farmers, researchers and development practitioners in many quarters. Their aim is not only to improve agricultural productivity, but to do so in a way that regenerates rural communities and strengthens local livelihoods.  Essentially, this means making better use of locally available resources, through:
<ul>
<li>A more thorough incorporation of natural processes such as nutrient cycles, nitrogen fixation, and pest-predator relationships into the agricultural production process.
<p>
<li>A reduction in the use of off-farm or external inputs with the greatest potential to harm the environment or the health of farmers and consumers, and a more targeted and efficient use of remaining inputs.
<p>
<li>A greater productive use of the biological and genetic potential of plant and animal species.
<p>
<li>An improvement in the match between cropping patterns and the productive potential and physical limitations of agricultural lands to ensure long-term sustainability of current production levels.
<p>
<li>Profitable and efficient production with emphasis on integrated farm management and conservation of soil, water, energy and biological resources. 
<p>
<li>The full participation of farmers and rural people in all processes of problem analysis, technology development, adaptation and extension.
<p>
<li>Building on local knowledge and capacity to experiment.
<p>
<li>More equitable access to productive resources and opportunities.
<p>
<li>An increase in self-reliance amongst farmers and rural people.
<p>
<li>An emphasis on building strong social organisations in rural areas.
</ul><p>
Sustainable agriculture does not mean a return to some form of low technology, ‘backward’ or traditional agricultural practices. Rather, it emphasises the importance of innovation. Also low-input agriculture does not mean low-output agriculture. While the basic ingredients for sustainable agriculture are common, specific requirements differ widely according to region and circumstance, particularly between the Green Revolution (GR) lands and the complex, diverse, risk-prone (CDR) areas.
<p>
Between 2.3-2.6 billion people are supported by agricultural systems characterised by modern technologies of the Green Revolution. Located on the broad irrigated plains and deltas of South, Southeast, and East Asia, parts of North Africa and Latin America, and in smaller patches in other regions, these systems depend on external resources for production, including synthetic nitrogen fertiliser or phosphates, chemical pesticides, and irrigation water from distant sources. Typically, they support monocrop or monoanimal, market-oriented enterprises, including lowland irrigated rice, wheat and cotton; plantations of bananas, pineapples, oil palm and sugar cane; intensive horticulture on urban perimeters; and intensive livestock rearing and ranching. The GR lands cover some 215 million ha and produce approximately 60 percent of the total quantity of grain grown in developing countries.  
<P>
However, the majority of low-income rural dwellers, some 1.9-2.2 billion people, reside in areas that are resource poor, highly heterogeneous and risk prone, particularly Sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia. Located in the arid and semi-arid lands, wetlands, uplands, mountains and hillslopes of developing countries, these peoples must rely on internal resources such as rainfall, biologically fixed nitrogen, nutrients from lower soil strata and biological pest control based on natural enemies.  Farming systems in these environments are complex and diverse, and must adapt to periodic water stress, high temperatures and other extreme conditions. Rural livelihood strategies in these CDR areas often depend on wild resources and off-farm employment, as well as agricultural products, since yields are generally low and variable. They are remote from services and roads, and they commonly produce one-fifth to one-tenth as much food per hectare as farms in the GR areas. 
<P>
The basic challenge for SARD in each of these environments is quite different. In the GR lands, it is to maintain yields at current levels while reducing environmental damage and other negative externalities. In the CDR areas, it is to increase yields per unit of production without damaging natural resources or degrading the environment.
<p>
<center>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<tr><td><center><h4>Sustainable Agriculture and Rural Development: Experiences from Africa</h4></center>
<ul>
<li>Generating Surplus Production from Low Potential Ethiopia: The Cheha Integrated Rural Development Project in southwest Ethiopia has achieved a 70% improvement of overall nutrition levels within the project area, along with a 60% improvement of crop yields since 1984, by employing a SARD approach.    An area once reliant on emergency food aid is able 	to feed itself and produce surplus crops for sale at local markets.<li>Participation & Farmer Exchange in Tanzania: The GTZ-funded Soil Erosion Control and Agroforestry Project (SECAP) has promoted sustainable agriculture practices, including agroforestry, manuring, zero grazing, composting, use of legumes, increased crop diversity. Participatory approaches are central, with farmer exchanges and discussions proving an important tool, particularly to motivate change and see how different practices work on real farms.<li>Reforming Extension Services in Kenya: The Soil and Water Conservation Branch of the Ministry of Agriculture, with support from Sida, has pioneered the development of participatory processes for extension staff. With the mobilisation of communities, support to local groups and collaboration with other departments, some 100,000 farms are applying soil and water conservation measures across the country. In many of these areas, food production has been increased and resource degradation reduced.<li>Farmer-Driven Research in Burkina Faso: In the drought-prone region of Yatenga, the Oxfam-assisted Project Agro-Forestier (PAF) has promoted a technology development process that builds on indigenous and external technical knowledge in soil and water conservation and land management for over 17 years.  By supporting a farmer-driven research agenda and SARD approaches to resource management, PAF has helped farmers develop 	low-cost and low-risk technologies that increase 	food production, improve soils and require few 	external inputs.</ul>	
</td></tr></table>
</center>
<p>
Empirical evidence indicates that the transition to SARD systems can be achieved in both of these zones, bringing environmental and economic benefits to individual farmers, communities and national governments. In the GR lands, farmers adopting regenerative technologies and integrated farming practices have maintained yields and profitability, while substantially reducing environmental and social costs. In the CDR environments, farmers using SARD approaches have doubled and sometimes trebled yields, often with little or no use of external inputs. This has been accompanied by various indirect social and economic benefits:  
<ul>
<li>There is less need for expansion into non-agricultural areas, thus ensuring that valuable wild resources and environmentally sensitive habitats are not lost;  
<p>
<li>There is reduced contamination and pollution of the environment, thus reducing the costs incurred by farming households, consumers and national economies as a whole.  
<p>
<li>In some places there has been a regeneration of local economies and a strengthened sense of community, which has led to the reversal of rural-urban migration patterns as the demand for agricultural labour grows and off-farm employment opportunities increase.  
</ul><p>
<H3>Core Elements of SARD</H3>

While there is no blueprint for implementing SARD, successful initiatives appear to share five core elements.
<P>
1.	<I>Resource-conserving technologies and integrated farm management practices</I>.  The hallmark of SARD is not the conventional practices it rejects, but the innovative practices it includes, such as nutrient recycling, integrated pest management, soil and water conservation, and multiple cropping.  In contrast to conventional agriculture, SARD systems more deliberately integrate and take advantage of naturally occurring beneficial interactions. These systems emphasise management over technology, and biological relationships and natural processes over chemically intensive methods. The objective is to enhance and manage complexity, rather than reduce and simplify the biophysical interactions on which agricultural production depends, thus reducing the harmful off-farm effects of production practices.  
<P>
2.	<I>Diversified livelihood strategies</I>.  Greater control leads not only to more diverse, stable and resilient livelihood strategies, but also to the generation of more and better off-farm as well as on-farm employment and income opportunities. Thus, both the wider rural economy and individual farming households benefit.
<P>
3.	<I>Collective action of local organisations and intermediaries</I>. Many innovative SARD efforts have been initiated through the collective actions of community-based organisations and non-governmental organisations which have mobilised local resources and instituted a dynamic process of social change. These organisations have designed their own projects and negotiated support directly from the state and donors. They have also attracted interest for their role as political agents who can also help make the state more accountable, especially when groups of these organisations form higher-level coalitions or federations. 
<P>
4.	<I>An enabling policy environment</I>.  Where SARD strategies have had the greatest impact is in those countries with policies that have created the conditions for the transition to more sustainable forms of agriculture and resource management; liberalised markets for agricultural inputs and outputs with major private sector involvement; efficient financial institutions and alternative rural credit and banking systems; adequate rural infrastructure; and effective institutions to develop and disseminate appropriate agricultural technologies and information, and foster farmer-led research and development.  
<P>
5.	<I>Support from external actors</I>.  The transition from unsustainable to more sustainable systems has been promoted and supported by a wide array of external actors, including government agencies, research organisations, and bilateral and multilateral technical and donor agencies, who have treated  local farmers as partners in the development process, rather than as clients, beneficiaries or ‘target groups’. 

<H3>SARD & Development Cooperation</H3>

At a time when the need for sensitive and innovative support for agriculture is becoming pressing, the agricultural sector in development assistance has come under suspicion of poor performance. At the World Bank, a review of over 1000 projects found that agricultural and rural projects performed worse in terms of rates of return than other sectors (particularly urban, transport and infrastructure). IIED’s analysis of 95 agricultural projects logged on the OECD-DAC database shows a disturbing rate of failure, with at least 27% of projects having non-sustainable structures, practices or institutions, and 10% causing significant negative environmental impact. And although the EC has been committed to the principles of sustainable agriculture since the signature of the Fourth Lomé Convention, a 1994 sectoral evaluation of 160 EC-financed rural development projects concluded with a “pessimistic prognosis” regarding environmental performance. 
<P>
What can the EU do to learn from the mistakes of the past and help support the transition toward sustainable agriculture? A starting point is to focus on the livelihood requirements of low-income rural households and then identify appropriate research and development priorities which meet their needs. Particular activities for donor assistance include: 
<ul>
<li><I>Support national policies/strategies for SARD</I>: National agriculture and resource management policies need to be coordinated more effectively, particularly to overcome problems of compartmentalisation of tasks between different ministries. Moreover, these policies must take a broader food systems perspective, rather than a narrow farming systems or food production approach.  This means understanding agriculture’s role in the wider regional economy and creating conditions that support off-farm as well as on-farm employment and income generating activities, the retention of surplus capital and the development of new rural social enterprises.
<p>
<li><I>Promote farmer-centred research and extension</I>: Many research and extension services in developing countries, particularly in Sub-Saharan Africa are under financial pressure. Most are also oriented towards high-input agriculture, with ingrained structures that bias services against sustainable agriculture and participatory development. Donors should now prioritise the SARD agenda, and wherever possible, involve farmers in research design and implementation, as it is they who know local conditions best. Farmer-to-farmer exchanges can also prove effective.
<p>
<li><I>Improve rural infrastructure</I>: Poor marketing, storage, processing and transport infrastructure are often key constraints to the production of agricultural surplus. Investment in physical and social infrastructure is vital but not enough. To be useful, these facilities have to be operated and maintained, which requires a new focus on establishing local revenue raising and monitoring mechanisms to take over once the donors have gone. Sound infrastructure will enable the establishment of better vertical linkages between agricultural production and agroprocessing and marketing activities in the wider economy, thus ensuring that surplus is retained in the countryside and stimulating new social enterprises.
<p>
<li><I>Strengthen local resource management</I>: Diversity is often a key to food security in resource poor lands, but this diversity is under increasing threat. Support should be provided for farmer associations to carry out in situ genetic conservation and breeding (eg through networks, local seed banks and farmer seed exchanges). Donors should also strengthen local  groups which manage wild resource and common property resource areas.  
<p>
<li><I>Provide entitlements for food security</I>: Several recent sustainable agriculture strategies have achieved success by placing as much emphasis on income-generating activities, establishing rural credit and banking schemes and developing rural social enterprises, as on agricultural production and resource management. Support for rural women as producers and facilitators is critical, involving projects that increase their access to productive resources and raise their health and educational status. 
<p>
<li><I>Establish fair and secure tenure</I>: Security of tenure has emerged as a significant factor in determining investments in land improvement. Donors should assist partner countries to design and implement policies which improve security of access to land and other productive resources for peasant producers, particularly women and pastoralists. 
<p>
<li><I>Reinforce farmers’ organisations and users’ groups</I>: The success of sustainable agriculture depends not just on the motivation, skills and knowledge of individual farmers, but on the collective action of membership organisations for farmers and resource users. A growing number are designing, implementing and managing their own projects.</ul>
<p>
<I>This briefing was prepared by John Thompson, Research Associate in the Sustainable Agriculture Programme of IIED. He is a resource geographer with extensive research experience in natural resources management and sustainable livelihoods issues. The Sustainable Agriculture Programme of IIED supports rural development based on sustainable agricultural and land management practices, strong rural social organisations, and dynamic, equitable rural economies.</I>
<p><hr><small>©Copyright:IIED 1996</small><p><TABLE BORDER=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="index.html"><img src="pix/home.gif" width=100 height=43 alt="Home Page"></a></TD></TR></TABLE></body></html>
