<html>
<header>
<title>Development Co-operation Review of the Netherlands</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><img src="../images/nl.jpg"><p></a>
Development Co-operation Review of the Netherlands<br>Summary and Conclusions<p>
<i>OECD Development Assistance Committee</i><p></h3>
<h5>1994<br>
For a copy of the full report, please contact OECD Publications, 2 rue Andr&#233; Pascal, 75775 Paris cedex 16, France
<br>
Home Page: <a href="http://www.oecd.org/dac/index.htm" target="_top">http://www.oecd.org/dac/index.htm</a></h5>
</center><p>
<hr>
<h4>This Report</h4>
The OECD Development Assistance Committee (DAC) conducts periodic reviews to improve the individual and collective development co-operation efforts of its members.
<p>
The peer review is prepared by the Secretariat and involves staff from development agencies in other DAC member countries. A draft report of the team is prepared by the Secretariat and it forms the basis for a review meeting with the member.
<p>
This publication contains the conclusions as agreed by DAC following the review meeting on 15 June 1994, as well as the report prepared by the Secretariat team.
<p>
<h4>Main Points</h4>
The aid volume of the Netherlands has for a long time surpassed the United Nations target of 0.7% of gross national product (GNP) and the Dutch aid programme has set quality standards in several respects. In recent years however, volume has stagnated and there has been no growth in real terms since the mid-1980's. Volume fell 5% in real terms in 1993 and the ODA/GNP ratio has declined from 0.99% in 1987/87 to an estimated 0.81% in 1993.
<p>
 New orientations for Dutch development cooperation policy were outlined in a government white paper of 1993: "A World in Dispute." In this, maintenance and restoration of peace is advocated as an additional objective for traditional aid, particularly as a way to deal with the many "man-made" crises that now beset the world. While these orientations still need detailed work and discussion to become operational, they illustrate how one donor is re-defining its role and programme in relation to the new aid context.
<p>
In this regard, this review gives special consideration to the coherence betweeen emergency assistance and long-term development cooperation, integration of development programmes with the efforts of other government departments, the capacity of the Dutch aid administration to manage the widened programme, aid relationships with recipient countries, and improvements in the aid evaluation system.
<p>

<HR>
<H6><i>Updated on July 19,
1995</i><p>
