<html>
<header>
<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Europe</title>
</header>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><IMG align=middle SRC  = "../images/ie.jpg"><h3>Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy in Ireland
</h3></center>
This information is drawn from the report of a survey (1993-1994) carried out by ECDPM on behalf of the National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) of the Netherlands.
<br> 
<h5><IMG align=left SRC  = "../images/nar.jpg" border=1> Source: Kooij, A. and R. Mevis. 1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen European Countries</i>. The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The report is available from: NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The Hague, the Netherlands.
</h5>
<hr>
<h3>Contents:</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org">Organisation of Irish Development Cooperation</a>
<li><a href="#ins">Institutional Framework</a>
<li><a href="#adv">Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</a>
<li><a href="#ngo">Non-State Sources of Advice</a>
<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on  <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"><IMG align=top SRC = "../images/acro.jpg"></a>
</ul><p>

<hr><a name="org"><h3>Organisation of Irish Development Cooperation</h3></a>

Ireland became independent in 1922 and joined the United Nations in 1955. Official
development cooperation started in 1973 and was built upon previous efforts of voluntary
and non-governmental organisations. Development cooperation is based upon the direct
contacts of Irish people living in Third World countries during British colonial rule, Irish
emigrants to a number of these countries, a strong and substantial Irish Roman Catholic
missionary tradition and (respect for) its anti-colonial stand during British rule. The high level
of resources raised by Irish NGOs is an indication of the significant public support for
development cooperation efforts of these organisations. In fact, NGO aid-activities still seem
more popular, and known, than the substantial government programme. 
<p>
Net official development assistance in 1992 stood at US $ 69 million, which was 0.16 per cent
of GNP, after a sharp decrease in 1987. The amount will increase by 0.05 per cent of GNP
each year until 1997. In 1992 42 per cent of total ODA was disbursed through the EU, and 17
per cent of ODA went to other multilateral channels. The Government decided to raise the
bilateral aid budget at a faster rate than multilateral aid in the coming years, so as to achieve
a situation where two thirds of its aid is bilateral.

<a name="ins"><hr><h3>Institutional Framework</h3></a>

Irish aid is administered by the Department of Foreign Affairs, under the political
responsibility of a Minister of State responsible for European Affairs and ODA. He reports
to the Minister of Foreign Affairs. Contributions for the World Bank group are handled by the
Department of Finance, and food aid by the Department of Agriculture. Irish aid being for a
large part technical assistance, is mainly implemented by NGOs.
<p>
The Development Cooperation Division (DCD) of the Department of Foreign Affairs
coordinates Ireland's bilateral and multilateral development assistance programmes. It is
responsible for the administration of the bilateral programme, emergency aid (mostly through
NGOs), participation in EU development programmes, and contributions to UN relief and
development agencies.
<p>
Development Cooperation Offices coordinate Irish aid in priority countries. The Agency for
Personal Service Overseas (APSO), a parastatal organisation, carries out the recruitment,
training, funding and monitoring of Irish personnel for developing countries.
<p>
An Inter-departmental Committee on Development Cooperation, in which the principal
economic departments are represented, oversees the ODA programme. A Subcommittee, the
Projects Appraisal and Evaluation Group (PAEG), chaired by the DCD assesses all projects
separately. The Subcommittee includes the desk officers of the DCD, the Evaluation and
Planning Unit of the DCD, and representatives of the Ministries of Finance, Agriculture, and
Industry and Commerce, 
<p>
Planning and evaluation at the Development Cooperation Division are carried out by an
internal Planning and Evaluation Unit with the assistance of outside consultants.


<a name="adv"><hr><h3>Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</h3></a>

In 1979 an Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (ACDC) was established for a
three year term. There have been four Councils since. The last one was abolished in
December 1991. The Councils have taken a very independent position and were at times
quite critical of the aid programme and of the work of the Department. Amongst others the
ACDC criticised the arrangements of the PAEG as being unwieldy and incomplete and the
absence of any substantial policy dialogue with partner developing countries.  The ACDC
used to include representatives of a wide section of Irish society, forming a broad
constituency but operating as individuals: trade unions, farmer's organisations, academics,
organisations of churches and a delegate from Northern Ireland. 
<p>
In January 1994 a new Irish Aid Advisory Committee (IAAC) was installed. The Committee has
fourteen members, who are appointed by the Minister of Foreign Affairs. The term of office
is two years. Membership is a honourary function. The function of the Committee is to offer
expert advice to the Minister on all matters relating to development cooperation and on
policy and management aspects of the aid programme. The IAAC is an independent body that
has the right of initiative. After consultation with the Minister of Foreign Affairs the
Committee may have research conducted on its behalf and arrange for publication. The
Committee receives an annual budget paid from bilateral ODA funds.
<p>
The Committee meets every five or six weeks while its terms of reference mention a
minimum of four meetings a year. A representative of the Department may attend meetings.
The secretariat consists of one person and is located at the Department. The Executive
Secretary works on a contract basis for the Committee and is not a civil servant. The present
agenda is not known yet since the IAAC has just started its work. 
<p>
In 1993 a new Parliamentary Sub-committee was established to deal specifically with
development cooperation. The Sub-committee can hear representatives of NGOs and
officials of the Government.

<a name="ngo"><hr><h3>Non-State Sources of Advice</h3><p></a>

Contributions by Irish NGOs are proportionally the largest among DAC member countries.
The Government manages a co-financing program through which it funds part of the costs
of NGO-initiated projects of its "basic needs priority policy". These projects include health-care, education, water supply, sanitation, employment creation, agriculture, and rural
development. The greater part of the humanitarian assistance budget is channelled through
Irish NGOs. The NGOs identify the majority of emergency aid projects. In 1993  an estimated
2.1 per cent of total Irish ODA was channelled through the co-financing programme with
NGOs. An umbrella body, the Confederation of Non-Governmental Organisations for
Overseas Development (CONGOOD) was established in 1979. It draws together 18 aid and
missionary organisations. There are about 50 development related NGOs in Ireland. 
<p>
Representatives of the NGOs and the Minister or his officials hold regular meetings to
discuss matters of mutual interest, amongst others the prolongation of the one-year period
for co-financing projects and procedures for emergency aid and development education.
Two points of critique by the NGO-community are that the new strategy is less clearly
directed towards poverty alleviation than was expected and that personnel cooperation
overseas is increasingly tied up with procurement of goods and services in Ireland. Annually
a National Forum on Development Aid takes place, whose deliberations influence
development cooperation policy. 
<p>
According to the 1991 OECD/EADI survey three Irish institutes qualify as Development
Research and Training Institutes. The research community takes an active stand on
development cooperation. For instance: after the abolishment of ACDC the research
community played an active part in the installation of the new Advisory Committee.
<p>

<hr>
