<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Week in Europe</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<hr>
<H2><center><img src="../images/cce.gif"><p></a>
The Week in Europe, 7 November 1996</h2>
<h4>by <i>David Jessop</i>
<p>
Executive Director of the Caribbean Council for Europe</h4>
</center>
<hr>
<P>
Can sovereignty ever be compromised and if so are politicians alone able to
take responsibility for agreeing to such a step? In an increasingly
interdependent world this  issue and its associated questions are fast
becoming one of, if not the leading political issue in both the Caribbean
and the EU.
<p>
During the cold war, sovereignty and its protection at all costs was the
norm. Otherwise, it was argued, where would the West or the East be if
compromises led to a shift in political allegiance? It was the cement that
kept the Berlin Wall in place until the people of eastern Europe realised
that it was an issue that belonged to them not government. 
<p>
All that has been blown away by first, the ending of the cold war and its
geo-political certainties and more recently by the unstoppable process of
globalisation. Whereas in the past political parties found their politics
defined by the need to defend sovereignty, they are today, almost without
exception, struggling to define to their people their competence in a world
in which the markets take the decisions. Governments and political parties
are having now to decide whether to choose between pragmatism, whether to
take the moral high ground by arguing for the status quo or, if they are
clever, trying to redefine what sovereignty now means. 
<p>
In the Caribbean this can be seen in the varying responses to the question
of co-operation on narcotics issues with nations outside the region. In
Europe the debate focuses on the establishment of the European Monetary
System and the ever growing body of EU regulations overriding national
legislation. Internationally it is reflected in the US Congress's desire to
extend its powers to attempt to control trade by third nations with Cuba,
Libya and Iran. And less exciting, but just as potent, is the threat to
sovereignty posed by the extension of European or US reciprocal free trade
areas to many regions including the Caribbean. 
<p>
The Caribbean's most recent encounter with the question of sovereignty came
in the context of US insistence on hot pursuit of narcotics traffickers
through shiprider and other agreements which seek to allow US agencies to
operate within the jurisdiction of  Caribbean nations. Caribbean
governments took different positions on this issue. A number argued, quite
rightly, that it was one matter to allow such operations within territorial
waters through special treaty arrangements and quite another to grant such
privileges onshore. Legal experts and those concerned with consistency
argued otherwise and suggested this was a false dichotomy. But to citizens
and politicians it is a matter that reached to the heart of what government
and representative democracy were all about. 
<p>
On these questions perception matters. Citizens want the right to decide
who does what in their own country and few if any vote to allow another
state to take decisions for or act directly in their nation. That is why
sovereignty is a populist issue which cannot be dealt with lightly and
requires great sensitivity on the part of all if serious confrontations are
to be avoided.  It is not about the evil of narcotics trafficking but about
the role and existence of nation states.
<p>
The same is true in Europe as witnessed by the heated debate now underway
over the European Monetary Union (EMU). This mechanism envisaged by the
Maastricht Treaty is meant to create a single EU currency from 1998 onwards
. It has the capacity to split Europe. Already nations such as Britain,
Italy and Greece that are unlikely to meet the convergence criteria, unless
they like France massage their figures, are growing increasingly angry and
concerned at a number of levels. Criticism runs from technical arguments by
bankers through to a sentimental attachment to, for instance, the pound
sterling. But most potent of all is the arguments comes from those who see
EMU as a threat to sovereignty. They argue that individual states should
not give control of economic decisions over questions such as base rates
and money supply to the stronger economies in Europe. Such decisions they
suggest are what makes a state sovereign.
<p>
The issue of  the exercise of sovereignty is also becoming more complex as
evidenced by the acrimonious debate between the EU, the US and the
Caribbean over the US Helms/Burton legislation on Cuba. First the US
Congress sought to impose its will on the world at large, then the EU
agreed to retaliate and in the week past, the US and EU have begun to
attempt to find common ground on Cuba over measures that they hope might
encourage democracy and the growth of civic society there. Forgotten in all
of this is Cuba's intense nationalism, the fact that its revolution was
based on the people's desire to see a re-assertion of sovereignty against
the US and the subsequent guiding principle that sovereignty can never be
compromised.
<p>
Less likely to engender such political passion as yet, is the desire to
establish over time free trade areas (FTAs) with the hemisphere by the
United States and the EU, if it decides to extend its thinking after the
year 2000 about FTAs for Latin America to the Caribbean. As these ideas are
taken forward the Caribbean is likely to find itself standing at a
metaphorical cross-roads in the debate about sovereignty as both the US and
EU FTA processes will, over time, require reciprocity. Unlike Brazil where
its size and economic and political muscle will continue to determine its
freedom of action, Caribbean islands may find that reciprocity eventually
removes from government the ability to determine many aspects of economic
policy. 
<p>
All of this is not to suggest that the free trade process, the structure of
the post war world or globalisation can in some way be changed or ignored
but that Caribbean solutions will have to be found that seek to redefine
and educate the people about the new nature of sovereignty and by extension
government's role.
<p>
The danger is that if in parallel to the many other complex issues that the
region has to consider this component is not fully debated, governments may
loose touch with popular sentiment. A lack of clarity may also lead outside
of the region to the assumption that wholly unacceptable solutions such as
that proposed by US ex Assistant Secretary of State, Eliot Abrams, may be a
viable way forward. In his little read but often talked about paper "The 
Shiprider Solution" he suggested in part that the US take charge of 
defence and foreign policy in smaller Caribbean States in return for
guarantees of aid. This profoundly undemocratic thought, which challenges
every concept of sovereignty, rightly brought indignation in the Caribbean.
But what the anger also showed was a sense of uncertainty about the future.
<p>
As in Europe, there is a pressing need in the Caribbean to debate how
nation states,  particularly those that are small, define and retain
sovereignty now that open economies and trade advantage, rather than
political ideology, have come to dominate the global agenda. 
<p>
<HR>
