<html><head><title>ODA School Section</title><!!keys: ODA ></head><body><center><img src="oda_pix/oda_schools2.gif"></center><br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="oda_info.html">  Overseas Development Administration</i></a><hr><center><h2>BRITISH NURSE ADOPTS STRICT DRESS CODE</h2></center>Most nurses put on a simple knee length dress or pair of trousers when theygo to work. British nurse Rachael Tapsell covered herself from head to footin a heavy veil when she went to help women and children in the Kandaharprovince of south-west Afghanistan, desperately poor after years of civilwar.The province,once a dangerous no-go zone,had just switched to strictIslamic control.<p>One of the new religious rules stated that women had to swathethemselves in full-length veils,know as <i>burqas. &nbsp;</i>If Rachael wanted to workin the hospitals and clinics,she would have to wear a burqa too.<p><i>"Wearing the burqa was an extraordinary experience"&nbsp;</i>,says Rachael. <i>"I'musually confident,vocal and happy but I sometimes felt withdrawn andisolated. If felt if I shouted people wouldn't hear"&nbsp;</i>.<p>Rachael was in Afghanistan with MERLIN,a British charity that sendsdoctors,nurses and supplies to war zones and disaster areas. As medical co-ordinator,it was her job to set up district clinics and supply much-neededmedicines to the area. Years of civil war had left the province's hospitalsbadly damaged and run down. <p>Getting Rachael into Afghanistan was hard work. There were no otherWestern women in the country at that time,and Rachael and her maleMERLIN colleagues needed all their powers of persuasion in their talks withthe religious leaders,the <i>mullahs. &nbsp;</i><p><i>"At first the authorities were very sceptical and cautious"&nbsp;</i>, remembersRachael.<i>"We explained that we wanted to run a woman and child healthprogramme, and that we wanted a Western female nurse, otherwise wewouldn't set up the programme. Fortunately, they agreed.&nbsp;</i><p>Gradually, things got easier. Rachael and her colleagues began setting uptheir programme and the religious leaders relaxed some of their rules.That meant that women could leave their homes to go shopping andRachael no longer had to wear the veil all the time. Life was still hard,though. Taking time off was tricky, partly because they were living in oneof the most heavily mined areas of Afghanistan.<p><i>"We played volleyball in the compound, but because of the landmines weseldom went for a walk on our own in the town or countryside"&nbsp;</i>, saysRachael.<i> "Work becomes your real focus, because there's so little else todo".&nbsp;</i><p>Keeping away from minefields is a long way from Rachael's early days asa nurse. After training as a registered general nurse in Canterbury Hospital,Kent, she went to St Thomas's Hospital in London for a two-year stint onthe wards. <i>"I realised then I wasn't a career nurse"&nbsp;</i>,she says. <i>"I wanted totravel".&nbsp;</i><p>A brief spell in West Africa and as a volunteer on an aid convoy to Bosniaconfirmed her dream. <i>"I was sitting at home with my family on ChristmasEve and I was watching the news about the horrors in Bosnia. I wanted todo something and I also wanted to see if I could cope with the work".&nbsp;</i>Rachael went - and loved it. <i>"It was an exciting opportunity: I was bittenby the bug"&nbsp;</i>.<a name="education"></a><p><hr><p><center><img border=1 src="oda_pix/education.gif"></center><p><li>Ghana is the focus of three new publications for key stage three pupilsproduced by the Development Education Centre in Birmingham.<p><i>Land and Life, &nbsp;</i>£4.95 plus £1 p&p, shows how people adapt to change,whether on a farm, in a mine or in a forest. <p><i> Kumasi and Beyond, &nbsp;</i>£4.95,covers the vibrancy of town life, with its flourishing informal economy. Both publications, written by British teachers after a DEC study visit toGhana, include case studies and personal histories.<p>  <i>Issues and enquiry, &nbsp;</i>£12.00, plus £1.20 VAT and £2.40 p&p, offers adviceand resources for teaches and a photo-pack for classroom use.  To order,contact the Development Education Centre, Gillett Centre, 998 Bristol Road,Selly Oak, Birmingham B29 6LE.  Tel 0121 472 3255.<p><li>September 16 sees the start of UNICEF week, when thousands ofvolunteers and supporters will raise funds for Vitamin A programmes aroundthe world.  Events range from a UNICEF weekend in Wiltshire to `Share aMeal' events, where guests bring a donation rather than wine or flowers.<br>UNICEF is supporting national programmes to prevent Vitamin A deficiency,which can lead to blindness, in the developing world.  UNICEF week postersand information sheets are available from UNICEF (UK) regional offices orfrom UNICEF (UK) headquarters at 55 Lincoln's In Fields, London WC2A3BN.<p><li>Schools considering setting up education links with schools in developingcountries can find out more by watching the <i>Linking Across the WorldVideo.&nbsp;</i><br>Produced by the International Broadcasting Trust and the BBC, the videolooks at ways that schools can set up links from letters and computer linksto exchange visits.<br>The video, which costs £18 including p&p and VAT, is available fromYorkshire International Thompson Multimedia, 104 Kirkstall Road, LeedsLS3 1JU, or the Development Education Dispatch Unit, 153 Cardigan Road,Leeds LS6 1LJ, whch offers bulk order discounts.<p><p><hr>©Copyright: Oda 1995<hr><p><center><TABLE BORDER=5><TR><TD><a href="oda_info.html"><img border=0 src="oda_pix/oda_logo2.gif"></a></TD><TH><a href="index.html"> ODA Home Page</a></TH><TH><a href="ssch_schools.html">School Section</a></TH></TR></TABLE></center><p></body></html>
