<head>
<title>Commonwealth Foundation - Literary Award</title>
<!!keys: The Commonwealth Foundation>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#oooooo" link="#A62a2a" vlink="#5c4033">
<img align=left src="comm_pix/comm_logo.gif"><img align=right src="comm_pix/writers_logo.gif"><br
clear=all><p>

<br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="info.html">The Commonwealth
Foundation  </i></a>
<hr>

<h1 align=center>Foundation launches second literary award</h1>


Next year you should listen for the award-winning Commonwealth short stories being
broadcast on your national radio station.  And if you are a writer, established or aspiring,
please send in your story now - you could win £2,000!<p>


The Commonwealth Foundation, in collaboration with the Commonwealth Broadcasting
Association (CBA), is launching a new Commonwealth Short Story Competition in 1996.  
National radio stations are currently soliciting entries of original five-minute short stories,
which will be initially screened by the CBA.  Then a small international panel of three judges
will meet in London in April 1996 to make the final selection.  They will choose one overall
winner, three regional winners and 22 commended writers.  The recordings of the 26 winning
stories will be available for free distribution to all radio stations in the Commonwealth.<p>


The Foundation and the CBA are delighted to be co-operating on this new joint project.  If
successful, the Commonwealth Short Story Competition could become a companion award to
the Commonwealth Writers Prize.  It will be another exciting means of celebrating the
richness of the English language which is the main common bond of the Commonwealth.<ul>


<b>Prizes:</b><p>
First prize:  £2,000<br>
Three regional prizes:  £500 each<br>
Twenty-two commended writers:  £100 each<p>

<b>For further details and rules of entry contact: </b> <br>
CBA, <br>
BBC Yalding House, <br>
152 Great Portland Street, <br>
London  W1N 6AJ, UK</ul><p>


<h3>Commonwealth Writers Prize 1995</h3><img align=right width=200 height=193 hspace=10 vspace=10
border=1 src="comm_pix/louis_bernieres.jpg">

Third time really was lucky for Louis de Bernieres, winner of the £10,000 Commonwealth
Writers Prize in 1995 and the first British novelist to take the award.  Two of his previous
books had been shortlisted for the Prize, but this year his novel, Captain Corelli's Mandolin,
won universal acclaim from the judges as a major contribution to the literature of war.  Set on
an occupied Greek island during the Second World War, it has a large and colourful cast of
characters who are protrayed both comically and tragically.  The international panel of judges
were dazzled by its energy, humanity and humour.<p>


The £3,000 prize for the best first published book was awarded to Adib Khan, a writer of
Bangladeshi origin now settled in Australia, for his novel Seasonal Adjustments.<p>


Louis de Bernieres was granted the customary audience with H M the Queen on 26 October
and afterwards the Foundation hosted a champagne reception for him in London.  To his great
disappointment he had been unable to attend the gala awards dinner in Harare, but he sent a
statement to be read on that occasion.
Here is an extract from his testimony to the Commonwealth Writers Prize:<p>
<ul>

<i>I am deeply honoured to be on the Commonwealth Writers Prize List, because I believe in the
Commonwealth and I believe in the Commonwealth Writers Prize.  The Commonwealth is a
splendid and improbable institution.  Never before has an empire been dissolved, with the
formerly subject nations choosing to remain fraternal both with each other and with the
former colonisers.  This is a perfectly unique phenomenon, and I am not even sure that it is
explicable.  To the modern mind the whole concept of empire seems both immoral and
pointless, and yet here we are, united by forgiveness, mutual affection, fraternity, and the
strange compromises and accommodations of a shared history.  We have picked up each
others' cuisine, habits and customs, and the English language has greedily nourished itself by
appropriating words and idioms from the hundreds of Commonwealth tongues.  We have
enough in common to be friends who understand each other, and enough diversity to keep us
mutually interesting.<p>


This diversity is the reason for the special status of the Commonwealth Writers Prize...  This
prize is judged by intellectuals, academics, and serious booklovers from all around the world,
from dozens of different cultures and traditions.  Thankfully these judges are uninfluenced by
the bizarre and fatuous literary fashions that are the curse of Europe, and therefore to be
chosen for the shortlist must mean that a writer has managed to come up with something
quintessential, something that transcends cultural differences and resonates in the universal
human heart.  To be on the shortlist is to be reassured that one has written a real book, and
there is truly no other prize of which this can be so confidently said.  Long may it prosper,
and my congratulations go to all of my fellow prizewinners.  To all those in the
Commonwealth who are writing in English even though it is their second or third language, I
wish to offer my special thanks.  I know that there is much heated debate about whether one
should rather write in one's mother tongue, but I am very selfishly grateful that so many do in
fact write in English; to these I say thank you for enriching and extending my language, thank
you for making your world accessible to me, and thank you for being the ones who keep the
flame alight.</i></ul><p>


<h4>Tribute to Ken Saro-Wiwa: <br>
former regional winner of the Commonwealth Writers Prize</h4>

Ken Saro-Wiwa, besides being a courageous campaigner for the rights of his people, was one
of the first two regional winners of the Commonwealth Writers Prize in Africa for his
collection of short stories, A Forest of Flowers.  Ironically, it was because the flowers were
withering in Ogoniland, killed off by the pollution from the oil rigs and the neglect of the
government, that Ken Saro-Wiwa, a committed nationalist, took up the cudgels on behalf of
the Ogoni people.<p>


In a moving plea for Ken Saro-Wiwa's life, shortly after his friend had been sentenced to
death, another Nigerian writer (and coincidentally the other winner of the regional award for
Africa in the Commonwealth Writers Prize 1987), Ben Okri, argued that writers are the
barometers of a nation's health.  Ken Saro-Wiwa himself, in the final television interview he
gave before being imprisoned, explained that African writers had no time to deal with
personal angst.  They had to tackle the burning issues of the day, they had to be combative.<p>


Alas, Ken Saro-Wiwa's fighting spirit led him to an untimely grave and his execution, along
with eight Ogoni colleagues, and contributed towards the two-year suspension of Nigeria
from the Commonwealth. 

<p>

