<html>
<header>
<title>Development Cooperation and Policy in Europe</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H2><center><img src="../images/eu.jpg"><p></a>
EU Council of Development Ministers<br>
Report from Meeting of May 1996</h2>
<h4>Source: <i>Liaison News</i>, No. 18, June 1996</h4>
<hr>
<A HREF = "../index.htm#top">EUFORIC
Home Page</a>
<p>
</center>
<A HREF = "cl96m_fr.htm"><IMG ALIGN=TOP SRC  =
"../images/fr.gif"></a> Cette page est aussi disponible en fran&#231;ais
<p><hr><p>
The Development Council convening in Brussels this Tuesday under
the Presidency of Mr Rino Serri, Italian Secretary of State for
Foreign Affairs, made smooth progress on the four texts aimed
at providing a legal base for important areas of intervention
of EU cooperation policy with the Third World. The Council formally
adopted at second reading the regulation on humanitarian aid and
approved at first reading its &quot;common positions&quot; on
the 3 regulations from Latin American and Asian LDCs&quot;, &quot;fight
against aids&quot; and &quot;environment and sustainable development&quot;.
For these three items, the UK delegation did not bring into play
its reserve in principle, arguing that the qualified majority
applied (in reality, unanimity was required, the Council having
amended the Commission proposal on the controversial item of comitology,
without its agreement).
<P>
The Council debated with positive results all the other items
on its agenda but was unable to formally adopt the resolutions
or conclusions anticipated because of the opposition from the
UK. Formal adoption will take place without debate at a forthcoming
Council as soon as the United Kingdom makes it possible.
<P>
<h3>Detailed minutes of the results of the Council:</h3>
<P>
In the light of the attitude of principle shown by the United
Kingdom on the various points on the agenda, the Council for Development
Cooperation reached the conclusions outlined below on the different
points on the agenda.
<P>
<B>1. Humanitarian aid.</B> The Council approved, in principle,
the regulation that will provide a legal base for the activities
of ECHO (Community Humanitarian Aid Office) which have developed
to a very large extent (about MECU 750 in 1995). This regulation
assigns clear objectives and general criteria for humanitarian
aid by defining the types of intervention and the links between
humanitarian aid and the preparation for disasters, rehabilitation
and reconstruction. It also sets the procedures for implementation
of humanitarian actions conducted in cooperation with NGOs and
aid programmes financed by the Community. The formal adoption
of the regulation will come about once the text bas been finalised.
<P>
<B>2. Aid to LDCALA refugees, the fight against AIDS in LDC, environmental
protection in the context of sustainable development</B>: the
Council approved its common positions on each of these three regulations.
The political agreement on the tricky question of comitology (which
determines the degree of decision-making autonomy on the part
of the Commission) was reached on the basis of a Presidency compromise,
that the Commission does not accept.
<P>
<B>3. Links between emergency aid, aid to rehabilitation and long-term
development</B>: the Council held an in-depth debate and a broad
consensus was reached on the need for a link between these three
aspects of development aid which presupposes, above all, that
NGOs be involved in development action, even beyond emergency
situations. Conclusions were not adopted for the reasons indicated.
<P>
We give below the content of the draft conclusions, given in the
press release by the Council although they are not officially
adopted:
<P>
a) the EU subscribes to the idea that the strengthening of links
between emergency aid, rehabilitation and development must take
place gradually according to the system proposed by the Commission;
<P>
b) the Commission will elaborate, with Members States concerned,
frameworks for global policy for a certain number of countries
or regions - mainly those that may be exposed to political or
economic risks and to tensions or natural disasters, and will
define more clearly the concrete means for strengthening links
between emergency aid, rehabilitation and development.
<P>
c) In the light of the first experience gained in the matter,
the Development Council will proceed to a new exchange of views
during its next sitting (November 1996) which will result in the
adoption of a resolution and the establishment of detailed guidelines.
<P>
The Commission has listed 12 countries that may be covered by
the first exercise: Angola, Liberia, Haiti, Somalia, Great Lake
Countries, Guatemala, Salvador, Cambodia, Afghanistan, Georgia,
Armenia, Azerbaijan.
<P>
<B>4. Environmental impact assessment of development projects
and programmes</B>: the Council held a political discussion on
this subject but did not adopt a resolution. The ministers stressed
the need to take into account the environment factor in every
decision or implementation of policies, programmes or development
projects and to have more systematic recourse to assessment of
environmental impact before giving formal approval of projects.
<P>
<B>5. Follow-up to Horizon 2000 resolution</B>: in the context
of follow-up to the declaration &quot;development cooperation
on Horizon 2000&quot;, the Council discussed: a) operation coordination
in the light of experience gained on the ground, without adopting
conclusions, still because of British reservation; b) coherence
between development policy and the other Community policies at
the request of the Danish delegation.
<P>
<B>6. Decentralised cooperation</B>: the Council held a discussion
and will approve conclusions as soon as possible.
<P>
<B>7. Migration and development</B>: the Council discussed the
links between certain forms of assistance to poor countries and
the increase in migratory flows, Conclusions were not adopted.
<P>
<B>8. Conflict prevention in Africa</B>: on the basis of the Commission
communication, presented to the ministers by Commissioner Pinheiro,
the Council showed itself to be largely in favour of the Commission's
approach that recommends an overall and voluntarist one which
that integrates early prevention of violent conflicts in the EU's
policy for development cooperation.
<P>
<HR>
