<html><head><title>Poland: Catholic backlash </title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><img align=left hspace=3 src="ippf_pix/ippf_logo.gif"><h3>International<br>Planned<br>Parenthood<br>Federation</h3><i>The material that follows has been provided by <a href="ippf_info.html">IPPF</a></i><br clear=left><hr><h1>Poland: Catholic backlash</h1><b>by Wanda Novicka</b><p>There have been a lot of changes in Poland since 1989 when communism finally collapsed.  The transition has affected all segments of the society at all levels of public and private life, but women's reproductive rights have been particularly affected.<p>When in the late 1980s some anti-choice forces started challenging legal abortion nobody believed that the abortion law could ever be overturned. It finally happened, though, in 1993 and seems to be lasting, although society, frightened by right-wing forces and their performance, have returned to the post-communists, electing them again to Parliament in 1992 for the first time in free elections.<p>It is certain that the post-communists will not meet the expectations of those who voted for them that they will oppose the right-wing forces supported strongly by the Roman Catholic Church. On the contrary, post-communists busy with strengthening their newly regained political and economic acquisitions will allow right-wing forces to strengthen their gains in social matters, particularly those which concern women and the youth.<p>Among these gains was Roman-Catholic influence on education at state schools since 1990 which goes much further than just religious teaching, and of course restrictions to abortion, which had been legal in Poland since 1956.  The anti-abortion law has already resulted in tragedies for women and their families and doctors.  Women are forced to make difficult choices either to seek illegal and sometimes unsafe abortion or to give birth to an unwanted child.  Women with serious health problems are forced to have a baby, and even those who have the right to legal abortion under the present law are often denied it.<p>There have been suicides resulting from unwanted pregnancy or from performing illegal abortion: a woman gynaecologist who performed an abortion in 1994 had to take the woman patient to hospital because problems had arisen, and then committed suicide because she expected criminal charges to be brought against her. Several women committed suicide as a result of unwanted pregnancy.<p>But this law has unexpectedly had some tragicomic effects such as the serious threat of closing a private clinic performing in vitro fertilization.  The need to freeze embryos resulted in a statement made by a Commission of Medical Ethics that it violates the anti-abortion law (officially called the Law on family planning, protection of the human embryo and conditions of admittance of abortion), and an investigation is in process. And the head of a school board issued a rule that embryos and other anatomical specimens cannot serve as educational models in schools, because they also violate the anti-abortion law.<p>As for young people, they are exposed to strange school textbooks on sexual education.  In one such book sexuality is described in symbolic language.  A girl is called "a closed garden, a sealed source".  The source will be unsealed after marriage.  In one chapter, "The secret of a girl and a boy", the names of human sexual organs are not mentioned, but described like this: "The source of life of a woman is located in lower part of her body, inside the body (...).  The source of life of a man is partially outside".  This is how sex education is taught by those teachers who have chosen this manual distributed by the Ministry of Education.<p>Family planning, which has never been popular in Catholic Poland, has been becoming an object of moral dilemma in the society. But it is not surprising in a country where there are doctors who instead of prescribing contraception make lectures to their patients on the Roman Catholic Church teaching on contraception and try to convince women that contraception is the same as abortion.  Some books on women's health only mention natural methods in chapters on family planning.<p>I hope that one day I will be laughing at such stupidities and other ones as the hangover from the never-returning past.  But for the time being these prospects are very distant.<p><hr width=60%><i>Wanda Nowicka is Executive Director of the Polish Federation for Women and Family Planning.</i><p> <hr><p>©Copyright IPPF 1995.<hr><img src="ippf_pix/ippf_logo2.gif"> <a href="index.html">IPPF Home Page</a><hr></body></html>
